All right,

00:02:26.635 --> 00:02:28.308
let's get into Tokyo.

00:02:28.609 --> 00:02:28.729
So,

00:02:29.851 --> 00:02:31.314
Tokyo is,

00:02:33.799 --> 00:02:34.561
on the face of it,

00:02:34.922 --> 00:02:37.908
what it does is it takes things that implement the future trait.

00:02:38.949 --> 00:02:39.070
So,

00:02:39.453 --> 00:02:41.288
if we pull up the future trait here.

00:02:42.892 --> 00:02:50.988
It is just the thing that takes things that implement this future trait and then returns the thing that is in the associated output type.

00:02:51.410 --> 00:02:54.325
That is all Tokyo kind of really does,

00:02:54.787 --> 00:02:54.948
right?

00:02:55.229 --> 00:03:00.508
It runs these futures and produces the output that that future represents the computation of.

00:03:02.235 --> 00:03:02.938
In practice,

00:03:02.958 --> 00:03:05.488
there's a lot that goes into that kind of machinery.

00:03:06.230 --> 00:03:07.174
And so when we go into Tokyo,

00:03:07.334 --> 00:03:11.408
I'm really going to sort of split this roughly into four parts.

00:03:11.829 --> 00:03:13.302
Let's see if it actually ends up being four,

00:03:13.322 --> 00:03:13.968
but roughly four.

00:03:14.691 --> 00:03:16.063
The first is about Tokyo,

00:03:16.123 --> 00:03:16.628
the runtime.

00:03:16.828 --> 00:03:17.191
Like basically,

00:03:17.474 --> 00:03:19.068
how does it execute futures?

00:03:20.769 --> 00:03:24.359
Here we're going to talk about things like worker threads and the thread pool,

00:03:24.841 --> 00:03:25.803
work stealing,

00:03:26.004 --> 00:03:26.726
blocking,

00:03:26.966 --> 00:03:27.508
shutdown.

00:03:28.996 --> 00:03:29.479
The sort of...

00:03:29.964 --> 00:03:31.649
inner workings of the scheduler,

00:03:31.769 --> 00:03:33.214
although not at the very,

00:03:33.294 --> 00:03:34.036
very lowest level,

00:03:34.337 --> 00:03:37.128
but enough that you sort of understand how the pieces fit together.

00:03:38.414 --> 00:03:40.422
The second thing we're going to talk about is resources.

00:03:41.124 --> 00:03:44.031
So this is anything that has to do with IO,

00:03:44.833 --> 00:03:48.463
anything that has to do with threading processes,

00:03:48.523 --> 00:03:49.606
the file system,

00:03:50.549 --> 00:03:51.692
timers as well.

00:03:52.233 --> 00:03:56.760
So all of the things that a future might use in order to interact with the outside world.

00:03:58.676 --> 00:04:00.143
Then we're going to talk about utilities.

00:04:01.168 --> 00:04:08.766
So this is more about what additional useful features Tokyo provides you with,

00:04:09.367 --> 00:04:12.377
both in the crate itself and in slightly adjacent crates,

00:04:12.819 --> 00:04:16.651
for things like coordination and synchronization between futures,

00:04:17.252 --> 00:04:18.936
handling multiple tasks,

00:04:19.618 --> 00:04:26.706
things like the select macro for allowing whichever one of these futures finishes first.

00:04:27.151 --> 00:04:29.177
So you can run multiple of them concurrently,

00:04:30.380 --> 00:04:37.468
as well as things like the sort of Tokyo util crate we'll touch on a little bit on bridging between async read and async write,

00:04:37.468 --> 00:04:38.251
which we'll talk about,

00:04:38.733 --> 00:04:39.597
and sync and stream,

00:04:39.677 --> 00:04:40.681
which we'll talk less about,

00:04:41.625 --> 00:04:42.635
and various other things like that.

00:04:43.268 --> 00:04:48.815
And then the fourth part is going to be talking about common complications when working with Tokyo.

00:04:49.548 --> 00:04:52.644
And I don't mean that as in bugs with Tokyo itself.

00:04:53.388 --> 00:04:54.579
I mean that as in...

00:04:56.867 --> 00:05:05.678
sort of things that are easy to shoot yourself in the foot with if you don't realize exactly how something works or the caveats that comes with something,

00:05:05.698 --> 00:05:07.223
the trade-offs that are involved with something.

00:05:07.945 --> 00:05:10.290
And so we'll talk through some common ones of those.

00:05:13.879 --> 00:05:15.302
That is...

00:05:18.551 --> 00:05:19.862
That's sort of the rough outline here.

00:05:19.882 --> 00:05:22.662
So let's start with how Tokyo works as a runtime.

00:05:23.702 --> 00:05:24.345
So in

00:05:24.888 --> 00:05:26.496
Tokyo, first of all,

00:05:26.496 --> 00:05:27.622
the documentation is quite good.

00:05:27.722 --> 00:05:29.369
Like I do recommend that in general,

00:05:29.852 --> 00:05:32.202
spend the time to read through the Tokyo docs.

00:05:33.165 --> 00:05:36.722
They do talk about a lot of the things that I'm going to be talking about here.

00:05:37.203 --> 00:05:40.242
It's just that you have to remember to read them in order to realize these things.

00:05:40.965 --> 00:05:42.782
There's a lot of really good documentation in there.

00:05:43.930 --> 00:05:45.055
So in Tokyo,

00:05:45.095 --> 00:05:47.806
there's a bunch of sub-modules and one of them is runtime.

00:05:47.846 --> 00:05:50.439
And the runtime is sort of the main,

00:05:50.520 --> 00:05:51.565
the heart of Tokyo,

00:05:51.565 --> 00:05:51.806
if you will.

00:05:52.067 --> 00:05:57.204
It is the thing that you give futures to and it gives you back the thing that the future computes.

00:05:58.869 --> 00:06:00.353
And at its core,

00:06:01.497 --> 00:06:02.580
the runtime,

00:06:02.600 --> 00:06:03.923
it says this at the top here,

00:06:03.923 --> 00:06:04.806
it has an IO event loop.

00:06:05.048 --> 00:06:06.578
This gets back to things like resources,

00:06:06.618 --> 00:06:07.725
which we'll talk about later,

00:06:08.771 --> 00:06:09.193
timers,

00:06:09.253 --> 00:06:10.218
which we'll also talk about later,

00:06:10.741 --> 00:06:11.685
and then a scheduler.

00:06:12.029 --> 00:06:15.017
And the scheduler's job is to take futures that come in,

00:06:15.438 --> 00:06:18.186
call the pull method on that future.

00:06:18.386 --> 00:06:18.747
So remember,

00:06:18.967 --> 00:06:21.812
futures are these things that implement the future trait,

00:06:22.193 --> 00:06:29.646
where async blocks and async functions are examples of things that automatically the compiler turns into things that implement the future trait.

00:06:31.281 --> 00:06:35.133
The scheduler is going to pick a future that hasn't completed yet,

00:06:35.514 --> 00:06:36.758
call its poll method.

00:06:37.500 --> 00:06:39.438
The poll method just executes like a normal function.

00:06:39.719 --> 00:06:40.506
And at some point,

00:06:40.527 --> 00:06:41.698
the poll function returns.

00:06:42.544 --> 00:06:44.277
And if we look at what it looks like.

00:06:46.215 --> 00:06:51.468
The return value of pull is this pull type that is either ready,

00:06:51.609 --> 00:06:52.813
which means the future has finished,

00:06:52.813 --> 00:06:53.918
it doesn't need to be run anymore,

00:06:54.239 --> 00:06:58.538
and that includes then the return value of that asynchronous task,

00:06:58.979 --> 00:06:59.501
or pending,

00:06:59.542 --> 00:07:00.927
which means I didn't finish,

00:07:01.027 --> 00:07:01.823
there's more work to do.

00:07:03.091 --> 00:07:06.220
And when a future returns ready,

00:07:06.862 --> 00:07:07.043
then

00:07:07.725 --> 00:07:09.350
Tokyo doesn't really do anything more with it.

00:07:10.109 --> 00:07:13.354
Depending on how you gave the task to Tokyo in the first place,

00:07:13.735 --> 00:07:14.937
it's either going to give you that T,

00:07:15.378 --> 00:07:17.481
or that T is sort of going to be dropped into the ether,

00:07:17.662 --> 00:07:20.046
usually because it's just units and no one cares about it anyway.

00:07:20.747 --> 00:07:23.811
But when a future returns pending from poll,

00:07:24.492 --> 00:07:30.080
what happens is that that future gets sort of put back into the runtime to be executed again,

00:07:30.381 --> 00:07:33.866
like for poll to be called again at some later point in time.

00:07:34.588 --> 00:07:38.006
And we'll talk about how that mechanism works in a little bit more detail.

00:07:39.050 --> 00:07:39.171
So,

00:07:39.171 --> 00:07:42.302
the scheduler part is the first thing we're going to talk about.

00:07:43.326 --> 00:07:44.962
There are two schedulers in Tokyo.

00:07:45.406 --> 00:07:48.603
There is a multi-threaded scheduler and there's the current thread scheduler.

00:07:49.126 --> 00:07:51.395
For almost all use cases,

00:07:51.516 --> 00:07:53.363
you want to use the multi-thread scheduler.

00:07:54.146 --> 00:07:56.994
The multi-thread scheduler creates,

00:07:57.335 --> 00:07:58.378
by default at least,

00:07:58.839 --> 00:07:59.862
one thread,

00:07:59.963 --> 00:08:04.163
one operating system thread for every CPU core that you have.

00:08:04.706 --> 00:08:07.146
And the idea here is that the different worker threads

00:08:07.486 --> 00:08:12.162
can be sort of in the process of calling pull on different futures at the same time.

00:08:12.483 --> 00:08:23.862
And so that way you get to have actual parallelism where these different futures are executing in parallel with each other so that you get to use the CPU resources of your machine.

00:08:24.223 --> 00:08:24.866
As opposed to,

00:08:24.866 --> 00:08:25.328
for example,

00:08:25.348 --> 00:08:31.802
just switching back and forth between them quickly on a single core where you wouldn't really get the parallelism but you get the perception of concurrency.

00:08:33.863 --> 00:08:36.871
The multi-threaded scheduler is configurable,

00:08:36.891 --> 00:08:39.378
so you can choose how many threads you actually want,

00:08:39.679 --> 00:08:40.541
but in general,

00:08:40.601 --> 00:08:44.392
having one per CPU core is usually the right choice.

00:08:45.355 --> 00:08:48.567
There are some caveats to that when it comes to blocking threads that we'll talk to in a second.

00:08:49.992 --> 00:08:51.840
When you have the multi-threaded scheduler,

00:08:52.301 --> 00:08:52.562
actually,

00:08:52.582 --> 00:08:57.201
I'll talk about the current scheduler first before I dive into either of these in more detail.

00:08:57.723 --> 00:09:00.958
The current thread scheduler does not start any threads.

00:09:01.691 --> 00:09:02.635
Instead what it does,

00:09:02.655 --> 00:09:04.141
like it doesn't start one thread per core,

00:09:04.141 --> 00:09:05.266
it doesn't even start one thread,

00:09:05.567 --> 00:09:06.169
it just uses,

00:09:06.289 --> 00:09:07.292
as its name implies,

00:09:07.573 --> 00:09:08.657
the current thread.

00:09:09.199 --> 00:09:13.492
And it starts up a Tokyo runtime on the current thread that is able to,

00:09:13.713 --> 00:09:19.410
that has this sort of IO integration and this little queue for which things haven't been run,

00:09:19.490 --> 00:09:20.454
which things can be run.

00:09:21.578 --> 00:09:24.129
And it just stores all of that locally on the current thread.

00:09:24.511 --> 00:09:27.306
It executes some future that you give it and ultimately...

00:09:29.578 --> 00:09:39.611
blocks the current thread until that work is done and only uses sort of CPU cycles on the current thread and nowhere else in order to drive those futures to completion.

00:09:42.685 --> 00:09:45.194
We can talk about how these work internally,

00:09:45.234 --> 00:09:46.399
and that might be a little bit interesting.

00:09:46.840 --> 00:09:47.845
But before we do that,

00:09:47.885 --> 00:09:50.339
I want to show you what this interface actually looks like.

00:09:50.740 --> 00:09:52.866
So if you have a runtime,

00:09:53.106 --> 00:09:54.530
and this is the same type,

00:09:54.610 --> 00:09:57.759
whether it's configured as a current thread runtime or a multi-threaded runtime.

00:09:59.604 --> 00:10:00.838
I wish this was default view.

00:10:02.220 --> 00:10:03.244
When you have a runtime,

00:10:03.685 --> 00:10:05.351
you have this method called spawn,

00:10:05.452 --> 00:10:07.138
which we're going to ignore for right now.

00:10:08.126 --> 00:10:10.239
And then you have this method called block on.

00:10:10.661 --> 00:10:15.219
And block on is the most straightforward interface to a runtime.

00:10:15.600 --> 00:10:17.739
It is also not the one you're going to use most commonly,

00:10:18.159 --> 00:10:21.279
but it is the sort of most straightforward.

00:10:23.580 --> 00:10:24.787
interface into a runtime.

00:10:25.289 --> 00:10:30.107
It takes a future that implements the future trait and it returns the output of that future.

00:10:30.850 --> 00:10:31.337
That is all,

00:10:31.459 --> 00:10:31.642
right?

00:10:32.047 --> 00:10:33.607
So if you create a current thread runtime,

00:10:34.048 --> 00:10:36.047
you pass it some future to block on,

00:10:36.448 --> 00:10:43.927
then it will do all the stuff that's needed behind the scene until that future ultimately returns the ready variant of the pull enum.

00:10:44.612 --> 00:10:46.626
And then it's going to extract the value and give that back to you.

00:10:47.208 --> 00:10:48.716
If you have the current thread runtime,

00:10:48.997 --> 00:10:49.520
at that point,

00:10:49.520 --> 00:10:50.947
the runtime doesn't do anything more,

00:10:51.227 --> 00:10:51.388
right?

00:10:51.428 --> 00:10:52.898
Because it does not spawn any threads,

00:10:52.918 --> 00:10:54.287
it doesn't do anything in the background.

00:10:54.707 --> 00:10:56.233
So the moment block on returns,

00:10:56.514 --> 00:10:59.265
the current thread is now under your control again.

00:10:59.606 --> 00:11:05.104
And there's no way for Tokyo to run any more logic because you're not in Tokyo anymore.

00:11:05.405 --> 00:11:11.007
This function has returned and whatever is in the sort of calling code is what's going to happen next.

00:11:12.512 --> 00:11:12.633
Um,

00:11:12.773 --> 00:11:12.893
and,

00:11:12.934 --> 00:11:14.178
and this talks about a little bit,

00:11:14.358 --> 00:11:14.760
uh,

00:11:14.760 --> 00:11:14.900
what,

00:11:14.981 --> 00:11:15.944
what that actually means.

00:11:16.145 --> 00:11:16.285
Um,

00:11:17.862 --> 00:11:24.719
So BlockCon is sort of the main interface here to Tokyo for turning futures into their outputs.

00:11:26.381 --> 00:11:28.525
In the multi-threaded scheduler,

00:11:29.748 --> 00:11:31.713
and actually in the current thread scheduler,

00:11:32.635 --> 00:11:34.459
you can call spawn.

00:11:34.982 --> 00:11:37.699
And what spawn does is it takes a future.

00:11:39.834 --> 00:11:45.231
and it puts it onto the sort of queue of futures.

00:11:46.235 --> 00:11:46.579
In fact,

00:11:46.781 --> 00:11:47.651
the queue of tasks,

00:11:47.711 --> 00:11:49.651
and I'll talk about the distinction between those in a second.

00:11:50.052 --> 00:11:55.211
It puts the future that you give onto the queue of tasks for the current runtime,

00:11:56.174 --> 00:11:59.511
regardless of whether that's a current thread runtime or a multi-threaded runtime,

00:12:00.576 --> 00:12:01.891
but it doesn't execute anything.

00:12:02.011 --> 00:12:04.611
It just sort of puts it on the queue and then returns,

00:12:05.053 --> 00:12:06.471
and it returns you a join handle.

00:12:06.552 --> 00:12:08.351
So this is sort of similar to if you use,

00:12:08.803 --> 00:12:09.051
you know,

00:12:09.213 --> 00:12:10.075
Threadspawn.

00:12:10.456 --> 00:12:12.901
So if you use Threadspawn from the standard library,

00:12:13.182 --> 00:12:17.231
it spawns a new thread that is eventually going to run the closure that you give it,

00:12:17.411 --> 00:12:21.502
and it gives you back a handle to that thread that you can use,

00:12:21.502 --> 00:12:22.023
for example,

00:12:22.063 --> 00:12:25.171
to wait for the thread to complete and get its result.

00:12:25.571 --> 00:12:28.151
And the semantics here for join handle are very similar.

00:12:28.531 --> 00:12:31.211
So the join handle you get back from calling spawn...

00:12:32.931 --> 00:12:38.147
is something that you can use to abort the task you've given,

00:12:38.608 --> 00:12:41.467
or you see it itself implements future,

00:12:41.847 --> 00:12:45.797
and so you can await the join handle you get back in order to wait for the task,

00:12:45.877 --> 00:12:47.326
the future that you spawned,

00:12:47.708 --> 00:12:50.747
to yield its value eventually and get it back.

00:12:52.989 --> 00:12:53.975
If you drop the handle,

00:12:54.015 --> 00:12:54.659
nothing happens.

00:12:55.383 --> 00:12:58.463
There's no automatic abort when you drop a join handle.

00:12:58.724 --> 00:13:02.781
This is the same thing as with standard thread spawn.

00:13:03.283 --> 00:13:07.946
The join handle you get back or the thread handle you get back does not do anything if you drop it.

00:13:10.803 --> 00:13:13.073
The distinction between spawn and block on,

00:13:13.134 --> 00:13:13.636
as I mentioned,

00:13:13.636 --> 00:13:17.700
is that block on will block where you call it until the future is resolved.

00:13:18.183 --> 00:13:20.631
Spawn will just sort of throw it out in a queue and then return.

00:13:22.531 --> 00:13:27.087
Every future that has been spawned onto a runtime becomes a task.

00:13:28.669 --> 00:13:32.207
That does not mean that every future that is on a runtime is a task.

00:13:32.347 --> 00:13:35.547
And the distinction here is that futures can contain other futures.

00:13:36.007 --> 00:13:37.314
So imagine that you have,

00:13:37.515 --> 00:13:37.736
you know,

00:13:37.776 --> 00:13:38.660
you write async,

00:13:39.223 --> 00:13:40.027
like an async block,

00:13:40.369 --> 00:13:41.636
and inside of the async block,

00:13:42.018 --> 00:13:43.467
you call some asynchronous function.

00:13:44.048 --> 00:13:46.067
That asynchronous function itself creates a future.

00:13:46.467 --> 00:13:47.458
And maybe inside of there,

00:13:47.518 --> 00:13:48.287
there's an async block.

00:13:48.428 --> 00:13:49.354
Maybe inside of there,

00:13:49.716 --> 00:13:50.320
it calls,

00:13:50.320 --> 00:13:50.703
I don't know,

00:13:50.783 --> 00:13:50.944
uh...

00:13:51.495 --> 00:13:53.503
it tries to read a file asynchronously,

00:13:53.624 --> 00:13:54.748
or it tries to open a socket,

00:13:54.769 --> 00:13:55.331
whatever it might be,

00:13:55.652 --> 00:13:56.657
that is also a future.

00:13:56.958 --> 00:14:00.294
And so these are futures that contain futures that contain futures that contain futures.

00:14:00.675 --> 00:14:02.602
And when you await one of those futures,

00:14:02.782 --> 00:14:05.191
you just sort of resolve that sub-future,

00:14:05.552 --> 00:14:09.971
but the larger future you're inside of is still there and has not returned ready yet.

00:14:10.472 --> 00:14:17.549
It's only when the outermost future returns that sort of that task has completed.

00:14:17.910 --> 00:14:18.391
And so again,

00:14:18.494 --> 00:14:18.621
you

00:14:18.870 --> 00:14:19.773
only the thing,

00:14:19.974 --> 00:14:24.547
only the futures that you pass to spawn become these top-level tasks.

00:14:25.209 --> 00:14:27.387
And Tokyo only knows about the top level.

00:14:27.708 --> 00:14:30.787
It can't see inside your future types and see all the inner futures.

00:14:31.168 --> 00:14:33.787
It only sees the top-level tasks.

00:14:34.209 --> 00:14:37.547
So the futures that have specifically been passed to runtime spawn,

00:14:38.048 --> 00:14:38.971
or if you look in

00:14:39.693 --> 00:14:40.375
Tokyo itself,

00:14:40.656 --> 00:14:44.247
you see there's a macro called spawn.

00:14:45.364 --> 00:14:48.839
And the spawn macro under the hood really does the same thing.

00:14:48.859 --> 00:14:52.251
It gets a handle to the current runtime and then it spawns the current,

00:14:52.472 --> 00:14:54.439
the future you give it onto that runtime.

00:14:54.599 --> 00:14:55.719
It gives you back the join handle.

00:14:56.379 --> 00:14:59.579
And so it's only things that have been passed to spawn that turn into tasks.

00:15:00.520 --> 00:15:01.263
In addition to,

00:15:01.484 --> 00:15:01.725
you know,

00:15:01.966 --> 00:15:05.339
the thing that you pass to block on also becomes one of these top level tasks.

00:15:06.068 --> 00:15:09.683
And the Tokyo scheduler only knows about these top-level tasks.

00:15:10.906 --> 00:15:12.472
When you have a thread in Tokyo,

00:15:12.552 --> 00:15:15.423
regardless of whether it's the current thread or a multi-threaded runtime,

00:15:16.123 --> 00:15:21.143
and that worker thread is looking for the next thing to work on,

00:15:21.565 --> 00:15:23.232
it will look at the set of tasks,

00:15:23.594 --> 00:15:25.683
not the set of all nested futures.

00:15:27.435 --> 00:15:28.538
And the thinking here,

00:15:28.638 --> 00:15:28.859
right,

00:15:28.899 --> 00:15:37.149
is that the only entry point that Tokyo has into your futures is calling the poll method on the future that it was actually passed.

00:15:37.189 --> 00:15:40.806
And then that sort of cascades all the way down into polling all the inner futures,

00:15:40.846 --> 00:15:44.983
but the real interface is just the poll call on the topmost task,

00:15:45.505 --> 00:15:46.469
the topmost future.

00:15:47.929 --> 00:15:51.946
So now we get to the distinction here between the current thread runtime and the multi-threaded runtime.

00:15:52.167 --> 00:15:53.351
In the current thread runtime,

00:15:53.492 --> 00:15:54.315
if you call spawn,

00:15:54.476 --> 00:15:55.238
nothing happens.

00:15:55.840 --> 00:15:57.868
The future gets turned into a task,

00:15:57.868 --> 00:15:59.515
gets put on the task queue,

00:15:59.736 --> 00:16:00.640
and then it returns.

00:16:01.041 --> 00:16:03.450
The future does not actually run in any meaningful sense.

00:16:03.892 --> 00:16:10.195
It is only when you call block on that you're sort of giving over execution control to the current thread runtime,

00:16:10.195 --> 00:16:10.677
to Tokyo.

00:16:11.259 --> 00:16:11.842
At that point,

00:16:12.103 --> 00:16:13.188
with the current thread runtime,

00:16:13.449 --> 00:16:16.105
Tokyo is going to look at the set of...

00:16:17.232 --> 00:16:18.218
tasks that it has,

00:16:18.741 --> 00:16:19.385
execute them.

00:16:20.907 --> 00:16:22.777
until they yield either pull ready,

00:16:22.957 --> 00:16:23.777
in which it's going to return,

00:16:24.220 --> 00:16:25.657
or yield pull pending,

00:16:25.857 --> 00:16:29.097
in which case they're going to put them on the not ready task queue.

00:16:29.539 --> 00:16:31.176
And then it just keeps doing this in a loop.

00:16:31.538 --> 00:16:40.725
It keeps calling pull on all of the tasks that it knows about until it gets to a point where the future that was passed to block on returns ready,

00:16:40.967 --> 00:16:41.997
and at that point it returns.

00:16:42.377 --> 00:16:44.137
And if there are tasks left in the queue,

00:16:44.459 --> 00:16:45.437
it just leaves them there,

00:16:45.698 --> 00:16:47.537
and then does not execute them any further.

00:16:47.817 --> 00:16:51.750
So it's only in the context of block on that things in the task queue actually run.

00:16:52.513 --> 00:16:54.180
If you have a multi-threaded scheduler,

00:16:54.462 --> 00:16:55.707
which again is the default,

00:16:56.270 --> 00:17:00.706
it's also what you get if you use like the Tokyo main annotation on a function,

00:17:01.428 --> 00:17:05.190
then what will actually happen is you have this pool of worker threads,

00:17:05.331 --> 00:17:05.472
right?

00:17:05.553 --> 00:17:06.377
So when Tokyo starts up,

00:17:06.638 --> 00:17:08.989
starts one worker thread for every CPU core you have.

00:17:09.793 --> 00:17:11.138
That pool of worker threads,

00:17:12.141 --> 00:17:14.288
each one has its own local queue.

00:17:14.733 --> 00:17:16.379
of tasks that it knows about,

00:17:16.640 --> 00:17:19.189
and there's also a global queue that they can all read from.

00:17:20.059 --> 00:17:22.793
And the idea is that every worker thread is just in a loop.

00:17:23.834 --> 00:17:28.053
And what they do in that loop is they look at their local queue and see if there are any tasks that can be executed.

00:17:28.894 --> 00:17:31.423
If all of them are pending and there's no reason to continue,

00:17:31.684 --> 00:17:34.133
assume that you might make progress if you pull them,

00:17:34.574 --> 00:17:36.953
then it looks at the global queue and sees if there are tasks there.

00:17:37.334 --> 00:17:38.601
If there are no tasks there either,

00:17:38.903 --> 00:17:40.753
then they can actually steal from each other.

00:17:40.833 --> 00:17:42.453
So it's a work stealing scheduler.

00:17:42.794 --> 00:17:42.915
So,

00:17:43.156 --> 00:17:43.377
you know,

00:17:43.357 --> 00:17:43.839
if you have,

00:17:44.502 --> 00:17:46.692
let's say you have two CPU cores and...

00:17:46.916 --> 00:17:47.156
You know,

00:17:47.296 --> 00:17:52.168
this thread has no tasks to run,

00:17:52.228 --> 00:17:54.804
and this one has a queue that's full of tasks that are ready to run.

00:17:55.333 --> 00:17:56.298
When this one realizes,

00:17:56.399 --> 00:17:56.520
oh,

00:17:56.560 --> 00:17:57.586
I don't have any more work,

00:17:57.867 --> 00:18:07.150
it's actually going to start looking at this other worker thread's queue and start to steal some tasks of it so that you're better utilizing your CPU resources.

00:18:07.533 --> 00:18:10.190
So this means that futures can start to move between threads.

00:18:10.653 --> 00:18:13.589
When this evens out load between your CPU cores so that you get a...

00:18:14.487 --> 00:18:16.981
make more use of the computer resources you have,

00:18:17.302 --> 00:18:18.267
but it also means,

00:18:18.287 --> 00:18:22.470
and this is sort of where that requirement that is sometimes annoying comes from,

00:18:22.652 --> 00:18:23.941
is that futures must be send.

00:18:24.583 --> 00:18:27.021
They must be allowed to move between threads.

00:18:27.481 --> 00:18:30.332
They must implement the send trait in order for

00:18:30.753 --> 00:18:32.961
TokyoP to be able to do this load distribution.

00:18:33.960 --> 00:18:34.441
And because

00:18:34.822 --> 00:18:41.077
Tokyo uses the same interface for current thread runtimes and multi-threaded runtimes,

00:18:41.538 --> 00:18:43.746
all futures you pass to Tokyo have to be sent,

00:18:44.007 --> 00:18:46.937
regardless of whether you're actually only using the current thread runtime.

00:18:47.478 --> 00:18:48.343
There is a way around this.

00:18:48.604 --> 00:18:49.751
We'll talk about that in a second,

00:18:49.972 --> 00:18:50.757
about local sets.

00:18:51.338 --> 00:18:54.417
But this is sort of the basic premise for the setup.

00:18:55.818 --> 00:18:57.996
Before I now talk more about how...

00:19:00.514 --> 00:19:02.258
Sort of how this interacts with blocking,

00:19:02.820 --> 00:19:04.284
when you can block threads,

00:19:04.906 --> 00:19:05.748
the co-op budget,

00:19:06.009 --> 00:19:06.754
block in place,

00:19:07.459 --> 00:19:07.942
shut down,

00:19:07.962 --> 00:19:08.567
that kind of stuff.

00:19:08.929 --> 00:19:12.255
Does the general sense for what a runtime looks like make sense?

00:19:19.977 --> 00:19:20.508
Let's see.

00:19:20.610 --> 00:19:21.683
Let's see.

00:19:25.670 --> 00:19:27.539
How does this model work with blocking worklets?

00:19:27.599 --> 00:19:28.645
We'll talk about that in a second.

00:19:28.886 --> 00:19:30.783
What's the use case for the current thread scheduler?

00:19:31.106 --> 00:19:32.743
The use case for the current thread scheduler...

00:19:33.909 --> 00:19:35.074
So there are sort of two.

00:19:35.958 --> 00:19:37.264
One is less so than the other.

00:19:37.546 --> 00:19:38.637
The first one is you just...

00:19:39.970 --> 00:19:41.425
Like let's say you're running your test suite.

00:19:41.807 --> 00:19:44.564
Every test is annotated with like TokyoTest.

00:19:45.470 --> 00:19:47.624
And you don't really want every test to spin up...

00:19:47.907 --> 00:19:49.143
Because you're going to run them all in parallel.

00:19:49.325 --> 00:19:50.774
You don't want every test to spin up

00:19:51.256 --> 00:19:52.443
N threads.

00:19:52.889 --> 00:19:54.255
where n is the number of CPU cores,

00:19:54.315 --> 00:19:56.865
because now you end up with n times your number of tests.

00:19:57.906 --> 00:19:59.533
And so you might use the current thread runtime there.

00:19:59.834 --> 00:20:00.697
In practice,

00:20:01.199 --> 00:20:04.131
and I think the Tokyo test annotation does this by default now,

00:20:04.533 --> 00:20:07.846
it actually starts a multi-threaded scheduler with only one thread.

00:20:08.650 --> 00:20:12.165
And so that is very often the thing you want instead of a current thread scheduler.

00:20:14.100 --> 00:20:18.801
just so that you don't have the sort of complexity of having to manage multiple schedulers and test multiple schedulers.

00:20:19.304 --> 00:20:23.619
The real reason for using the current thread scheduler is if you have things like,

00:20:25.304 --> 00:20:29.154
you want to limit the amount of movement that happens between threads,

00:20:29.455 --> 00:20:35.399
because you have a workload where you know that it's very costly if you're executing some sequence of instructions on one CPU,

00:20:36.101 --> 00:20:38.289
and suddenly they get moved to a different CPU,

00:20:38.691 --> 00:20:38.851
right?

00:20:39.052 --> 00:20:41.924
That ends up sort of making your...

00:20:42.810 --> 00:20:44.622
CPU cache utilization worse.

00:20:45.363 --> 00:20:56.122
Sometimes you have sort of CPU pinning that you do so that all of your workload happens on a particular set of CPU cores and you don't want the other CPU cores to be used at all for some reason.

00:20:56.462 --> 00:20:58.562
Maybe you've dedicated them to some other worker pool.

00:20:59.202 --> 00:21:03.242
So the current thread runtime gives you more control over exactly what runs where,

00:21:04.048 --> 00:21:04.982
but it does come with the cost.

00:21:05.082 --> 00:21:07.902
It's like it's much less of a general purpose executor.

00:21:12.464 --> 00:21:15.398
Why would I use Tokyo spawn over Rust std thread spawn?

00:21:16.301 --> 00:21:18.718
So the difference there is that Tokyo spawn lets you give a future.

00:21:19.178 --> 00:21:22.938
The standard library thread spawn spawns an operating system level thread.

00:21:23.399 --> 00:21:26.678
So you give it a closure and it executes that synchronous closure.

00:21:26.818 --> 00:21:27.758
There's no async involved.

00:21:32.163 --> 00:21:33.718
Is Tokyo main also a task?

00:21:33.919 --> 00:21:34.081
Yeah,

00:21:34.383 --> 00:21:36.418
so this is actually an interesting thing to look at.

00:21:36.418 --> 00:21:40.716
So if I go here and I do cargo new bin...

00:21:43.814 --> 00:21:44.195
Kyoto.

00:21:44.595 --> 00:21:44.716
Aha!

00:21:45.457 --> 00:21:46.278
Kyoto.

00:21:47.700 --> 00:21:47.840
Yeah.

00:21:49.162 --> 00:21:49.984
Because Tokyo,

00:21:50.404 --> 00:21:50.625
right?

00:21:51.947 --> 00:21:52.247
Anyway.

00:21:53.529 --> 00:21:54.851
Let me do add

00:21:55.332 --> 00:21:57.055
Tokyo here with features full,

00:21:57.897 --> 00:21:58.658
source main,

00:21:58.798 --> 00:21:59.720
and I'll just do

00:22:00.382 --> 00:22:01.404
Tokyo main,

00:22:02.426 --> 00:22:04.009
asyncfn main.

00:22:04.850 --> 00:22:06.153
And then I run cargos band.

00:22:06.253 --> 00:22:07.456
Let's see what this gives us.

00:22:09.363 --> 00:22:12.434
So this is what we actually get when we run...

00:22:14.288 --> 00:22:17.154
When we add the Tokyo main annotation to an asyncfn,

00:22:18.157 --> 00:22:22.566
it really just replaces your main function with a non-async main function.

00:22:23.228 --> 00:22:27.906
It takes the body of the main function that you gave and turns it into an async block.

00:22:29.528 --> 00:22:31.697
And then it creates a Tokyo runtime,

00:22:32.460 --> 00:22:33.726
enables all the features on it.

00:22:33.846 --> 00:22:34.906
It's a multi-threaded runtime.

00:22:35.327 --> 00:22:37.166
And then it passes that body to block on.

00:22:38.482 --> 00:22:39.205
And so in other words,

00:22:39.205 --> 00:22:40.470
when you use Tokyo main,

00:22:40.871 --> 00:22:49.015
all it turns into is that future just becomes both a top level task and it becomes the main thing that the runtime is blocking on.

00:22:49.158 --> 00:22:50.904
And so when the main function returns,

00:22:50.924 --> 00:22:55.300
when the future that is in your asyncfn main is completed,

00:22:55.300 --> 00:22:56.063
it returns ready,

00:22:57.066 --> 00:23:01.845
then the whole runtime is considered done and yields control to the actual main function,

00:23:02.106 --> 00:23:04.317
which then returns and closes your program.

00:23:13.619 --> 00:23:16.046
Do you know what the Tokyo approach is regarding the work stealing logic?

00:23:16.646 --> 00:23:17.814
Because when we think about work stealing,

00:23:17.814 --> 00:23:19.566
we think about costly context switches potentially.

00:23:20.226 --> 00:23:26.066
So there's actually pretty decent documentation in Tokyo about exactly how it does work stealing.

00:23:26.086 --> 00:23:26.588
If you go to

00:23:27.130 --> 00:23:27.892
Tokyo runtime,

00:23:27.892 --> 00:23:31.926
you scroll down a bunch and you go to multi-threaded runtime behavior at the time of writing.

00:23:32.767 --> 00:23:36.066
This one talks about the different cues that they have and what the...

00:23:36.459 --> 00:23:39.010
policies are for when you look at the local queue,

00:23:39.010 --> 00:23:40.014
when you look at the global queue,

00:23:40.295 --> 00:23:41.199
when you're allowed to steal.

00:23:41.581 --> 00:23:44.534
And they basically try to balance the cost here,

00:23:44.594 --> 00:23:44.735
right?

00:23:44.755 --> 00:23:46.203
Because there is a cost to stealing,

00:23:46.444 --> 00:23:48.214
but there's also a huge benefit to stealing.

00:23:48.935 --> 00:23:54.193
And so you basically tweak the parameters until it hits something that generally works.

00:23:54.374 --> 00:23:58.774
And then there's a bunch of configuration parameters you can set if that

00:23:59.073 --> 00:24:01.246
the default behavior doesn't work well for your application.

00:24:01.628 --> 00:24:04.906
But you should really benchmark and make sure that if you change these settings,

00:24:05.507 --> 00:24:07.433
it's actually under like real load,

00:24:08.095 --> 00:24:09.439
realistic load,

00:24:10.442 --> 00:24:11.646
that these numbers make sense.

00:24:15.751 --> 00:24:19.206
While looping on pending check when available instead of park and unpark like threads.

00:24:19.407 --> 00:24:23.326
So it's not actually a loop on just if it returns pending then loop.

00:24:24.247 --> 00:24:30.619
This is where we get into the idea of wakers and notify,

00:24:31.240 --> 00:24:34.026
which is sort of the asynchronous version of park and unpark.

00:24:35.106 --> 00:24:37.596
So it is actually more sophisticated than that,

00:24:37.797 --> 00:24:40.306
which we'll get to when we talk about resources a little bit later.

00:24:41.110 --> 00:24:45.646
how that mechanism works for choosing which futures have become ready.

00:24:46.146 --> 00:24:46.911
So in general,

00:24:47.113 --> 00:24:49.046
the sort of logical way to think about it,

00:24:49.046 --> 00:24:50.506
or the theoretical way to think about it maybe,

00:24:50.927 --> 00:24:52.715
is that every worker has,

00:24:53.137 --> 00:24:54.081
or every runtime really,

00:24:54.161 --> 00:24:55.246
has two queues.

00:24:55.708 --> 00:24:58.166
One of them is a queue of runnable tasks,

00:24:58.687 --> 00:25:02.106
and one of them is a queue of not runnable tasks,

00:25:03.270 --> 00:25:04.337
or pending tasks,

00:25:04.337 --> 00:25:04.619
if you will,

00:25:04.639 --> 00:25:05.626
but not runnable tasks.

00:25:06.702 --> 00:25:08.928
When you choose which thing to execute next,

00:25:08.948 --> 00:25:11.916
you only look at the things in the runnable task column,

00:25:12.136 --> 00:25:12.758
in that queue.

00:25:13.319 --> 00:25:16.052
And those are things where you know that if you call poll on them,

00:25:16.253 --> 00:25:17.278
they're going to do some useful work.

00:25:17.759 --> 00:25:20.564
The ones that are in the non-runnable queue,

00:25:21.566 --> 00:25:26.075
those you have no reason to believe the calling poll will make progress on,

00:25:26.316 --> 00:25:27.318
and so you just don't do it.

00:25:27.899 --> 00:25:31.712
And then there's this mechanism that moves things from one queue to the other,

00:25:31.752 --> 00:25:33.538
so from the non-runnable to the runnable queue.

00:25:34.608 --> 00:25:37.022
whenever there's a signal that indicates that this future,

00:25:37.323 --> 00:25:39.262
this task may now be able to make progress.

00:25:39.583 --> 00:25:39.786
Again,

00:25:39.826 --> 00:25:41.142
we'll talk about that when we get to resources.

00:25:41.723 --> 00:25:45.492
And when you run a future from the runnable queue and it returns pending,

00:25:45.512 --> 00:25:46.862
you move it to the non-runnable queue.

00:25:46.942 --> 00:25:48.382
So you don't try to execute it again.

00:25:49.303 --> 00:25:52.171
And if a worker thread runs out of the runtime,

00:25:52.472 --> 00:25:54.318
runs out of thing in the runnable column,

00:25:54.799 --> 00:26:00.778
then it will actually park itself and only get unparked when there is some future,

00:26:00.958 --> 00:26:03.478
some task that has moved into the runnable state again.

00:26:08.373 --> 00:26:10.564
Why not spawn more threads than cores?

00:26:10.886 --> 00:26:13.564
So there's no real reason to have more threads than cores,

00:26:13.605 --> 00:26:13.746
right?

00:26:13.806 --> 00:26:17.119
The number of cores is the amount of work you can do in parallel anyway,

00:26:18.123 --> 00:26:20.304
and so there's not really a benefit to having more of them.

00:26:26.524 --> 00:26:29.396
CurrentThreadScheduler is also important if you're on a system without multithreading.

00:26:29.918 --> 00:26:32.691
So things like in WASI where there are no threads,

00:26:33.253 --> 00:26:36.491
the CurrentThreadScheduler is the only scheduler you can have because there aren't threads,

00:26:36.531 --> 00:26:37.295
you can't spawn them.

00:26:37.778 --> 00:26:40.928
And so you can only execute in the current execution context anyway.

00:26:50.204 --> 00:26:50.905
Thank you.

00:26:59.756 --> 00:27:01.379
Okay.

00:27:03.724 --> 00:27:03.844
Ah,

00:27:04.145 --> 00:27:05.588
so kernel CPU scheduler,

00:27:05.628 --> 00:27:13.026
so the operating system CPU scheduler also implement work stealing in the sense that like if one CPU core is executing a thread,

00:27:14.009 --> 00:27:14.210
then,

00:27:14.431 --> 00:27:15.554
and another CPU core,

00:27:15.995 --> 00:27:16.216
you know,

00:27:16.296 --> 00:27:18.081
wants to choose something to work,

00:27:18.101 --> 00:27:25.048
it can steal the threads that are sort of locally locally queued on some other CPU.

00:27:25.895 --> 00:27:26.316
Sort of,

00:27:26.537 --> 00:27:26.718
right?

00:27:26.758 --> 00:27:32.374
So basically the observation here is that threads on the OS level can move between CPU cores.

00:27:32.474 --> 00:27:33.317
And that is totally true.

00:27:33.699 --> 00:27:35.265
It's not usually work stealing,

00:27:35.466 --> 00:27:37.434
but it does mean that the threads can move in this way.

00:27:38.337 --> 00:27:41.194
The difference here is that the operating system is not aware of futures.

00:27:41.534 --> 00:27:43.308
It doesn't know about different futures,

00:27:43.349 --> 00:27:44.034
different tasks.

00:27:44.895 --> 00:27:50.414
And so you could spawn one thread for every single task that you have.

00:27:50.896 --> 00:27:55.213
The problem is every time the kernel wants to switch between threads...

00:27:55.921 --> 00:27:58.431
It has to do like a kernel level context switch,

00:27:58.793 --> 00:28:00.058
which are fairly expensive.

00:28:00.919 --> 00:28:05.270
Whereas futures are a user space concept,

00:28:05.371 --> 00:28:06.453
not just a user space concept,

00:28:06.453 --> 00:28:08.138
but a Rust based concept.

00:28:08.559 --> 00:28:10.538
And so you don't really need to go via the kernel.

00:28:10.959 --> 00:28:16.733
So if you instead have your own scheduler that moves a single operating system thread between multiple tasks,

00:28:17.134 --> 00:28:18.558
you can do that way more efficiently.

00:28:18.698 --> 00:28:21.417
And this is sort of the whole idea behind green threading.

00:28:36.193 --> 00:28:39.886
Is the queue of tasks an OS-based event queue?

00:28:40.718 --> 00:28:40.843
No.

00:28:41.627 --> 00:28:43.192
So these are actually just,

00:28:43.994 --> 00:28:47.886
you can think of them as linked lists that Tokyo keeps internally of tasks.

00:28:48.306 --> 00:28:48.709
That it just,

00:28:49.051 --> 00:28:51.186
you can atomically add things to either queue.

00:28:51.687 --> 00:28:55.406
There's no operating system level part of those task lists.

00:28:55.788 --> 00:28:58.101
The only place where the operating system comes in is in...

00:28:58.510 --> 00:29:00.557
spawning these different threads,

00:29:00.577 --> 00:29:01.681
the worker threads initially,

00:29:02.423 --> 00:29:05.778
and some of the mechanisms for dealing with IO resources and timer resources,

00:29:06.642 --> 00:29:07.586
which we'll talk about in a second.

00:29:12.798 --> 00:29:12.999
Okay,

00:29:13.341 --> 00:29:13.541
great.

00:29:13.903 --> 00:29:17.997
So now it seems like there's a sort of general understanding for what the runtime here is.

00:29:19.240 --> 00:29:21.545
Let's then talk about blocking.

00:29:22.266 --> 00:29:23.589
So when you,

00:29:24.050 --> 00:29:26.677
given that we only have these n worker threads,

00:29:26.717 --> 00:29:30.553
where n is your number of CPUs or whatever value you configure it to,

00:29:31.579 --> 00:29:34.383
Where you run into trouble is if you pass a future,

00:29:34.463 --> 00:29:35.204
an async block,

00:29:35.204 --> 00:29:37.227
an async function to Tokyo,

00:29:38.208 --> 00:29:40.872
and one of the worker threads is executing that future,

00:29:41.353 --> 00:29:45.218
and that future ends up calling something that blocks the current thread.

00:29:45.618 --> 00:29:47.341
Think of like it calls,

00:29:48.222 --> 00:29:52.287
let's say it tries to read from the standard in from the terminal,

00:29:52.708 --> 00:29:56.693
but it doesn't do it through like an asynchronous std in handle from Tokyo.

00:29:57.053 --> 00:29:59.256
It uses like std io,

00:29:59.737 --> 00:30:00.378
std io.

00:30:01.268 --> 00:30:01.529
stood,

00:30:02.030 --> 00:30:02.151
IO,

00:30:02.532 --> 00:30:02.954
stood in,

00:30:03.597 --> 00:30:04.982
and just like a normal read call.

00:30:05.423 --> 00:30:05.584
Well,

00:30:05.866 --> 00:30:08.342
that's going to block the current operating system level thread.

00:30:08.442 --> 00:30:09.702
This is not a Tokyo concept.

00:30:10.083 --> 00:30:11.662
You're just doing something that blocks.

00:30:13.184 --> 00:30:13.889
And at that point,

00:30:14.170 --> 00:30:16.142
you're not just blocking the execution of this future.

00:30:16.505 --> 00:30:18.622
You're actually holding up that entire worker thread.

00:30:19.143 --> 00:30:26.522
It has no way to now start working on some other task because the operating system level thread is blocked.

00:30:27.733 --> 00:30:33.744
And so this is why it is really important that when you have asynchronous futures that you pass to Tokyo,

00:30:34.165 --> 00:30:36.650
that you don't have them do blocking calls.

00:30:37.112 --> 00:30:37.915
Because if they do,

00:30:38.376 --> 00:30:42.010
they're going to hold up the execution of any other task on that CPU core.

00:30:42.651 --> 00:30:42.933
Again,

00:30:43.013 --> 00:30:46.690
because the number of worker threads you have is just the number of CPU cores.

00:30:48.233 --> 00:30:49.005
And this is not a...

00:30:49.907 --> 00:30:51.395
...sort of hard limit,

00:30:51.737 --> 00:30:51.858
right?

00:30:51.918 --> 00:30:52.080
Like,

00:30:52.141 --> 00:30:53.617
what does blocking mean?

00:30:54.079 --> 00:30:58.638
Because reading from standard in just means you're blocking until the user presses a key.

00:30:58.818 --> 00:31:00.277
So it's not an infinite block.

00:31:00.758 --> 00:31:02.138
Very few blocking things are.

00:31:03.099 --> 00:31:03.541
In general,

00:31:03.541 --> 00:31:10.098
what we're talking about is just you should avoid holding up a worker thread for a very long period of time.

00:31:10.529 --> 00:31:12.601
And what very long means is sort of up to you.

00:31:13.043 --> 00:31:18.762
But imagine that you have a system where like a bunch of your asynchronous futures all do some kind of blocking call.

00:31:19.162 --> 00:31:20.530
And those blocking calls take,

00:31:20.851 --> 00:31:21.213
I don't know,

00:31:21.294 --> 00:31:22.762
they take a second for whatever reason.

00:31:23.677 --> 00:31:23.918
If you,

00:31:24.059 --> 00:31:25.523
let's say you have two CPU cores,

00:31:27.289 --> 00:31:30.701
both of them end up executing futures that have this one second block,

00:31:31.263 --> 00:31:33.834
then now you're going to have some periods of time where for

00:31:34.938 --> 00:31:36.984
500 milliseconds at a time or something,

00:31:37.646 --> 00:31:41.931
no futures are being executed because both of the worker threads are held up in the blocking call.

00:31:42.294 --> 00:31:45.449
So even though there are lots of other futures that could be making progress,

00:31:45.992 --> 00:31:48.785
there are no worker threads to pick up those tasks.

00:31:49.500 --> 00:31:54.268
And so that's why when we talk about you don't want to block in an asynchronous context,

00:31:54.528 --> 00:32:00.058
we don't really mean like you can't do an operating system call that might block.

00:32:00.398 --> 00:32:10.738
We're talking about you don't want to hold up any worker thread for a prolonged period of time because that's going to mean not picking up other asynchronous tasks for that period of time.

00:32:12.135 --> 00:32:15.225
So even if you do just very compute heavy work,

00:32:15.245 --> 00:32:16.910
so let's say you're not actually pausing,

00:32:16.990 --> 00:32:17.753
you're not blocking,

00:32:18.035 --> 00:32:21.992
you just have like a matrix multiply or something that takes like two or three seconds,

00:32:22.413 --> 00:32:27.430
then that still has the same property that you're holding up the pickup of other tasks.

00:32:28.391 --> 00:32:31.564
And so there isn't really a rule here for how long to wait.

00:32:31.564 --> 00:32:34.956
It just depends on your tolerance for futures not being executed.

00:32:35.418 --> 00:32:39.503
The general rule of thumb I've seen is that if you have a

00:32:41.169 --> 00:32:43.354
chunks of code in your futures,

00:32:44.316 --> 00:32:50.814
so that is code that executes between two await points with no awaits in this critical block.

00:32:51.175 --> 00:32:55.590
If you have blocks like this that take more than 100 milliseconds to execute,

00:32:56.091 --> 00:33:00.908
you should probably move them to a separate blocking thread or use block in place.

00:33:01.329 --> 00:33:01.771
Basically,

00:33:02.052 --> 00:33:03.276
you need to tell Tokyo,

00:33:03.678 --> 00:33:03.858
hey,

00:33:04.380 --> 00:33:05.866
I'm going to do something blocking now.

00:33:06.950 --> 00:33:08.897
Do that in a different thread or...

00:33:09.995 --> 00:33:11.481
We'll talk about block in place in a second,

00:33:11.481 --> 00:33:13.128
but basically you need to notify Tokyo,

00:33:13.309 --> 00:33:16.942
I'm about to do something that's going to take a while on this thread.

00:33:19.230 --> 00:33:28.530
And there are also calls that are fast most of the time and sometimes really slow.

00:33:28.751 --> 00:33:30.644
So you can imagine things like taking a lock.

00:33:31.410 --> 00:33:33.039
And I'm not talking here about the Tokyo mutex,

00:33:33.079 --> 00:33:34.447
we'll talk about the distinction in a second.

00:33:34.990 --> 00:33:38.389
I'm talking about standard sync mutexes.

00:33:38.989 --> 00:33:39.814
If you take one of those,

00:33:40.176 --> 00:33:41.202
usually it's super fast.

00:33:41.483 --> 00:33:42.856
Usually you take the lock,

00:33:42.876 --> 00:33:43.481
you get the lock,

00:33:43.643 --> 00:33:45.142
and then you do some work and you release the lock.

00:33:45.202 --> 00:33:45.941
There's no real delay.

00:33:46.382 --> 00:33:52.142
But it could be that some other thread in your system has the lock and it's doing something that takes like 10 seconds.

00:33:52.464 --> 00:33:59.302
And so now your thread that tries to take the same lock is actually going to block for 10 seconds while waiting for this other thing to release the lock.

00:33:59.643 --> 00:34:02.602
And now you're holding up your thread for that period of time as well.

00:34:03.952 --> 00:34:04.142
And so...

00:34:04.142 --> 00:34:04.267
So...

00:34:05.694 --> 00:34:07.520
What we're talking about when we say blocking is like,

00:34:07.761 --> 00:34:08.845
in the worst case,

00:34:08.885 --> 00:34:10.110
does this take too long?

00:34:10.812 --> 00:34:13.810
Or longer than you're willing to wait for your other futures to be picked up?

00:34:15.913 --> 00:34:17.570
There are two ways to deal with this problem.

00:34:23.663 --> 00:34:26.810
One of them is this spawn blocking thing.

00:34:27.795 --> 00:34:27.916
So,

00:34:28.499 --> 00:34:30.509
Tokyo actually has two worker pools.

00:34:30.810 --> 00:34:31.843
It has two thread pools.

00:34:32.350 --> 00:34:33.330
One of them is for the workers.

00:34:33.350 --> 00:34:33.451
So,

00:34:33.471 --> 00:34:35.786
these are the things that execute asynchronous tasks.

00:34:36.390 --> 00:34:38.166
The other is a blocking thread pool.

00:34:38.670 --> 00:34:40.708
These are threads that are...

00:34:41.086 --> 00:34:42.109
expected to block.

00:34:42.189 --> 00:34:46.062
They're just doing something that we know is going to block the current thread.

00:34:46.602 --> 00:34:47.365
We have a huge,

00:34:47.405 --> 00:34:51.302
like the limit for how many blocking threads you can run is like super high.

00:34:51.402 --> 00:34:53.251
We don't really cut you off at any point.

00:34:53.734 --> 00:34:54.819
There is theoretically a limit,

00:34:54.879 --> 00:34:55.422
but in practice,

00:34:56.124 --> 00:34:58.333
we assume that most of those are sort of sleeping or something.

00:34:58.836 --> 00:35:00.282
And that pool is initially zero.

00:35:00.831 --> 00:35:01.212
Or rather,

00:35:01.232 --> 00:35:02.257
that's not quite true,

00:35:02.518 --> 00:35:04.325
all of the worker threads are actually in that pool,

00:35:04.446 --> 00:35:05.536
but let's ignore that for a second.

00:35:06.686 --> 00:35:11.818
The blocking thread pool is a place where you can spawn your own threads using the spawn blocking thing.

00:35:12.266 --> 00:35:14.679
And this is almost like using std thread spawn,

00:35:14.900 --> 00:35:16.508
that's basically what it turns into under the hood,

00:35:16.949 --> 00:35:23.401
except that Tokyo sort of remembers that thread for you and deals with it when it comes to clean up at shutdown for example.

00:35:26.065 --> 00:35:29.654
But this is really just an interface for spawning,

00:35:30.175 --> 00:35:31.438
blocking synchronous threads.

00:35:32.299 --> 00:35:38.778
The reason it's a little more efficient than using the standard thread version is because Tokyo actually knows to reuse these threads.

00:35:39.238 --> 00:35:42.785
So if you call spawn blocking and something runs and then finishes,

00:35:43.046 --> 00:35:44.408
and you call spawn blocking again,

00:35:44.749 --> 00:35:45.771
Tokyo might realize that,

00:35:45.791 --> 00:35:45.911
oh,

00:35:46.192 --> 00:35:49.258
there is already a thread in the blocking pool that doesn't have any work to do.

00:35:49.637 --> 00:35:51.810
we're just going to schedule this closure on that same thread.

00:35:52.130 --> 00:35:56.290
And there's some policy for when threads get sort of actually shut down from this pool.

00:35:57.150 --> 00:35:59.010
But so spawn blocking is one way in which you,

00:35:59.130 --> 00:36:01.570
if you know that you're going to do some kind of blocking work,

00:36:01.952 --> 00:36:04.390
you can use spawn blocking to take that closure,

00:36:05.010 --> 00:36:06.530
spawn it on one of these blocking threads,

00:36:06.750 --> 00:36:12.510
and you get back a join handle that is a future that you can then choose to await whenever you want to wait for that thing to have finished.

00:36:12.912 --> 00:36:14.950
And you can await it immediately after spawning.

00:36:15.294 --> 00:36:15.475
Right,

00:36:15.495 --> 00:36:17.663
that's fine because you're awaiting,

00:36:18.044 --> 00:36:19.590
which means that you're going to return pending,

00:36:19.690 --> 00:36:24.227
which means other futures are going to get to run while that blocking task is executing on the other pool.

00:36:25.805 --> 00:36:29.092
The other thing you can do if you're not willing to take,

00:36:29.192 --> 00:36:29.493
you know,

00:36:30.395 --> 00:36:33.742
whatever the thing you want to execute blockingly is,

00:36:34.203 --> 00:36:36.655
if you're not willing to send that over to another thread,

00:36:36.695 --> 00:36:37.177
for example,

00:36:37.217 --> 00:36:38.202
because it's not send,

00:36:40.184 --> 00:36:44.902
and you'll notice here that this indeed requires that the closure you pass in is send,

00:36:45.568 --> 00:36:46.720
is you can use...

00:36:47.656 --> 00:36:48.779
Block in place.

00:36:49.480 --> 00:36:51.224
So in Tokyo task block in place,

00:36:51.685 --> 00:36:55.393
this is a function you can call.

00:36:55.473 --> 00:36:56.496
You pass it a closure,

00:36:56.837 --> 00:36:58.585
but this closure does not need to be sent.

00:36:59.167 --> 00:37:08.194
And what happens when you call this function is that Tokyo takes all of the state that the worker thread has and sort of saves it somewhere.

00:37:09.356 --> 00:37:11.180
And then it,

00:37:11.200 --> 00:37:13.003
which you can think of as when it saves it somewhere,

00:37:13.003 --> 00:37:17.430
it actually sort of gives it away all of the state related to this worker thread,

00:37:17.670 --> 00:37:19.854
and it becomes a non-worker thread.

00:37:20.734 --> 00:37:25.070
And it sort of gives Tokyo the green light to start a new worker thread in its place.

00:37:25.851 --> 00:37:26.532
And so that way,

00:37:27.555 --> 00:37:34.390
this thread that was a worker thread stops being a worker thread and gives its worker state away to Tokyo or back to Tokyo.

00:37:34.992 --> 00:37:37.330
And then it just continues executing your blocking code.

00:37:37.690 --> 00:37:38.392
And at this point,

00:37:38.592 --> 00:37:46.810
you're not holding up any other futures because some new thread that Tokyo spawns can pick up the worker state and then resume executing all of the futures from here.

00:37:47.449 --> 00:37:49.622
So you can think of it as a spawn blocking.

00:37:50.004 --> 00:37:51.222
If you have this as the worker thread,

00:37:51.463 --> 00:37:53.501
it starts a new thread and moves your work over there.

00:37:53.924 --> 00:37:56.462
Whereas block in place is you have a worker thread,

00:37:56.943 --> 00:38:00.522
you start a new thread that is the worker thread and you continue your blocking work here.

00:38:01.383 --> 00:38:03.873
So they are sort of symmetrical,

00:38:03.974 --> 00:38:04.375
if you will,

00:38:04.395 --> 00:38:04.978
in that sense.

00:38:05.438 --> 00:38:05.599
Now,

00:38:06.041 --> 00:38:10.058
block in place comes with a couple of performance things to be aware of.

00:38:10.499 --> 00:38:11.745
This is fairly subtle stuff,

00:38:11.745 --> 00:38:14.118
so I recommend reading the docs for block in place.

00:38:15.299 --> 00:38:16.082
In general,

00:38:16.504 --> 00:38:20.458
only use block in place if you truly need to do some blocking stuff that is not send.

00:38:21.341 --> 00:38:22.007
But when you do,

00:38:22.512 --> 00:38:23.118
that's what it's for.

00:38:26.738 --> 00:38:26.918
Okay,

00:38:27.340 --> 00:38:30.229
let's pause there before I continue on runtime stuff.

00:38:31.714 --> 00:38:32.716
How much sense does this make?

00:38:44.823 --> 00:38:48.178
How much overhead would using async in an embedded system with one core be?

00:38:50.001 --> 00:38:52.456
There is overhead to using asynchrony,

00:38:52.657 --> 00:38:52.798
right?

00:38:52.938 --> 00:38:58.158
Because you now need to have this stuff that keeps track of the...

00:39:00.940 --> 00:39:03.209
of the task and it chooses how to schedule them,

00:39:03.651 --> 00:39:05.238
the overhead is less than you might think.

00:39:06.418 --> 00:39:08.303
And usually the overhead sort of,

00:39:10.650 --> 00:39:16.068
you can make up for it by the fact that you get to use green threading rather than going through the kernel if you do a lot of context switching.

00:39:16.711 --> 00:39:19.340
But in terms of performance,

00:39:19.340 --> 00:39:22.047
like async is usually slightly slower.

00:39:23.692 --> 00:39:24.474
The difference,

00:39:24.835 --> 00:39:25.095
again,

00:39:25.156 --> 00:39:26.621
for exactly the same workload,

00:39:28.629 --> 00:39:30.337
assuming that you can use...

00:39:30.673 --> 00:39:31.502
Can't use threads.

00:39:35.453 --> 00:39:40.710
Where asynchronous shines is both if you have a huge number of tasks.

00:39:41.491 --> 00:39:44.589
So think of things like you have a task for every connection and you're expecting,

00:39:44.589 --> 00:39:44.830
you know,

00:39:45.170 --> 00:39:47.250
tens of millions of connections or something.

00:39:47.711 --> 00:39:54.610
Then doing them in a green threading approach rather than going through the kernel every time does end up increasing your overall performance.

00:39:55.253 --> 00:39:55.978
The second reason,

00:39:56.018 --> 00:39:57.709
if you want to do things concurrently.

00:39:58.030 --> 00:40:04.108
So one pattern that we see a lot when used in asynchronous context is that you want to like wait for...

00:40:04.666 --> 00:40:09.302
either a TCP packet to come in or the user to press something on the keyboard.

00:40:10.063 --> 00:40:11.450
If you were in the threading model,

00:40:11.811 --> 00:40:18.522
you would need to have one thread that blocks on a read from the TCP socket and one thread that blocks on a read from the standard in,

00:40:19.043 --> 00:40:21.222
and then you need some way for those threads to synchronize.

00:40:22.096 --> 00:40:23.078
In the async world,

00:40:23.459 --> 00:40:25.142
each of those is just a future,

00:40:25.462 --> 00:40:26.504
and then you can use select,

00:40:26.544 --> 00:40:27.486
which we'll talk to in a second,

00:40:27.686 --> 00:40:31.754
so that one task awaits either of the two things.

00:40:32.195 --> 00:40:35.100
And you don't actually need two separate threads that then need,

00:40:35.381 --> 00:40:35.621
you know,

00:40:35.801 --> 00:40:38.627
atomics in order to synchronize,

00:40:39.027 --> 00:40:40.971
because they're happening on one task,

00:40:41.191 --> 00:40:42.534
so there's no synchronization needed.

00:40:43.976 --> 00:40:45.340
And very often,

00:40:45.440 --> 00:40:49.794
programs end up wanting that kind of concurrency.

00:40:51.333 --> 00:40:52.135
And it's actually,

00:40:52.456 --> 00:40:52.997
I would argue,

00:40:53.198 --> 00:40:57.730
easier to write programs in this way when you have a lot of these either-or events.

00:41:05.301 --> 00:41:10.026
Does Tokyo create a thread pool and automatically spawn more tasks if needed or is this something one has to manually set?

00:41:11.136 --> 00:41:12.944
When you start Tokyo by default,

00:41:13.466 --> 00:41:23.112
it will use the multi-threaded scheduler which starts this thread pool for you with n worker threads where n is the number of cores and with a blocking pool that has no threads.

00:41:23.676 --> 00:41:27.936
And then it will start blocking threads as needed whenever you call spawn blocking.

00:41:33.977 --> 00:41:35.223
Are you planning to talk about cancellation?

00:41:35.283 --> 00:41:35.705
Yes I am.

00:41:39.484 --> 00:41:41.176
Is there overhead in promoting the threads?

00:41:41.236 --> 00:41:41.398
Right?

00:41:41.398 --> 00:41:42.062
So this is the,

00:41:42.747 --> 00:41:43.855
you call block in place.

00:41:44.056 --> 00:41:49.556
So you take the worker state and you give it away to Tokyo and then Tokyo is going to start a new thread that picks up that worker state.

00:41:50.017 --> 00:41:51.021
And the answer is yes,

00:41:51.201 --> 00:41:55.496
there is some cost in starting up a new thread and then it picking up the state.

00:41:55.938 --> 00:41:56.522
In practice,

00:41:56.542 --> 00:41:58.596
Tokyo is actually a little bit smarter than what I just said.

00:41:59.499 --> 00:42:01.668
What will happen is when you call block in place,

00:42:01.668 --> 00:42:03.435
the worker state is saved in Tokyo.

00:42:03.966 --> 00:42:11.784
This thread runs its blocking code and when it finishes it'll look at has another thread picked up this worker state yet and if not I'm just going to take it back.

00:42:12.486 --> 00:42:16.944
And so that sort of minimizes the cost for short blocking sections.

00:42:18.307 --> 00:42:22.404
So you can often avoid this overhead of moving the execution.

00:42:32.113 --> 00:42:33.823
What does the worker thread state contain?

00:42:34.124 --> 00:42:39.180
It's mostly the queues of tasks and a couple of other things,

00:42:39.240 --> 00:42:40.362
but it's mostly the queues.

00:42:45.658 --> 00:42:48.372
How much of the stuff we're talking about can be generalized to other asynchronous runtimes?

00:42:49.016 --> 00:42:51.372
A lot of this applies to other asynchronous runtimes as well.

00:42:52.894 --> 00:42:56.345
The exact nature of how they manage blocking,

00:42:56.987 --> 00:42:58.332
whether they do work stealing,

00:42:58.852 --> 00:43:01.844
whether they have pools and how large they are will vary,

00:43:02.005 --> 00:43:03.732
but many of the concepts translate.

00:43:12.090 --> 00:43:14.503
So the programmer needs to be aware of the functions that may block.

00:43:15.165 --> 00:43:18.164
Can we instrument the code to send off blocking calls to separate IO workers?

00:43:19.505 --> 00:43:19.705
Yeah,

00:43:20.006 --> 00:43:21.088
you can think of this as like,

00:43:23.492 --> 00:43:25.175
in asynchronous context,

00:43:25.455 --> 00:43:30.104
you should not be doing significant amounts of work without calling await.

00:43:31.433 --> 00:43:33.017
Like between any two await points,

00:43:33.278 --> 00:43:34.382
you should not be taking,

00:43:34.843 --> 00:43:35.084
you know,

00:43:35.184 --> 00:43:39.021
hundreds of milliseconds or many seconds before you call the next await,

00:43:39.282 --> 00:43:40.937
because chances are you're holding up the runtime.

00:43:41.488 --> 00:43:43.566
Detecting this automatically is super hard.

00:43:44.229 --> 00:43:45.956
I'm not going to claim it's impossible,

00:43:46.599 --> 00:43:49.671
but I haven't seen any sound strategies for doing it automatically,

00:43:50.536 --> 00:43:52.606
which means that it becomes a sort of manual task.

00:43:52.948 --> 00:43:56.084
There are tools like Tokyo Console will highlight when these kinds of things happen.

00:43:58.001 --> 00:44:01.314
But you still then manually need to figure out why and how to rectify.

00:44:08.118 --> 00:44:10.816
Doesn't it still need to be using an OS level asynchronous primitive in the end?

00:44:10.856 --> 00:44:11.138
Yeah,

00:44:11.178 --> 00:44:12.548
we'll talk about that when we get to resources.

00:44:25.975 --> 00:44:26.475
Okay.

00:44:30.469 --> 00:44:32.357
If a worker thread is blocked by synchronous code,

00:44:32.377 --> 00:44:34.244
wouldn't it be fine because we have other worker threads?

00:44:34.766 --> 00:44:36.319
It's fine until it's not,

00:44:36.803 --> 00:44:36.924
right?

00:44:36.964 --> 00:44:40.837
So if you have a bunch of futures or want many instances of a single future,

00:44:41.218 --> 00:44:43.024
all of which may block at some time,

00:44:43.624 --> 00:44:47.336
what is inevitably going to happen is you're going to get at some point in time,

00:44:47.777 --> 00:44:49.884
all of the worker threads are in the blocking section.

00:44:50.466 --> 00:44:52.284
And so there are no other worker threads anymore.

00:44:52.666 --> 00:44:56.024
So that only works if you generally don't run into the situation.

00:44:57.075 --> 00:44:57.256
But,

00:44:57.479 --> 00:44:57.701
but...

00:44:58.177 --> 00:45:00.526
You generally don't want to rely on that being the case,

00:45:00.526 --> 00:45:01.932
that there's always another thread.

00:45:05.466 --> 00:45:05.687
Okay,

00:45:06.510 --> 00:45:09.320
there are then three more things to talk about with the runtime.

00:45:09.360 --> 00:45:11.297
The runtime is the biggest segment of this,

00:45:11.317 --> 00:45:11.580
I think.

00:45:12.121 --> 00:45:14.940
The first of them is shutdown.

00:45:15.760 --> 00:45:17.584
So when you have a runtime,

00:45:19.468 --> 00:45:19.889
down here,

00:45:20.972 --> 00:45:21.974
when you have a runtime,

00:45:22.896 --> 00:45:30.339
the general rule is that whenever the future that is passed to block on resolves,

00:45:30.439 --> 00:45:30.740
finishes.

00:45:31.836 --> 00:45:34.328
Then the runtime yields control back to its caller.

00:45:34.649 --> 00:45:36.394
And like we saw in the expansion here,

00:45:37.356 --> 00:45:38.359
when you use Tokyo main,

00:45:38.419 --> 00:45:40.024
that means that when block on returns,

00:45:40.364 --> 00:45:41.648
the whole main function returns.

00:45:42.088 --> 00:45:42.757
And so at that point,

00:45:42.838 --> 00:45:43.628
the program exits.

00:45:44.028 --> 00:45:45.216
And when the program exits,

00:45:45.296 --> 00:45:47.028
the operating system shuts down all of the threads.

00:45:48.704 --> 00:45:50.491
That may or may not be what you want.

00:45:51.556 --> 00:45:53.904
This means that when the main future exits,

00:45:54.125 --> 00:45:55.590
everything else just gets dropped.

00:45:57.216 --> 00:46:07.064
There are ways to try to mitigate this by having the main thing that you do in the main future actually wait for,

00:46:07.446 --> 00:46:07.928
for example,

00:46:07.988 --> 00:46:11.056
all the join handles so you've gotten back from spawn.

00:46:11.056 --> 00:46:15.695
So that you make sure that you don't actually exit until all the things you spawned have finished.

00:46:16.441 --> 00:46:17.666
There are some tools that can help with this.

00:46:17.666 --> 00:46:20.356
We can talk about that later on when we talk about utilities.

00:46:21.237 --> 00:46:30.653
But you also have the means to shut down a runtime by using shutdown background or shutdown timeout,

00:46:30.693 --> 00:46:32.396
which lets you give a grace period as well.

00:46:33.698 --> 00:46:35.344
When you call shutdown background,

00:46:35.686 --> 00:46:37.995
what actually happens is that...

00:46:39.537 --> 00:46:42.304
the moment things that are spawned yield,

00:46:43.106 --> 00:46:44.270
they will then be dropped.

00:46:44.771 --> 00:46:50.091
So it won't immediately shut down because there might be futures that are still in the call to pull.

00:46:50.231 --> 00:46:53.602
But when the call to pull for every spawn future returns,

00:46:54.544 --> 00:46:59.359
that future or each future as it happens to them will then be dropped and not executed anymore,

00:46:59.761 --> 00:47:01.688
even if they haven't returned ready yet.

00:47:02.230 --> 00:47:04.571
And so the moment you call shutdown background,

00:47:05.327 --> 00:47:10.342
The number of tasks is just going to steadily decrease until eventually there are none left.

00:47:10.683 --> 00:47:11.526
And at that point,

00:47:12.028 --> 00:47:13.493
shutdown background will return saying,

00:47:13.513 --> 00:47:13.714
okay,

00:47:13.895 --> 00:47:14.999
there are no more futures now,

00:47:15.019 --> 00:47:15.902
you can safely shut down.

00:47:17.143 --> 00:47:21.021
This does mean that they are not guaranteed to run to completion,

00:47:21.061 --> 00:47:21.182
right?

00:47:21.202 --> 00:47:22.162
They will just be dropped.

00:47:22.242 --> 00:47:23.270
They will be canceled,

00:47:23.331 --> 00:47:24.742
like we'll talk about a little bit later.

00:47:28.064 --> 00:47:28.707
But these are,

00:47:28.707 --> 00:47:29.370
in some sense,

00:47:29.671 --> 00:47:31.198
a graceful way to shut down.

00:47:31.620 --> 00:47:33.871
If you instead just return from,

00:47:34.433 --> 00:47:35.418
so we had that here,

00:47:36.300 --> 00:47:40.738
if you instead just return when the main future returns or resolves,

00:47:41.239 --> 00:47:41.984
then at this point,

00:47:42.205 --> 00:47:43.452
after you finish main,

00:47:43.512 --> 00:47:44.438
after you return from main,

00:47:45.040 --> 00:47:47.358
all of the threads are just killed by the operating system.

00:47:47.839 --> 00:47:51.698
What that means is the drop method will not be called on the future,

00:47:51.778 --> 00:47:54.438
so they don't get a chance to clean up after themselves.

00:47:54.974 --> 00:47:56.059
That might not matter to you,

00:47:56.159 --> 00:47:57.344
but if it matters to you,

00:47:57.665 --> 00:48:08.730
chances are you want something like shutdown background as a call at the end of your main to make sure that you actually wait for the spawn task to also finish and at least get dropped.

00:48:11.813 --> 00:48:14.490
The next thing I want to talk about is send bounds.

00:48:14.931 --> 00:48:15.051
So

00:48:15.713 --> 00:48:22.770
Tokyo does have a way to run futures that aren't sent.

00:48:23.750 --> 00:48:27.262
So these are things where once you start executing them on a given thread,

00:48:27.604 --> 00:48:29.505
you are not allowed to move them to another thread.

00:48:29.586 --> 00:48:29.807
In fact,

00:48:30.510 --> 00:48:31.856
once you've constructed them,

00:48:32.157 --> 00:48:33.684
you're not allowed to move them to another thread.

00:48:34.126 --> 00:48:37.344
This obviously sort of doesn't really work with work stealing,

00:48:37.404 --> 00:48:37.585
right?

00:48:37.766 --> 00:48:42.104
Because work stealing assumes that you can move threads to another task.

00:48:42.606 --> 00:48:44.654
So Tokyo has this type called a local set,

00:48:45.276 --> 00:48:50.478
and a local set is a set of tasks that are all guaranteed to be executed on the same thread.

00:48:51.928 --> 00:49:01.606
So the idea here is that you create a local set and then you can spawn things using the spawn local method onto the local set.

00:49:01.948 --> 00:49:04.186
And that adds the future to this local set.

00:49:05.068 --> 00:49:05.410
But again,

00:49:05.410 --> 00:49:06.577
the local set does not send.

00:49:06.617 --> 00:49:08.166
It's guaranteed to not move between threads.

00:49:08.526 --> 00:49:12.886
So these spawn locals creates additional top level tasks for the local set.

00:49:13.348 --> 00:49:15.606
And then you can await the local set at the end.

00:49:16.228 --> 00:49:20.806
And that will run all of the futures that have been spawned on that local set.

00:49:21.137 --> 00:49:23.130
until they all resolve.

00:49:24.033 --> 00:49:27.430
The trick with local set though is that it cannot be used anywhere.

00:49:28.032 --> 00:49:31.770
You can't just like arbitrarily use them somewhere deep down in a future somewhere.

00:49:32.213 --> 00:49:36.309
And the reason to that is if you can start the local set deep down in a future stack,

00:49:36.670 --> 00:49:38.750
Tokyo doesn't know that there's a local set there.

00:49:39.190 --> 00:49:40.830
So like when it calls,

00:49:40.970 --> 00:49:43.870
when all it sees again are the tasks at the top level.

00:49:44.437 --> 00:49:45.090
So up there,

00:49:45.291 --> 00:49:49.930
it doesn't know that this thing can't be moved between threads because that would move the inner local set.

00:49:50.545 --> 00:49:53.976
And so local set can only be used in top-level tasks.

00:49:54.337 --> 00:50:11.853
It can only be used as you'll see here on it passed to block on or yeah so remember Tokyo main basically ends up calling block on right so here we're allowed to use the local set because we are in a block on

00:50:14.090 --> 00:50:18.906
You can also use this run until which is sort of a block on on a local set but let's ignore that for now.

00:50:19.606 --> 00:50:30.266
So you can just await this inside of a block on and if you need to be able to use it somewhere else what you actually need to do is you need to spawn your own thread that owns the local set.

00:50:30.747 --> 00:50:38.366
And it locally executes with its own current thread runtime and then you send tasks to it over a channel.

00:50:39.429 --> 00:50:40.432
It's a little awkward,

00:50:40.673 --> 00:50:47.815
but again it is because it needs to be known at the very top level that this task is not safe to move between threads.

00:50:50.606 --> 00:50:52.214
If you truly need something like this,

00:50:52.254 --> 00:50:53.722
if you need non-send futures,

00:50:54.024 --> 00:51:00.115
I recommend you read the docs for local set because there are a bunch of nuances here that we don't quite have time to go into.

00:51:01.686 --> 00:51:03.644
But know that this mechanism does exist.

00:51:05.589 --> 00:51:08.042
And then the last thing that I want to talk about when it comes to the runtime,

00:51:08.462 --> 00:51:10.730
and then I'll do questions after this last one,

00:51:11.051 --> 00:51:16.549
is the difference between a Tokyo mutex and a standard library mutex.

00:51:17.131 --> 00:51:17.251
So,

00:51:17.552 --> 00:51:18.214
and again,

00:51:18.435 --> 00:51:21.685
here you see there is a giant section that talks about this in the docs,

00:51:22.307 --> 00:51:25.137
but the standard library has a standard sync mutex,

00:51:25.538 --> 00:51:26.622
and Tokyo has its own

00:51:27.004 --> 00:51:28.029
Tokyo sync mutex.

00:51:28.390 --> 00:51:28.933
And you might wonder,

00:51:29.034 --> 00:51:29.174
well,

00:51:29.255 --> 00:51:30.059
why do we have both?

00:51:30.099 --> 00:51:30.682
Why do they differ?

00:51:31.207 --> 00:51:31.368
Well,

00:51:31.590 --> 00:51:32.519
the Tokyo mutex...

00:51:33.461 --> 00:51:41.824
The sort of main difference at a high level is that the lock methods on the Tokyo mutex are asynchronous,

00:51:41.984 --> 00:51:42.165
right?

00:51:42.185 --> 00:51:43.009
So if you call lock,

00:51:43.049 --> 00:51:43.973
you then call dot await.

00:51:44.455 --> 00:51:44.635
Great.

00:51:44.916 --> 00:51:45.941
That seems straightforward.

00:51:46.242 --> 00:51:47.287
And so you might then assume,

00:51:47.367 --> 00:51:47.548
okay,

00:51:47.568 --> 00:51:49.758
I should just use Tokyo mutexes everywhere.

00:51:52.033 --> 00:51:53.561
That's not quite true.

00:51:54.024 --> 00:51:58.621
And this ties back to the nature of how these runtimes work and the nature of blocking.

00:51:59.284 --> 00:52:02.915
So when you take a standard library mutex,

00:52:04.018 --> 00:52:06.285
what you're doing is you might block the current thread,

00:52:06.285 --> 00:52:10.773
but let's assume that like this mutex is only held for a short period of time in general.

00:52:11.344 --> 00:52:13.252
So you take the mutex,

00:52:13.775 --> 00:52:16.476
it doesn't really block the thread because you got the mutex right away.

00:52:16.884 --> 00:52:18.722
So you do a work and then you release the mutex.

00:52:19.748 --> 00:52:21.313
There's not really a lot of risk there,

00:52:21.715 --> 00:52:27.658
because as long as your critical section is not very long and as long as your mutex is not very contended,

00:52:27.678 --> 00:52:28.763
so you never wait like,

00:52:29.004 --> 00:52:29.205
you know,

00:52:29.205 --> 00:52:30.731
a second for it to become available,

00:52:31.495 --> 00:52:32.640
that works fine,

00:52:32.981 --> 00:52:33.202
right?

00:52:33.665 --> 00:52:36.920
The fact that this is using a synchronization primitive at the OS level,

00:52:37.362 --> 00:52:38.598
Tokyo doesn't really care.

00:52:38.925 --> 00:52:40.453
It just cares how much time you spent in there,

00:52:40.654 --> 00:52:43.090
how much time you spent holding up that runtime thread,

00:52:43.131 --> 00:52:43.882
that worker thread.

00:52:44.693 --> 00:52:48.948
And it turns out that a standard library mutex is actually really efficient.

00:52:49.990 --> 00:52:52.015
Like just performance-wise,

00:52:55.964 --> 00:52:57.789
it is an efficient synchronization mechanism.

00:52:58.310 --> 00:52:59.293
The Tokyo mutex,

00:52:59.654 --> 00:53:03.243
in order to make lock and unlock asynchronous,

00:53:03.584 --> 00:53:05.149
is actually fairly inefficient.

00:53:05.969 --> 00:53:08.176
And so when you can use a standard library mutex,

00:53:08.497 --> 00:53:11.909
you probably should because it has lower overhead than the Tokyo one.

00:53:13.172 --> 00:53:18.988
Where this gets subtle and the reason why Tokyo provides its own mutex is not just because it's nice to be able to call lock.await,

00:53:19.430 --> 00:53:25.788
but it is because if it might take a long time for you to get access to the mutex to lock the mutex,

00:53:26.390 --> 00:53:28.699
then you're holding up the worker thread,

00:53:28.960 --> 00:53:29.723
that's not okay,

00:53:29.804 --> 00:53:31.008
so you need to use a Tokyo mutex.

00:53:31.911 --> 00:53:37.744
Or if you take the lock and then you call await on something before you unlock.

00:53:38.679 --> 00:53:38.980
Because,

00:53:39.441 --> 00:53:41.406
so the way this would actually look is,

00:53:41.948 --> 00:53:42.850
imagine in here,

00:53:44.053 --> 00:53:44.273
right,

00:53:44.674 --> 00:53:52.654
I do something like mutex.lock.await.

00:53:53.677 --> 00:53:54.745
So that gives me back a guard.

00:53:56.237 --> 00:53:57.327
That's not how you spell guard.

00:53:58.397 --> 00:54:02.327
And then I do some func.await,

00:54:03.329 --> 00:54:04.733
and then I drop the guard.

00:54:08.811 --> 00:54:09.011
Right?

00:54:09.572 --> 00:54:10.374
If I do this,

00:54:11.095 --> 00:54:17.808
the problem you run into is that some function here could take an arbitrarily long amount of time.

00:54:18.770 --> 00:54:20.318
Maybe it tries to read from standard in.

00:54:20.419 --> 00:54:22.229
Maybe it tries to wait for a TCP packet.

00:54:22.629 --> 00:54:26.205
Maybe it tries to send a TCP packet to a peer that's disconnected.

00:54:26.225 --> 00:54:26.948
Whatever it might be.

00:54:27.370 --> 00:54:29.589
This can take an arbitrary amount of time.

00:54:31.110 --> 00:54:32.135
What that means is,

00:54:32.356 --> 00:54:34.567
now that you hold the lock...

00:54:35.299 --> 00:54:35.442
Um...

00:54:36.390 --> 00:54:38.836
For the period that this blocks,

00:54:39.297 --> 00:54:44.108
what will happen is that you're holding up.

00:54:44.869 --> 00:54:50.677
So if this was not a Tokyo mutex,

00:54:50.697 --> 00:54:51.839
if it was a standard library mutex,

00:54:52.359 --> 00:54:53.821
then during this time,

00:54:53.821 --> 00:54:54.983
you're still holding the mutex,

00:54:55.744 --> 00:54:59.349
even though you've yielded and you're trying to now execute other tasks.

00:54:59.709 --> 00:55:03.968
Imagine that there's another task on this runtime that now tries to call mutex lock.

00:55:04.555 --> 00:55:05.547
It will now be blocked.

00:55:05.890 --> 00:55:06.333
forever,

00:55:06.574 --> 00:55:08.524
or at least until this await call returns,

00:55:09.126 --> 00:55:12.364
because it can't get the lock because it's held up by this await call.

00:55:12.967 --> 00:55:14.204
And it actually gets even worse than that,

00:55:14.305 --> 00:55:17.344
which is that a mutex guard in the standard library is not send.

00:55:18.147 --> 00:55:19.864
But if you're holding it across an await point,

00:55:20.246 --> 00:55:27.269
that means that this entire future is not send because it might need to hold on to that guard until this await comes back because who knows,

00:55:27.269 --> 00:55:30.344
we might do guard.foo equals 42 down here.

00:55:31.030 --> 00:55:34.116
So during the await call it needs to hold on to the guard in here,

00:55:34.517 --> 00:55:37.021
and guard from the standard library is not send,

00:55:37.262 --> 00:55:39.165
and therefore this whole future is not send,

00:55:39.366 --> 00:55:40.728
and therefore you can't use it with Tokyo.

00:55:42.331 --> 00:55:51.768
And so there's some really tricky situations that come up the moment you have await calls inside or during which you're holding a standard library lock.

00:55:52.996 --> 00:55:54.949
The Tokyo mutex does not have this problem.

00:55:55.729 --> 00:55:57.779
The Tokyo mutex guard that you get back,

00:55:57.819 --> 00:55:58.201
first of all,

00:55:58.321 --> 00:55:58.964
is send.

00:55:59.425 --> 00:56:01.171
So if you hold it across an await point,

00:56:01.472 --> 00:56:04.040
then it's fine because the mutex guard is send,

00:56:04.261 --> 00:56:05.464
and so the future remains send.

00:56:06.221 --> 00:56:09.336
But the other reason is because when you call await here,

00:56:09.977 --> 00:56:15.636
Tokyo knows that this future is actually holding onto that mutex.

00:56:16.121 --> 00:56:22.071
And so if another task comes along and tries to lock that same mutex and it calls await,

00:56:22.555 --> 00:56:22.696
right?

00:56:23.197 --> 00:56:23.438
Then

00:56:23.921 --> 00:56:24.745
Tokyo knows,

00:56:24.986 --> 00:56:25.107
oh,

00:56:25.127 --> 00:56:28.257
I should put this task to sleep and pick up something else instead.

00:56:28.759 --> 00:56:29.728
Instead of,

00:56:30.092 --> 00:56:30.596
in this case,

00:56:30.697 --> 00:56:35.257
where it will block that worker thread and therefore block any other tasks that might be executing.

00:56:36.516 --> 00:56:37.077
So the rule,

00:56:37.138 --> 00:56:43.256
the general rule here is that use a standard library mutex if you have short critical sections,

00:56:43.598 --> 00:56:49.108
like the stuff you do while holding the lock is short and there are no awaits in the critical section.

00:56:49.613 --> 00:56:50.476
For anything else,

00:56:50.858 --> 00:56:51.682
use the Tokyo mutex.

00:56:55.398 --> 00:56:55.619
Okay,

00:56:56.082 --> 00:56:58.272
I think those are all the things I wanted to say about the runtimes.

00:56:58.433 --> 00:57:01.492
Let's do questions about the runtime before I move on to IOResources.

00:57:07.028 --> 00:57:07.149
Um...

00:57:11.097 --> 00:57:16.438
Might it make sense to have two separate Tokio runtimes and spawn tasks of those runtimes to increase performance,

00:57:16.699 --> 00:57:18.953
assuming we assign separate CPUs to those runtimes?

00:57:20.068 --> 00:57:23.464
it usually should not make sense to have two separate Tokio runtimes.

00:57:24.005 --> 00:57:27.664
Usually you're better off just allowing work stealing across your entire task pool.

00:57:28.228 --> 00:57:29.584
There are some exceptions to this.

00:57:29.665 --> 00:57:30.227
So for example,

00:57:30.588 --> 00:57:36.964
if you have an application where you have some tasks that are all very similar to each other and some other tasks that are all very similar to each other,

00:57:37.485 --> 00:57:40.564
you might get enough and the performance requirements are strict enough,

00:57:40.986 --> 00:57:48.984
you might get some benefit from having one task pool that only runs futures of a certain type and another one that only runs futures of a different type.

00:57:49.390 --> 00:57:52.182
so that you get better cache performance on your CPUs.

00:57:53.110 --> 00:57:54.262
But this is one of those like,

00:57:54.585 --> 00:58:00.662
you should be damn sure with performance benchmarks and profiling that that is actually worth the complexity.

00:58:01.225 --> 00:58:03.084
Because once you manage multiple runtimes,

00:58:03.205 --> 00:58:05.222
it's really easy to shoot yourself in the foot.

00:58:07.325 --> 00:58:09.503
So I would very much default to just having one.

00:58:18.557 --> 00:58:22.692
Why do they not use implicit return in the Tokyo main macro when you expand it?

00:58:23.696 --> 00:58:24.021
You know,

00:58:24.366 --> 00:58:24.772
I don't know.

00:58:27.075 --> 00:58:29.992
I don't know why they don't use an implicit return here.

00:58:32.776 --> 00:58:34.392
I don't think there's a great reason for it.

00:58:37.495 --> 00:58:40.413
Is local set slower than regular tasks in the current thread runtime?

00:58:40.954 --> 00:58:41.075
No,

00:58:41.256 --> 00:58:42.823
local set does not,

00:58:42.883 --> 00:58:43.727
as far as I'm aware,

00:58:43.788 --> 00:58:44.812
come with a performance penalty.

00:58:48.651 --> 00:58:51.184
When sending through channels you probably need fuchsias to be sent anyway.

00:58:51.325 --> 00:58:54.742
This is for local set if you want to sort of spawn it on a separate thread.

00:58:55.145 --> 00:59:03.707
The idea here is that there are cases where you can make the description of what to do be sent,

00:59:04.229 --> 00:59:07.843
but have the execution of that thing not be sent.

00:59:08.325 --> 00:59:10.972
And then you should be able to still use this channel and local set trick.

00:59:15.165 --> 00:59:15.461
And that's it.

00:59:23.231 --> 00:59:25.984
I've heard the term green thread but never fully understood it.

00:59:26.065 --> 00:59:28.022
Is it just a task in a task queue slash event loop?

00:59:28.425 --> 00:59:28.586
Yeah,

00:59:28.646 --> 00:59:31.821
you can think of a green thread here as basically being equivalent to a task,

00:59:32.223 --> 00:59:33.528
the way I've described it so far.

00:59:41.457 --> 00:59:48.172
Are there any tools you can use to discover or visualize how often your async tasks are being blocked and if your CPU bond tasks should be awaiting more?

00:59:48.633 --> 00:59:48.774
Yeah,

00:59:48.794 --> 00:59:50.993
so that is the tool called Tokyo Console.

00:59:52.194 --> 00:59:54.402
So if you look up Tokyo Console,

00:59:56.029 --> 00:59:56.952
this thing right here.

00:59:59.200 --> 01:00:08.036
It has this view under extremely cool and amazing screenshots that shows you for all of the tasks that Tokyo knows about,

01:00:08.277 --> 01:00:09.741
how much time has been spent busy,

01:00:10.743 --> 01:00:13.069
how much time they've been spent sort of scheduling,

01:00:13.670 --> 01:00:14.853
how much time has been idle,

01:00:14.853 --> 01:00:16.176
how many times have they been pulled.

01:00:16.797 --> 01:00:22.776
And it also has information about tasks that have been that are blocking the runtime for a longer period of time.

01:00:23.037 --> 01:00:24.936
And it shows these little warning icons for those.

01:00:25.463 --> 01:00:26.496
So that's a great.

01:00:26.804 --> 01:00:29.431
Great tool for learning this information about Tokyo.

01:00:32.561 --> 01:00:34.641
Do IO resources include TokyoFS?

01:00:34.862 --> 01:00:35.447
Yes it does.

01:00:37.201 --> 01:00:40.339
Is the Tokyo lock guard dropped when another await is called in the future?

01:00:41.396 --> 01:00:41.620
No.

01:00:41.641 --> 01:00:42.813
In fact it would be unsafe to do so.

01:00:43.461 --> 01:00:53.736
So if you had guard is mutex.lock.await something.await drop guard.

01:00:55.618 --> 01:00:58.544
If this await caused this guard to be dropped,

01:00:58.885 --> 01:01:01.912
that would mean you release the lock and then call this thing.

01:01:02.474 --> 01:01:04.351
But that's not the semantics of this code,

01:01:04.391 --> 01:01:04.532
right?

01:01:04.813 --> 01:01:08.232
The implication here is the lock is held during this entire call.

01:01:09.013 --> 01:01:13.013
And so it's not okay for Tokyo to drop this guard sort of implicitly just because you're waiting.

01:01:27.121 --> 01:01:29.428
When using a single-threaded runtime and spawn blocking,

01:01:29.428 --> 01:01:30.832
it still spawns a separate OS thread.

01:01:31.253 --> 01:01:31.414
Yeah,

01:01:31.454 --> 01:01:34.513
so spawn blocking will always happen on a separate thread.

01:01:35.033 --> 01:01:40.372
I forget whether with the current thread runtime there even is a blocking pool.

01:01:41.013 --> 01:01:42.159
I think there is,

01:01:43.505 --> 01:01:44.128
but I'm not sure.

01:01:44.148 --> 01:01:45.072
You would have to double-check that.

01:01:46.035 --> 01:01:47.566
There are no task priorities in Tokyo,

01:01:47.626 --> 01:01:48.432
so you can't say,

01:01:49.093 --> 01:01:50.925
this task is more important than this task,

01:01:50.925 --> 01:01:52.012
so schedule it more regularly.

01:01:52.695 --> 01:01:54.312
That's not a feature that Tokyo currently has.

01:01:57.484 --> 01:02:00.856
Can a worker thread steal from a currently blocked other worker thread?

01:02:01.543 --> 01:02:02.277
It's complicated.

01:02:02.557 --> 01:02:05.377
So if a worker thread is currently blocked,

01:02:05.497 --> 01:02:08.936
because the future called some kind of blocking system call,

01:02:09.977 --> 01:02:12.916
the queue of that worker can still be stolen from,

01:02:13.537 --> 01:02:15.048
but the currently executed task,

01:02:15.068 --> 01:02:16.197
the one that is blocked,

01:02:16.737 --> 01:02:20.536
cannot be stolen because it's currently active in that worker thread.

01:02:21.022 --> 01:02:22.317
There are also some other things that are...

01:02:23.183 --> 01:02:24.786
I don't want to say hard to steal,

01:02:25.167 --> 01:02:31.540
but there's some optimizations that mean certain other tasks may also not be stealable.

01:02:40.864 --> 01:02:41.167
Nope,

01:02:41.167 --> 01:02:42.380
I have not switched to Emacs.

01:02:44.717 --> 01:02:48.974
Can there be a deadlock or similar if you share the same task between multiple runtimes?

01:02:49.296 --> 01:02:51.203
You cannot share a task between runtimes.

01:02:51.464 --> 01:02:55.038
So a task fundamentally is a single instance of the future trait.

01:02:55.901 --> 01:02:57.467
And so there's no way to share that,

01:02:57.627 --> 01:02:57.828
right?

01:02:58.229 --> 01:02:59.113
Whoever owns it,

01:02:59.133 --> 01:03:00.217
whichever runtime owns it,

01:03:00.337 --> 01:03:01.703
is the one that will be executing it.

01:03:02.325 --> 01:03:05.538
So there's no way for one task to be handled by multiple runtimes.

01:03:06.421 --> 01:03:07.865
If you do have multiple runtimes,

01:03:08.306 --> 01:03:13.257
you could get into a deadlock situation between the tasks of the two runtimes.

01:03:13.932 --> 01:03:15.100
But that's sort of a different concern.

01:03:17.983 --> 01:03:20.940
Since Tokyo shares the work across threads and the futures need to be sent,

01:03:21.081 --> 01:03:23.481
does this have overhead every time a future is shared across threads?

01:03:23.982 --> 01:03:35.021
There's no real overhead of futures being work stealable because Tokyo will generally avoid stealing futures unless specifically a core is running out of,

01:03:35.302 --> 01:03:40.080
one worker thread is running out of work and another worker thread has too much work for it.

01:03:40.357 --> 01:03:40.919
And in that case,

01:03:41.120 --> 01:03:42.506
you would rather it be executed,

01:03:42.607 --> 01:03:44.033
even if it's with a little bit of overhead,

01:03:44.354 --> 01:03:47.873
than just have one thread execute and the other one just sit idle and do nothing.

01:03:48.193 --> 01:03:49.719
So usually it's worth it,

01:03:50.060 --> 01:03:53.112
even though there is a small overhead when you choose to steal.

01:03:59.216 --> 01:04:02.613
Is there a way to shut down Tokyo Runtime and wait for all current pending tasks?

01:04:03.413 --> 01:04:04.779
Not to my knowledge,

01:04:05.643 --> 01:04:07.852
but the way you do this is you implement this yourself.

01:04:08.655 --> 01:04:11.012
And we'll talk about some of the ways in which you can do that.

01:04:11.113 --> 01:04:13.589
There are some utilities in Tokyo Util,

01:04:13.650 --> 01:04:14.053
for example,

01:04:14.153 --> 01:04:16.492
which is a separate crate that helps you do this kind of stuff.

01:04:21.095 --> 01:04:22.872
Is parking lock mutex faster than stood mutex?

01:04:23.093 --> 01:04:26.592
I'll leave that for a separate conversation because it doesn't have to do with async.

01:04:27.178 --> 01:04:27.684
Um...

01:04:30.780 --> 01:04:32.463
What are the advantages of using the local set?

01:04:32.584 --> 01:04:34.147
It's that it allows non-send futures.

01:04:39.517 --> 01:04:42.514
What's the difference between Tokyo's instant now and the standard library instant now?

01:04:43.117 --> 01:04:44.862
They're the same instant type so there's no difference.

01:04:49.577 --> 01:04:50.240
I got your email,

01:04:50.260 --> 01:04:50.903
I've just been busy.

01:04:56.904 --> 01:04:58.836
Can you use Tokio resources with a different runtime?

01:04:58.877 --> 01:05:00.173
We'll talk about that when we get to resources.

01:05:01.427 --> 01:05:02.033
Um...

01:05:09.679 --> 01:05:11.295
Okay...

01:05:12.502 --> 01:05:12.622
Yeah,

01:05:12.662 --> 01:05:18.251
so if you're running on particularly newer machines that have large numbers of CPU cores,

01:05:18.672 --> 01:05:23.540
the CPU cores might physically be located far from each other on what these things are known as NUMA nodes.

01:05:24.641 --> 01:05:29.394
And stealing across NUMA node boundaries can actually be quite expensive,

01:05:29.795 --> 01:05:32.020
much more expensive than it being worth it.

01:05:32.723 --> 01:05:33.125
And again,

01:05:33.427 --> 01:05:36.440
Tokyo tries really hard to not steal unless it's necessary.

01:05:37.563 --> 01:05:41.401
But there might be an outsized cost on these high CPU core count machines.

01:05:41.988 --> 01:05:42.711
for stealing.

01:05:43.554 --> 01:05:46.504
There isn't a NUMA-aware scheduler in Tokyo at the moment,

01:05:47.126 --> 01:05:50.884
but that is something that I'm guessing Tokyo will probably grow over time.

01:05:54.669 --> 01:05:56.084
Tokyo does not have its own instant type.

01:05:59.805 --> 01:06:00.267
Great.

01:06:01.110 --> 01:06:01.331
Okay,

01:06:02.436 --> 01:06:04.625
I think it's time to move on to resources.

01:06:06.280 --> 01:06:06.400
So,

01:06:06.962 --> 01:06:08.827
we've talked now about the runtime,

01:06:09.769 --> 01:06:12.316
but the runtime is just about executing futures,

01:06:12.397 --> 01:06:14.311
like calling the poll function and nothing else.

01:06:14.957 --> 01:06:15.518
In reality,

01:06:15.900 --> 01:06:20.596
you generally want these futures that you spawn to interact with the real world.

01:06:20.697 --> 01:06:21.547
You want them to do I.O.

01:06:22.297 --> 01:06:22.766
Things like...

01:06:24.620 --> 01:06:25.182
Okay,

01:06:25.643 --> 01:06:25.763
wait,

01:06:25.883 --> 01:06:28.851
someone is insisting that Tokio has its own instant type.

01:06:30.737 --> 01:06:31.933
It is just a standard time instant.

01:06:32.177 --> 01:06:32.789
There is no difference.

01:06:33.785 --> 01:06:34.227
So yeah,

01:06:34.428 --> 01:06:34.810
you're right.

01:06:34.930 --> 01:06:36.196
They do have their own instant type,

01:06:36.437 --> 01:06:38.645
but it's just the standard library instant type.

01:06:39.126 --> 01:06:39.969
I believe,

01:06:40.129 --> 01:06:40.270
yeah,

01:06:40.330 --> 01:06:40.992
so here,

01:06:41.393 --> 01:06:42.978
if you look at the note,

01:06:43.058 --> 01:06:43.740
that explains why.

01:06:46.869 --> 01:06:47.090
Okay,

01:06:47.751 --> 01:06:47.872
so

01:06:48.293 --> 01:06:52.403
Tokio has these resources that are intended for interacting with I.O.

01:06:52.925 --> 01:06:54.288
This is stuff like TCP and UDP,

01:06:55.090 --> 01:06:55.792
file system,

01:06:56.273 --> 01:06:57.456
other processes,

01:06:58.319 --> 01:06:59.482
signal handlers,

01:07:00.123 --> 01:07:01.459
all of that kind of stuff.

01:07:02.106 --> 01:07:05.319
I'm not really counting synchronization primitives like channels here,

01:07:05.339 --> 01:07:07.491
but they are in some sense resources as well.

01:07:09.365 --> 01:07:09.648
And the-

01:07:11.203 --> 01:07:16.355
The way to think about these is that these are provided by Tokyo because if you,

01:07:16.436 --> 01:07:18.039
let's say you have a TCP stream,

01:07:18.380 --> 01:07:18.501
right?

01:07:18.501 --> 01:07:19.980
And you want to read from a TCP stream.

01:07:22.207 --> 01:07:25.039
So you have one of these and you want to call...

01:07:27.354 --> 01:07:28.139
Where is...

01:07:31.378 --> 01:07:31.899
AsyncRead.

01:07:32.139 --> 01:07:40.856
So asyncRead is the sort of underlying trait that Tokio uses for things that can be read from in an asynchronous context.

01:07:41.277 --> 01:07:44.726
So you have a poll read that reads stuff out of,

01:07:44.906 --> 01:07:45.147
you know,

01:07:45.167 --> 01:07:46.169
whatever type implements it,

01:07:46.189 --> 01:07:47.011
like TCP stream,

01:07:47.433 --> 01:07:48.575
into a provided buffer,

01:07:48.896 --> 01:07:50.477
and then returns poll to either say,

01:07:50.838 --> 01:07:51.038
okay,

01:07:51.078 --> 01:07:52.439
I successfully read a bunch of bytes,

01:07:52.659 --> 01:07:54.401
or it returns pending saying,

01:07:54.942 --> 01:07:55.062
oh,

01:07:55.342 --> 01:07:56.303
I tried to read some bytes,

01:07:56.383 --> 01:07:56.543
but...

01:07:56.881 --> 01:07:58.112
there weren't any bytes available.

01:07:58.592 --> 01:07:58.813
And so,

01:07:59.176 --> 01:07:59.418
you know,

01:07:59.559 --> 01:08:01.092
yield in this future and come back later.

01:08:02.367 --> 01:08:03.150
And ultimately,

01:08:03.491 --> 01:08:07.303
if you think about the sort of stacks of futures that make up a task,

01:08:07.824 --> 01:08:12.304
generally near the bottom is where you're going to have these resources that ultimately,

01:08:13.446 --> 01:08:14.710
some giant future,

01:08:14.851 --> 01:08:16.256
whatever its construction might be,

01:08:16.638 --> 01:08:19.788
at the bottom you have things like read from a socket,

01:08:20.169 --> 01:08:21.213
write to a socket,

01:08:21.293 --> 01:08:22.316
read from a file,

01:08:22.376 --> 01:08:23.359
write to a file,

01:08:23.680 --> 01:08:24.703
read from standard in,

01:08:25.224 --> 01:08:26.066
write to standard in,

01:08:26.448 --> 01:08:27.692
or wait for a timer.

01:08:28.174 --> 01:08:30.964
So you have these resources all the way at the bottom.

01:08:30.964 --> 01:08:31.094
So

01:08:31.481 --> 01:08:31.903
that are in,

01:08:32.164 --> 01:08:34.113
they're not actually futures,

01:08:34.495 --> 01:08:34.636
right?

01:08:34.696 --> 01:08:40.193
They are things like async read that have a future compatible interface,

01:08:40.515 --> 01:08:40.656
right?

01:08:40.736 --> 01:08:42.415
So they have a poll method,

01:08:43.519 --> 01:08:46.255
they're given asynchronous context and they return poll,

01:08:46.656 --> 01:08:49.016
but they do not themselves contain futures.

01:08:49.678 --> 01:08:51.116
And all of these leaf resources,

01:08:51.296 --> 01:08:58.695
these leaf future-like things or asynchronous primitives are provided by Tokyo.

01:08:59.606 --> 01:09:03.658
And the reason for this is because whenever a future is blocked,

01:09:04.340 --> 01:09:04.521
sorry,

01:09:04.922 --> 01:09:05.423
I should say,

01:09:05.704 --> 01:09:07.371
whenever a future is pending,

01:09:07.411 --> 01:09:08.134
it's yielded,

01:09:08.515 --> 01:09:10.383
it claims that it can't do any more work,

01:09:10.925 --> 01:09:15.984
then that is usually because one of these resource level calls returned pending.

01:09:16.664 --> 01:09:20.563
That is the ultimate reason why the future can't make any more progress.

01:09:21.085 --> 01:09:28.344
And that also means that the way in which it can start to make progress again is if one of those resources suddenly becomes available.

01:09:28.767 --> 01:09:28.987
Like,

01:09:29.248 --> 01:09:34.223
you did a read from a TCP socket and now there is data available on that socket.

01:09:34.424 --> 01:09:36.921
Or you tried to read from standard in and now there is data available.

01:09:37.344 --> 01:09:40.616
Or you tried to wait on a timer and now that timer has expired,

01:09:40.636 --> 01:09:41.741
like that time has passed.

01:09:42.484 --> 01:09:51.862
Or you were waiting for a process to finish executing and now that process has finished executing.

01:09:52.490 --> 01:09:53.632
And those things,

01:09:53.973 --> 01:09:56.398
those events that indicate that,

01:09:56.418 --> 01:09:56.618
okay,

01:09:56.979 --> 01:09:59.224
now you should try this future again,

01:10:00.466 --> 01:10:00.707
is...

01:10:02.070 --> 01:10:10.212
the connection between these IO resources and the future traits that happens through this context thing.

01:10:10.674 --> 01:10:13.243
And you'll see this concept argument is in async read.

01:10:13.545 --> 01:10:17.623
It's also in all of the low-level resource primitives that have these poll-like calls,

01:10:17.704 --> 01:10:19.089
but aren't themselves futures.

01:10:19.671 --> 01:10:21.456
It's also passed to future,

01:10:21.756 --> 01:10:21.897
right?

01:10:21.897 --> 01:10:25.787
So the top-level call to poll on any given task,

01:10:26.049 --> 01:10:27.094
so on any given future,

01:10:27.536 --> 01:10:28.582
is given a context.

01:10:28.582 --> 01:10:29.917
And that context is passed over.

01:10:30.190 --> 01:10:32.704
all the way down the chain of futures.

01:10:33.164 --> 01:10:35.004
And this mostly happens without you thinking about it.

01:10:35.044 --> 01:10:36.922
So when you call.await,

01:10:37.845 --> 01:10:40.823
it de-sugars to get the current context,

01:10:41.044 --> 01:10:42.063
pass that into poll,

01:10:42.464 --> 01:10:45.903
and then it gets threaded all the way down on your behalf,

01:10:46.524 --> 01:10:52.143
which means that the context to get passed in at the top to a task is the same thing that makes it down to the resource at the bottom.

01:10:53.485 --> 01:10:55.203
And context is defined in the standard library,

01:10:55.545 --> 01:10:58.723
and the main thing that a context has is this waker thing.

01:10:59.627 --> 01:11:04.962
And a waker only has one real method that matters,

01:11:05.022 --> 01:11:05.583
which is wake.

01:11:06.325 --> 01:11:08.784
So a waker gets passed all the way down to the resource.

01:11:09.224 --> 01:11:13.533
And the idea is when a future returns pending,

01:11:13.774 --> 01:11:15.517
so the whole task becomes pending,

01:11:15.918 --> 01:11:18.223
it's moved to the sort of non-runnable queue.

01:11:19.173 --> 01:11:23.921
And when the waker that was passed into that future,

01:11:24.161 --> 01:11:25.323
when it returns pending,

01:11:25.824 --> 01:11:27.807
when someone calls wake on it,

01:11:28.267 --> 01:11:30.951
that means this future might be able to make progress again.

01:11:31.392 --> 01:11:40.931
And so this is a signal to Tokyo that this future should be moved from the non-runnable queue into the runnable queue and then get picked up by a worker pool thread again.

01:11:41.972 --> 01:11:42.618
And so you might wonder,

01:11:42.679 --> 01:11:42.841
well,

01:11:43.123 --> 01:11:43.911
who calls wake?

01:11:44.556 --> 01:11:45.302
And this is where,

01:11:45.323 --> 01:11:46.432
when we looked at runtime.

01:11:47.929 --> 01:11:51.903
you'll see up here that runtime has this IO event loop.

01:11:52.265 --> 01:11:54.043
And this is separate from the scheduler.

01:11:54.387 --> 01:11:55.863
The IO event loop and the scheduler,

01:11:56.104 --> 01:11:57.864
they don't run on different threads necessarily,

01:11:58.064 --> 01:12:02.684
but they're sort of distinct components or services that are provided by the runtime.

01:12:03.044 --> 01:12:04.723
The scheduler chooses what to pick up next.

01:12:05.044 --> 01:12:13.544
And the IO event loop is looking for these events that might mean that some task can make progress and then calling wake on the appropriate waker.

01:12:14.263 --> 01:12:17.352
If we take an example of something that ultimately reads from a TCP stream,

01:12:17.934 --> 01:12:18.456
the context,

01:12:19.097 --> 01:12:22.476
the pull method gets called by the Tokyo runtime scheduler.

01:12:23.040 --> 01:12:25.696
It passes in the context that represents the current task.

01:12:26.340 --> 01:12:30.896
It's passed all the way down to the async read call on the TCP stream.

01:12:31.780 --> 01:12:35.090
That tries to read from the socket and gets told there's no more data.

01:12:36.099 --> 01:12:38.346
What it will do is then internally in Tokyo,

01:12:38.467 --> 01:12:39.410
internally in the

01:12:39.891 --> 01:12:41.195
TCP stream type,

01:12:41.677 --> 01:12:46.131
it'll take the waker in the context that was given into Paul Reed,

01:12:46.993 --> 01:12:48.598
so the waker that was inside here,

01:12:49.119 --> 01:13:00.881
and it will save that waker inside of a little secret storage area next to the TCP stream's file descriptor.

01:13:01.604 --> 01:13:05.719
And all of that is stored inside of the IO event loop inside Tokyo.

01:13:06.426 --> 01:13:07.469
And the IO event loop,

01:13:07.770 --> 01:13:09.737
whenever a worker runs out of stuff to do,

01:13:09.978 --> 01:13:10.640
or in reality,

01:13:11.121 --> 01:13:11.964
every now and again,

01:13:12.908 --> 01:13:18.919
this event loop is going to be looking for events on all of these little secret compartment file descriptors.

01:13:19.283 --> 01:13:20.085
So look for,

01:13:20.566 --> 01:13:27.883
has anything happened on any resource that I know about and have a waker for?

01:13:27.883 --> 01:13:28.104
And if so,

01:13:28.104 --> 01:13:30.035
I will go to that thing and call wake on it,

01:13:30.377 --> 01:13:33.562
which ultimately then kicks off all this machinery of moving things into the runnable queue.

01:13:34.294 --> 01:13:41.302
And so this is what I mean by the runtime does not really have a loop that just calls pull on every future or every task,

01:13:41.945 --> 01:13:42.931
even if they return pending.

01:13:43.292 --> 01:13:47.731
What actually happens is it calls pull on all of the ones that are runnable.

01:13:48.351 --> 01:13:50.459
And when it runs out of things that are runnable,

01:13:50.781 --> 01:13:53.330
it will call into the IO event loop.

01:13:54.221 --> 01:13:56.375
and see whether it can make some of them runnable.

01:13:56.856 --> 01:13:57.482
And in reality,

01:13:57.562 --> 01:13:58.974
it's actually more sophisticated than that.

01:13:59.557 --> 01:14:06.594
It will periodically check whether things should have become runnable so that it doesn't like starve out the ones that are waiting for IO.

01:14:09.137 --> 01:14:11.935
So that's the sort of low level connection here to resources.

01:14:12.055 --> 01:14:15.075
Let's see if that makes sense first before we keep going.

01:14:25.596 --> 01:14:27.747
Can Tokyo react to mouse or keyboard input?

01:14:28.551 --> 01:14:28.974
In theory,

01:14:29.136 --> 01:14:29.459
yes.

01:14:30.731 --> 01:14:34.708
Tokyo doesn't actually mandate that you use Tokyo-provided resources.

01:14:35.171 --> 01:14:38.846
The rule is just that if you implement your own resource that represents,

01:14:38.866 --> 01:14:39.409
for example,

01:14:39.871 --> 01:14:40.333
mouse input,

01:14:41.077 --> 01:14:43.730
you need to provide something.

01:14:44.862 --> 01:14:52.844
some resource you implement yourself that will take the waker out of the context that your pull method is given for,

01:14:53.105 --> 01:14:53.366
let's say,

01:14:53.446 --> 01:14:53.828
mouse,

01:14:54.369 --> 01:14:56.436
and make sure that when the mouse moves,

01:14:56.857 --> 01:15:00.490
the wake method on the waker is called.

01:15:01.072 --> 01:15:03.561
And Tokyo doesn't dictate that you have to do this in a particular way.

01:15:03.842 --> 01:15:05.529
And this isn't even a Tokyo requirement.

01:15:05.851 --> 01:15:09.109
This is the requirement for futures more broadly.

01:15:09.130 --> 01:15:10.259
So if we go to look at future,

01:15:12.545 --> 01:15:13.087
You'll see here,

01:15:13.509 --> 01:15:17.143
the core method of future poll attempts to resolve the future into a final value.

01:15:17.486 --> 01:15:19.402
This method does not block if the value is not ready.

01:15:19.583 --> 01:15:19.743
Instead,

01:15:19.743 --> 01:15:24.582
the current task is scheduled to be woken up when it's possible to make further progress by polling again.

01:15:25.083 --> 01:15:27.633
The context passed to the poll method can provide a waker,

01:15:27.955 --> 01:15:29.882
which is a handle for waking up the current task.

01:15:30.023 --> 01:15:32.702
That is to say that it is now ready to make progress.

01:15:34.265 --> 01:15:37.002
And the contract here is that...

01:15:39.429 --> 01:15:40.175
Let's see...

01:15:41.493 --> 01:15:41.782
Okay...

01:15:42.999 --> 01:15:43.120
Yeah,

01:15:43.160 --> 01:15:45.150
the pull function is not called repeatedly in a type loop,

01:15:45.411 --> 01:15:50.034
instead it should only be called when the future indicates that it's ready to make progress by calling wake.

01:15:51.027 --> 01:15:52.357
And there are a bunch of different ways to do that.

01:15:52.499 --> 01:15:58.081
The way that Tokyo does it internally for most of its IO resources is to use something like ePoll,

01:15:58.462 --> 01:16:02.713
which is an operating level mechanism for saying,

01:16:02.993 --> 01:16:04.818
I have all these file descriptors,

01:16:04.999 --> 01:16:05.461
all these,

01:16:05.882 --> 01:16:06.626
you know,

01:16:06.626 --> 01:16:06.787
UDP,

01:16:07.208 --> 01:16:08.052
TCP sockets,

01:16:08.092 --> 01:16:08.494
files,

01:16:08.554 --> 01:16:08.856
whatever.

01:16:09.459 --> 01:16:11.758
Tell me if any of them become readable or writable.

01:16:11.879 --> 01:16:15.734
That is if they have bytes available or are ready to be sent on again.

01:16:16.759 --> 01:16:18.429
And so Tokyo will handle that sort of

01:16:18.792 --> 01:16:19.718
IO loop for you.

01:16:27.984 --> 01:16:31.188
Would it be possible to implement zero copy using async read?

01:16:41.823 --> 01:16:43.793
It depends what you mean by zero copy.

01:16:44.779 --> 01:16:44.900
So,

01:16:45.060 --> 01:16:47.812
do you count a copy from kernel space to user space?

01:16:48.535 --> 01:16:48.898
Because if so,

01:16:48.918 --> 01:16:49.221
yes.

01:16:50.575 --> 01:16:58.171
The tricky part is when you really want to give a buffer to the operating system and say the operating system gets to write into this.

01:16:58.695 --> 01:17:00.908
And this is sort of IOU ring kind of setup.

01:17:01.935 --> 01:17:03.502
This interface doesn't let you do that,

01:17:03.562 --> 01:17:06.776
although there are experiments with this and I think it's the Tokyo

01:17:07.938 --> 01:17:10.884
Uring Crate that tries to figure out how this might,

01:17:11.285 --> 01:17:12.086
what this might look like.

01:17:15.870 --> 01:17:20.284
Is there a new waker given to each future or async read poll?

01:17:20.525 --> 01:17:22.085
I'm confused about who creates the waker.

01:17:22.506 --> 01:17:28.484
The waker is created by Tokyo when it calls poll on the top level task.

01:17:29.371 --> 01:17:31.945
And it's actually pretty cheap to create a waker.

01:17:32.926 --> 01:17:33.589
It's really just a

01:17:34.212 --> 01:17:34.856
V table,

01:17:34.916 --> 01:17:36.645
like a virtual dispatch table,

01:17:36.845 --> 01:17:39.182
a list of function pointers that it constructs.

01:17:39.827 --> 01:17:41.884
And the idea is that what wake actually,

01:17:42.485 --> 01:17:47.764
what sort of gets stored in the waker is really just a pointer to the task.

01:17:48.998 --> 01:17:50.607
so that Tokyo knows which tasks,

01:17:50.607 --> 01:17:51.733
like when wake gets called,

01:17:52.034 --> 01:17:53.633
which task was actually awoken,

01:17:54.735 --> 01:17:55.960
and a function pointer to the

01:17:56.321 --> 01:17:59.253
Tokyo code to execute when wake is called.

01:18:00.313 --> 01:18:01.256
So it's executed by,

01:18:01.337 --> 01:18:05.612
it's created by Tokyo at the top before it calls poll.

01:18:08.194 --> 01:18:08.897
So it's not actually,

01:18:09.922 --> 01:18:13.692
it's not like a waker is created when a task is created and it's stored next to the task.

01:18:13.994 --> 01:18:16.312
It's actually created on the fly for every call to poll,

01:18:16.635 --> 01:18:17.733
because it's so cheap to create.

01:18:26.135 --> 01:18:28.439
The implementation details of waker are actually kind of interesting,

01:18:28.439 --> 01:18:29.100
the vtable stuff.

01:18:29.221 --> 01:18:31.818
It feels like waker could also have been a trait instead of a concrete struct.

01:18:32.221 --> 01:18:40.360
So the reason why waker isn't a trait is because it also needs to implement drop.

01:18:42.405 --> 01:18:43.997
Let me see here.

01:18:44.639 --> 01:18:45.377
Local waker.

01:18:50.204 --> 01:18:51.496
Where is the type I'm after?

01:18:54.308 --> 01:18:54.857
Raw waker.

01:18:57.661 --> 01:19:00.696
So you see that there's implementation of drop for waker,

01:19:02.162 --> 01:19:03.296
which means that you...

01:19:03.846 --> 01:19:06.919
it needs to be able to implement drop so that the runtime,

01:19:06.919 --> 01:19:07.241
for example,

01:19:07.341 --> 01:19:10.081
can keep track of whether a waker is still around and do cleanup.

01:19:10.843 --> 01:19:15.260
But the drop trait is not object safe because...

01:19:19.241 --> 01:19:19.423
Well,

01:19:20.108 --> 01:19:20.673
it's complicated.

01:19:21.933 --> 01:19:22.054
No,

01:19:22.174 --> 01:19:22.335
sorry,

01:19:22.436 --> 01:19:22.939
clone,

01:19:23.200 --> 01:19:23.341
sorry,

01:19:23.401 --> 01:19:24.065
it's clone,

01:19:24.146 --> 01:19:24.729
it's not drop,

01:19:24.810 --> 01:19:25.333
that's the problem.

01:19:25.653 --> 01:19:26.433
Clone is the problem.

01:19:26.893 --> 01:19:31.332
So clone is not object safe because it names the self type,

01:19:31.774 --> 01:19:33.631
which object safe methods are not allowed to do,

01:19:33.893 --> 01:19:35.392
or object safe trace are not allowed to do.

01:19:35.913 --> 01:19:36.618
And so as a result,

01:19:36.860 --> 01:19:38.492
if you made waker a trait,

01:19:39.093 --> 01:19:40.792
the trait would not be object safe,

01:19:41.114 --> 01:19:44.832
which means that you couldn't have a box din waker or an arc din waker.

01:19:45.975 --> 01:19:48.348
Which is a problem because that's very often what you want.

01:19:48.670 --> 01:19:53.508
And so the alternative would be that you have a generic everywhere for your waker.

01:19:53.909 --> 01:20:00.348
But that gets super annoying because now you have a generic for every future going all across the system design.

01:20:00.889 --> 01:20:03.368
And so instead what they did is they have this raw...

01:20:06.159 --> 01:20:15.072
this raw waker API that is the V table that is a V table that includes what call should do.

01:20:15.614 --> 01:20:21.092
And the clone implementation here returns a new raw waker rather than self to get around this problem.

01:20:21.733 --> 01:20:26.692
There is actually a waker trait as well,

01:20:27.374 --> 01:20:30.152
which is this task wake trait,

01:20:30.554 --> 01:20:34.653
which basically forcibly wraps it in an arc to get around this problem.

01:20:36.198 --> 01:20:37.301
But there's a little bit of like,

01:20:38.265 --> 01:20:40.552
there's a reason why it's not just a trait.

01:20:44.255 --> 01:20:47.752
Why does Tokyo have async read and async write instead of std?

01:20:48.593 --> 01:20:48.714
Ah,

01:20:49.115 --> 01:20:52.812
so the reason for that is because if you look here at the read trait.

01:20:54.677 --> 01:20:59.228
So the read trait in the standard library has two problems.

01:20:59.669 --> 01:21:02.368
The first of them is that it takes a mutable reference to self,

01:21:02.970 --> 01:21:05.328
whereas the async read takes a pin of self.

01:21:05.869 --> 01:21:07.356
This is important because

01:21:08.882 --> 01:21:10.348
I don't want to get into all of pin,

01:21:10.929 --> 01:21:16.768
but in order to have futures be able to have local state,

01:21:17.289 --> 01:21:20.269
that is like local stack variables inside of a future,

01:21:21.154 --> 01:21:23.428
you need to have a pin of self.

01:21:24.161 --> 01:21:25.652
to be able to do that soundly.

01:21:26.113 --> 01:21:30.333
And read does not take a pin of self and therefore wouldn't work in a future context.

01:21:30.973 --> 01:21:39.613
The second reason is because we want this poll type that indicates whether the read did something or failed to do something,

01:21:39.693 --> 01:21:41.332
or rather couldn't do it yet.

01:21:41.833 --> 01:21:42.703
The difference between

01:21:43.047 --> 01:21:45.112
I'm done and I have more work to do.

01:21:46.109 --> 01:21:49.544
the signature of read in the standard library does not have that type.

01:21:50.025 --> 01:21:50.145
Now,

01:21:50.668 --> 01:21:51.452
IO result,

01:21:52.196 --> 01:21:52.719
technically,

01:21:52.799 --> 01:21:53.764
if you look at the error,

01:21:54.445 --> 01:21:59.084
there's an error kind and there's an error kind called would block.

01:21:59.585 --> 01:22:00.732
And you could look at that,

01:22:01.014 --> 01:22:02.040
but that gets really,

01:22:02.141 --> 01:22:06.464
really ugly to have to parse out exactly which error kind in every call to read.

01:22:06.965 --> 01:22:08.384
So that's the reason why this is a separate trait.

01:22:13.717 --> 01:22:17.372
So is the scheduler and the IO event loop kind of always waiting for each other?

01:22:19.097 --> 01:22:19.746
Sort of,

01:22:20.091 --> 01:22:20.213
right?

01:22:20.253 --> 01:22:22.672
So the schedule doesn't wait for the IO loop.

01:22:22.933 --> 01:22:23.254
Instead,

01:22:23.274 --> 01:22:28.872
you can think of it as the runtime is running the scheduler and the IO loop at the same time.

01:22:29.453 --> 01:22:31.080
The scheduler just chooses,

01:22:31.260 --> 01:22:34.172
the scheduler is to run locally for every worker thread,

01:22:34.574 --> 01:22:37.052
and it just chooses which future to run next.

01:22:37.376 --> 01:22:39.073
And the only thing it really knows about is...

01:22:39.634 --> 01:22:42.369
whether tasks are runnable or not runnable,

01:22:42.629 --> 01:22:45.288
and it only considers running the ones in the runnable column,

01:22:45.609 --> 01:22:46.509
or the runnable queue.

01:22:47.472 --> 01:22:48.420
The event loop,

01:22:48.662 --> 01:22:49.328
its job,

01:22:49.629 --> 01:22:51.609
is to move things from non-runnable to runnable.

01:22:52.909 --> 01:23:07.839
by calling wake so it doesn't actually know about these two queues all it knows is here's a bunch of stuff that we're waiting for and here's the method i should call whenever they become whenever a resource becomes available it just so happens that the the

01:23:08.020 --> 01:23:22.488
code that gets called when something some resource is now available happens to do the move from non-runnable to runnable queues so they actually end up being relatively discrete but cooperating services

01:23:28.362 --> 01:23:29.104
So who calls wake?

01:23:29.565 --> 01:23:29.686
The

01:23:30.031 --> 01:23:31.024
IO event loop calls wake.

01:23:38.603 --> 01:23:39.686
Or you can call wake.

01:23:39.706 --> 01:23:46.760
So this is the idea that you can implement your own resource and all you have to do is you need to have a method that looks kind of like this.

01:23:47.221 --> 01:23:48.643
So if we look at something like,

01:23:51.488 --> 01:23:53.831
if we look at the Tokyo channel,

01:23:53.931 --> 01:23:54.633
for instance,

01:23:55.033 --> 01:23:56.055
and we look at receiver,

01:23:57.417 --> 01:23:59.760
you'll see that there is a poll receive method.

01:24:00.521 --> 01:24:02.260
And this one is not pin.

01:24:03.936 --> 01:24:05.648
for reasons that I'm not going to get into,

01:24:06.250 --> 01:24:09.028
but it has a poll method that kind of looks like the future poll method.

01:24:09.450 --> 01:24:11.328
It takes a context and returns a poll.

01:24:11.849 --> 01:24:15.548
And so this is really the only signature that you need to provide for your own resource type.

01:24:15.889 --> 01:24:22.788
And then you just need to guarantee somehow that if you ever return poll pending instead of poll ready here,

01:24:23.290 --> 01:24:29.688
then you have some way to guarantee that the waker inside of this context will eventually be called wake on.

01:24:30.375 --> 01:24:31.545
when you might be able to make progress.

01:24:31.825 --> 01:24:33.825
That's the contract you have to fulfill for your own resources.

01:24:43.465 --> 01:24:43.665
Okay,

01:24:43.746 --> 01:24:45.452
so there's then a question of,

01:24:45.452 --> 01:24:45.653
okay,

01:24:45.733 --> 01:24:47.741
if async read and read have to be different,

01:24:48.081 --> 01:24:50.050
why isn't async read in the standard library?

01:24:50.411 --> 01:24:52.381
The answer to that is a little more complicated,

01:24:52.741 --> 01:24:55.912
but it's basically because we don't know that this is the,

01:24:56.173 --> 01:24:56.775
and I say we,

01:24:57.036 --> 01:24:58.321
like we as a community,

01:24:58.821 --> 01:25:03.896
don't know what the correct definition of the async read trait should be.

01:25:04.698 --> 01:25:05.882
This one works pretty well,

01:25:06.384 --> 01:25:10.260
but it doesn't work so well when you get to sort of next generation.

01:25:12.145 --> 01:25:14.256
OS-level interfaces for asynchronous I.O.,

01:25:14.599 --> 01:25:15.516
things like IOU Ring.

01:25:15.939 --> 01:25:21.747
It's not clear that this is actually the right interface for async read once you want the ability to do

01:25:22.732 --> 01:25:23.696
IOU Ring-type stuff,

01:25:23.777 --> 01:25:25.117
which is more efficient.

01:25:26.140 --> 01:25:31.697
And so it's mostly just a matter of the moment we're sure that this is the right interface,

01:25:31.898 --> 01:25:33.177
then it will move into the Zend library,

01:25:33.457 --> 01:25:34.376
and we're just not sure yet.

01:25:35.699 --> 01:25:36.205
In some sense,

01:25:36.245 --> 01:25:37.336
we're sure for now,

01:25:37.477 --> 01:25:39.517
but we're not sure we want to commit to it permanently.

01:25:43.355 --> 01:25:45.881
There's also this read buff stuff,

01:25:46.703 --> 01:25:49.108
which takes a mutable reference to a slice of U8s.

01:25:49.349 --> 01:25:50.817
I'm not going to dig into that here,

01:25:50.837 --> 01:25:53.970
but this is another thing where we're not quite sure what the interface should look like.

01:26:05.749 --> 01:26:07.881
Is the IO loop local to each thread?

01:26:10.265 --> 01:26:10.387
No.

01:26:11.611 --> 01:26:14.929
The nature of exactly how the IO event loop gets executed,

01:26:15.129 --> 01:26:18.369
I'm not going to get into here because it's not terribly important.

01:26:18.870 --> 01:26:20.069
And also it's kind of complicated.

01:26:20.330 --> 01:26:23.228
And also it's not guaranteed to stay the same.

01:26:23.650 --> 01:26:26.548
This is sort of considered an internal implementation detail of Tokyo.

01:26:32.586 --> 01:26:35.841
So the I-O event loop periodically runs and checks if a wake needs to be called.

01:26:36.684 --> 01:26:37.279
Kind of.

01:26:38.502 --> 01:26:42.480
The way I would probably think about it is that the I-O event loop is kind of always running,

01:26:42.862 --> 01:26:44.801
rather than thinking about running periodically.

01:26:45.301 --> 01:26:49.574
So it should pick up on data being available on a socket,

01:26:49.574 --> 01:26:50.195
for example,

01:26:50.777 --> 01:26:51.981
basically immediately.

01:26:52.381 --> 01:26:54.341
And it should call wake basically immediately.

01:26:54.561 --> 01:26:59.220
It's not like you have to wait for the next time for it to be time to do an I-O check.

01:27:07.420 --> 01:27:07.621
Okay,

01:27:08.283 --> 01:27:08.483
great.

01:27:09.486 --> 01:27:12.516
So let's now talk about the different...

01:27:13.697 --> 01:27:15.924
IO resource types in a little bit more detail,

01:27:16.005 --> 01:27:18.492
now that we know how the structure of this works.

01:27:19.994 --> 01:27:24.511
The IO types in Tokyo look mostly like the ones in the standard library,

01:27:24.571 --> 01:27:24.732
right?

01:27:24.732 --> 01:27:26.036
You have TCP listeners,

01:27:26.056 --> 01:27:26.317
you have

01:27:26.839 --> 01:27:27.521
UDP stream,

01:27:27.541 --> 01:27:27.762
you have

01:27:28.324 --> 01:27:29.368
UDP socket,

01:27:29.408 --> 01:27:30.712
you have TCP stream,

01:27:31.654 --> 01:27:32.175
you have,

01:27:32.857 --> 01:27:33.098
you know,

01:27:33.198 --> 01:27:33.519
Tokyo

01:27:34.261 --> 01:27:36.688
FS, which has things that are,

01:27:37.250 --> 01:27:37.491
you know,

01:27:37.611 --> 01:27:38.132
files.

01:27:39.052 --> 01:27:39.814
directories,

01:27:39.914 --> 01:27:40.416
readdir,

01:27:40.837 --> 01:27:45.709
you have a bunch of the same methods that you have inside of stdfs.

01:27:46.654 --> 01:27:49.068
Similarly for under process.

01:27:50.236 --> 01:27:52.985
You'll see that you have a child,

01:27:53.045 --> 01:27:53.888
you have command,

01:27:53.928 --> 01:27:54.811
which is the builder.

01:27:55.353 --> 01:27:57.001
All of this looks very much like the standard library,

01:27:57.323 --> 01:28:00.900
except of course for the fact that all of the methods are async,

01:28:01.583 --> 01:28:03.371
and instead of implementing read and write,

01:28:03.371 --> 01:28:05.184
they implement async read and async write.

01:28:06.253 --> 01:28:09.808
So it's really just sort of an async adaptation of mostly the same interface.

01:28:10.713 --> 01:28:15.668
But there are a couple of differences and also surprising similarities to be aware of.

01:28:16.973 --> 01:28:18.790
So let's start with Tokyo FS.

01:28:20.729 --> 01:28:20.849
So,

01:28:21.250 --> 01:28:23.177
this is Tokyo's implementation of,

01:28:23.538 --> 01:28:23.758
sort of,

01:28:23.779 --> 01:28:26.597
asynchronous implementation of ways to access the file system.

01:28:27.185 --> 01:28:27.305
Now,

01:28:27.827 --> 01:28:36.201
the file system is actually a little bit weird because a lot of operating system operations on the file system do not support asynchronous access.

01:28:36.885 --> 01:28:41.662
There just isn't an asynchronous interface to working with files.

01:28:42.265 --> 01:28:44.476
This may be surprising and kind of annoying,

01:28:44.737 --> 01:28:45.501
but it is the case.

01:28:46.125 --> 01:28:46.311
And so,

01:28:47.240 --> 01:28:53.336
Depending a little bit on your operating system and depending on the current phase of the moon,

01:28:54.417 --> 01:28:57.646
Tokyo will often use a blocking thread,

01:28:57.666 --> 01:29:01.116
like a dedicated blocking thread or set of blocking threads,

01:29:01.558 --> 01:29:04.436
in order to give you asynchronous file system access.

01:29:04.897 --> 01:29:06.996
There's a little bit of discussion about it here.

01:29:08.709 --> 01:29:11.559
But what it means is for some of the file system operations,

01:29:12.222 --> 01:29:13.847
even though it looks like an asyncfn,

01:29:14.248 --> 01:29:22.135
what actually happens is that it has a blocking thread that's going to do the real operating system invocation for you,

01:29:22.477 --> 01:29:24.003
and it does a sort of spawn blocking,

01:29:24.224 --> 01:29:26.581
and then it just waits on the join handle as a result.

01:29:27.125 --> 01:29:27.787
This works,

01:29:28.430 --> 01:29:30.157
and it does give you an asynchronous interface,

01:29:30.438 --> 01:29:31.723
but it actually means that for

01:29:32.165 --> 01:29:33.651
Tokyo FS specifically,

01:29:34.414 --> 01:29:36.483
it can be a decent amount slower.

01:29:36.841 --> 01:29:38.333
than the standard library implementation,

01:29:39.155 --> 01:29:41.493
or rather I should say the synchronous implementation.

01:29:41.913 --> 01:29:45.793
And that is because the operating system just doesn't provide an asynchronous interface.

01:29:46.217 --> 01:29:51.093
So we kind of need to fake one by sticking a bunch of overhead on top of the synchronous interface.

01:29:52.294 --> 01:30:08.033
You still usually want to use the asynchronous interface because it gives you things like select and join and you can combine them with other asynchronous futures and you can stack these inside of futures and not worry about blocking the executor for example or the worker pool thread.

01:30:08.215 --> 01:30:08.537
So

01:30:11.334 --> 01:30:12.742
It's usually still worth it,

01:30:12.762 --> 01:30:14.612
but you should be aware of this cost.

01:30:15.193 --> 01:30:17.396
And as this also talks about at the top,

01:30:17.676 --> 01:30:21.480
there are some cases where if you're seeking the sort of highest level of performance,

01:30:21.781 --> 01:30:31.853
it can actually be worthwhile to turn your asynchronous file system stuff into a synchronous thing that you run in a spawn blocking closure.

01:30:32.374 --> 01:30:36.393
So that you get the sort of high performance for all the synchronous file system operations.

01:30:37.014 --> 01:30:40.812
And then it's just the final result that gets turned into something that's async.

01:30:41.427 --> 01:30:50.344
That can be a path you want to take for something where performance of the file system operations specifically are on your critical path.

01:30:54.545 --> 01:30:56.613
That's the main caveat about TokioFS.

01:30:56.693 --> 01:30:57.235
Apart from that,

01:30:57.255 --> 01:30:59.844
it mostly looks like all the things you would expect.

01:31:08.218 --> 01:31:08.338
Yeah,

01:31:08.338 --> 01:31:13.756
so there's some discussion in chat here about what the ace and green and right traits would look like in an IOU ring world.

01:31:14.037 --> 01:31:15.816
And the answer is they just wouldn't be there.

01:31:15.937 --> 01:31:18.017
It just is completely different.

01:31:18.117 --> 01:31:18.478
And again,

01:31:18.799 --> 01:31:19.220
if you look,

01:31:19.341 --> 01:31:20.304
if you're curious about this,

01:31:22.151 --> 01:31:22.873
there is no,

01:31:23.074 --> 01:31:23.756
that's not what I want.

01:31:23.917 --> 01:31:24.499
I want

01:31:26.986 --> 01:31:27.990
Tokyo

01:31:29.334 --> 01:31:30.196
IOU ring.

01:31:33.721 --> 01:31:34.576
Tokyo U ring.

01:31:35.197 --> 01:31:35.722
Tokyo

01:31:36.731 --> 01:31:37.256
U ring.

01:31:39.506 --> 01:31:40.107
Tokyo U-ring,

01:31:41.990 --> 01:31:46.217
which is basically an attempt to figure out what would Tokyo look like on top of

01:31:46.778 --> 01:31:49.763
IOU-ring for sort of higher performance asynchronous interaction,

01:31:49.843 --> 01:31:50.664
specifically on Linux.

01:31:51.848 --> 01:31:53.925
And it just doesn't have async read and async write.

01:31:54.125 --> 01:31:54.683
They're just not there.

01:31:56.247 --> 01:31:57.844
So worth taking a look at if you're curious about this.

01:31:59.632 --> 01:32:03.622
IOUring is a high-performance asynchronous I.O.

01:32:03.762 --> 01:32:06.268
interface that's available in Linux 5.10 and later.

01:32:07.451 --> 01:32:10.858
And so this is why it's not the standard thing that's being used,

01:32:10.918 --> 01:32:16.268
because it's a very new feature of only certain Linux kernels.

01:32:16.689 --> 01:32:22.602
Its API also looks completely different from the older APIs that are used for asynchronous interaction,

01:32:23.023 --> 01:32:25.208
which allows it to get higher performance.

01:32:26.257 --> 01:32:29.692
but you have to match the interface well in order to get that performance benefit.

01:32:30.193 --> 01:32:30.695
And so hence,

01:32:31.036 --> 01:32:38.472
there's still some experimentation on what should abstractions on top of IOU ring look like in order to maximize the chance you get those performance boosts.

01:32:42.795 --> 01:32:42.935
Yeah,

01:32:42.956 --> 01:32:45.892
so IOU ring would replace at least part of the IOU event loop.

01:32:48.934 --> 01:32:49.176
Okay,

01:32:50.162 --> 01:32:51.793
so that is Tokyo FS.

01:32:52.935 --> 01:32:53.572
Let's then...

01:32:54.960 --> 01:32:55.080
Yeah,

01:32:55.100 --> 01:32:56.323
so Windows I.O.

01:32:56.704 --> 01:32:58.329
is also completion-based,

01:32:58.369 --> 01:32:58.630
which is,

01:32:58.810 --> 01:32:58.931
so

01:32:59.592 --> 01:33:01.658
I.O. U-Ring is a completion-based rather than,

01:33:05.670 --> 01:33:06.212
what's the word?

01:33:06.994 --> 01:33:07.696
It's escaping me now.

01:33:09.757 --> 01:33:11.444
The way that Linux does asynchronous I.O.

01:33:12.047 --> 01:33:14.216
is different from how Windows does asynchronous I.O.

01:33:14.558 --> 01:33:16.509
Windows has a completion-based I.O.

01:33:16.589 --> 01:33:16.871
model,

01:33:17.092 --> 01:33:17.916
which Linux does not.

01:33:18.477 --> 01:33:18.597
I.O.

01:33:18.798 --> 01:33:19.079
Uring,

01:33:19.159 --> 01:33:20.042
which is a Linux thing,

01:33:21.025 --> 01:33:24.616
does have a completion-based interface that's different from the one that's currently on Windows.

01:33:25.257 --> 01:33:31.876
But it might be that we actually end up in a world where the completion-based interface is what's used on all platforms down the line.

01:33:32.237 --> 01:33:35.753
But how that looks like is probably not async read and async write,

01:33:35.934 --> 01:33:36.536
but something else.

01:33:36.657 --> 01:33:39.456
Hence why it's probably a good idea that we haven't put it in the standard library.

01:33:43.260 --> 01:33:47.777
I guess readiness-based or polling-based as opposed to completion-based is the wording.

01:33:48.677 --> 01:33:48.858
Okay,

01:33:49.742 --> 01:33:52.557
next thing I want to talk about is Tokyo Process.

01:33:53.518 --> 01:33:55.328
This is sort of the equivalent to

01:33:56.153 --> 01:33:56.777
Stood Process.

01:33:57.863 --> 01:33:58.816
It looks very similar.

01:33:59.237 --> 01:34:01.396
Command is very similar for constructing things.

01:34:01.877 --> 01:34:03.283
The main two differences,

01:34:03.685 --> 01:34:05.916
there's one similarity and one difference to be aware of.

01:34:07.104 --> 01:34:08.836
The similarity is that...

01:34:09.743 --> 01:34:13.713
When you drop a handle to a child process,

01:34:13.954 --> 01:34:16.641
and this is also true for the standard library version of child,

01:34:17.163 --> 01:34:18.128
when you drop it,

01:34:18.510 --> 01:34:20.441
the process is not terminated.

01:34:22.204 --> 01:34:24.177
And this again is similar to stuff like...

01:34:26.673 --> 01:34:27.815
If you have a join handle,

01:34:28.637 --> 01:34:29.519
both in the standard library,

01:34:29.559 --> 01:34:31.643
you spawned a thread,

01:34:31.984 --> 01:34:33.006
and in Tokyo,

01:34:33.126 --> 01:34:34.208
you used Tokyo spawn.

01:34:34.529 --> 01:34:35.351
The handle you get back,

01:34:35.411 --> 01:34:36.172
if you drop it,

01:34:36.893 --> 01:34:38.336
the future that you have a handle to,

01:34:38.496 --> 01:34:39.057
or in this case,

01:34:39.238 --> 01:34:40.841
the process that you have a handle to,

01:34:41.402 --> 01:34:42.804
continues executing,

01:34:43.145 --> 01:34:44.968
even though you dropped your handle to it.

01:34:46.237 --> 01:34:47.401
This can be surprising,

01:34:47.763 --> 01:34:49.168
even though it's the same as the standard library,

01:34:49.188 --> 01:34:50.252
it can be surprising there too,

01:34:50.873 --> 01:34:51.997
because in general,

01:34:52.298 --> 01:34:54.947
what we expect in futures is that when you drop a future,

01:34:54.988 --> 01:34:56.312
it doesn't do any more work.

01:34:56.813 --> 01:34:57.235
It's sort of,

01:34:57.777 --> 01:34:59.405
you drop it and then it cancels,

01:34:59.405 --> 01:35:01.153
like it stops doing everything it was doing.

01:35:01.674 --> 01:35:04.112
That's not the case when you have a child handle in there.

01:35:04.634 --> 01:35:05.718
When the future gets dropped,

01:35:05.718 --> 01:35:06.822
when the future gets cancelled,

01:35:07.023 --> 01:35:09.613
the child process will continue executing.

01:35:10.432 --> 01:35:12.164
There are ways you can change this behavior.

01:35:12.345 --> 01:35:16.182
There's a kill on drop method you can call on command that changes this behavior,

01:35:16.504 --> 01:35:18.521
but you should be aware that this is the default.

01:35:18.905 --> 01:35:19.106
And again,

01:35:19.348 --> 01:35:21.164
it is the default to match the standard library.

01:35:22.069 --> 01:35:23.034
There's also some stuff about just

01:35:23.416 --> 01:35:24.924
Unix processes that are complicated.

01:35:24.985 --> 01:35:27.052
I'm not going to talk about this too much,

01:35:27.795 --> 01:35:32.743
but you should just be aware of how Unix handles processes if you try to use this in an advanced way.

01:35:34.100 --> 01:35:37.933
The other thing you should be aware of is that on child,

01:35:38.053 --> 01:35:40.509
which is the sort of reference to a child that you might have.

01:35:42.376 --> 01:35:47.728
there is an asynchronous function wait that you can use for waiting the process.

01:35:48.289 --> 01:35:50.569
Child itself is not a future.

01:35:51.170 --> 01:35:52.309
So you can't await,

01:35:52.709 --> 01:35:53.072
you can't,

01:35:53.295 --> 01:35:54.668
if you spawn a process,

01:35:55.654 --> 01:35:58.109
you can't just await the child in order to get its output.

01:35:58.671 --> 01:35:59.018
Instead,

01:35:59.038 --> 01:36:03.488
what you have to do is you have to call wait or wait with output and await that thing.

01:36:04.989 --> 01:36:05.313
It's just,

01:36:05.555 --> 01:36:06.889
it's not super complicated.

01:36:07.069 --> 01:36:08.888
It's just a nuance to be aware of here.

01:36:15.575 --> 01:36:15.856
Okay.

01:36:17.021 --> 01:36:18.700
So that's the only thing I want to talk about process.

01:36:18.761 --> 01:36:23.013
You should just be aware of this particular idiosyncrasy maybe.

01:36:27.416 --> 01:36:27.638
Okay.

01:36:27.941 --> 01:36:29.559
Two more things here.

01:36:29.721 --> 01:36:33.191
See this is why I have my notes because there are a lot of things to touch on.

01:36:36.261 --> 01:36:37.295
When we talk about IO.

01:36:38.768 --> 01:36:40.812
So there's async-read and async-write which we've talked about,

01:36:41.273 --> 01:36:48.463
but there's also the async-read-ext and async-write-ext extension traits.

01:36:50.766 --> 01:36:57.425
These are the things that provide you with convenience methods on top of things that implement async read and async write.

01:36:57.725 --> 01:37:07.255
Things like read this many bytes or read a single thing of this type or read to string or write all,

01:37:07.335 --> 01:37:09.418
which is when you do a write,

01:37:10.159 --> 01:37:11.120
just like in the standard library,

01:37:11.140 --> 01:37:12.241
when you write to a socket,

01:37:12.621 --> 01:37:15.585
it's not guaranteed that it writes the entire buffer you give it.

01:37:15.645 --> 01:37:18.324
It might only write the first eight bytes or something.

01:37:18.567 --> 01:37:19.822
And you might need to do it in a loop.

01:37:20.174 --> 01:37:23.348
write all will make sure you actually write all of them before the future resolves.

01:37:23.769 --> 01:37:31.471
So async read x and async write x provide futures on top of the low level interface that async read and async write has.

01:37:31.551 --> 01:37:32.475
So again,

01:37:32.675 --> 01:37:36.087
the async read interface is just a pull read method.

01:37:36.368 --> 01:37:39.161
And you generally don't want to call those methods directly from a future.

01:37:39.462 --> 01:37:40.186
And so instead,

01:37:40.487 --> 01:37:42.835
you would use dot read,

01:37:43.316 --> 01:37:45.001
which returns a read,

01:37:45.041 --> 01:37:47.588
which is a future here that you can await instead.

01:37:50.495 --> 01:37:54.644
And there's also variants of this for buff read,

01:37:55.325 --> 01:37:58.912
which is if you have similar to buff reader and buff writer in the standard library,

01:38:00.115 --> 01:38:05.672
you have the same thing in async world where if you have an async buff read,

01:38:06.154 --> 01:38:08.360
so something that internally knows how to buffer reads,

01:38:08.581 --> 01:38:10.948
you can do additional things like split by line,

01:38:11.008 --> 01:38:11.529
for example,

01:38:11.549 --> 01:38:12.572
and get futures for those.

01:38:13.174 --> 01:38:19.132
So you should just be aware of these extension traits that make it easier to work with IO resources.

01:38:19.839 --> 01:38:22.892
rather than directly working with the async read and async write traits.

01:38:24.014 --> 01:38:27.371
And these are implemented for anything that implements the underlying traits,

01:38:27.392 --> 01:38:27.573
right?

01:38:27.813 --> 01:38:31.162
So if we go look here at read,

01:38:31.223 --> 01:38:31.985
for instance,

01:38:33.349 --> 01:38:34.552
just to see what it looks like.

01:38:36.005 --> 01:38:36.172
Read.

01:38:43.402 --> 01:38:43.524
Oh,

01:38:43.586 --> 01:38:43.872
boy.

01:38:49.497 --> 01:38:50.570
I'm going to regret this aren't I?

01:38:51.617 --> 01:38:52.120
I want to go...

01:38:54.197 --> 01:38:56.629
Maybe it's just actually imported somewhere.

01:39:00.144 --> 01:39:00.325
Yeah,

01:39:00.505 --> 01:39:00.766
it's

01:39:01.750 --> 01:39:04.403
IOUtilRead. Let's go to the repo and see.

01:39:06.337 --> 01:39:06.600
Tokyo.

01:39:08.098 --> 01:39:08.704
Source.

01:39:10.339 --> 01:39:12.755
IOUtilRead.

01:39:13.198 --> 01:39:13.683
Read.

01:39:16.103 --> 01:39:17.806
So the read method,

01:39:17.966 --> 01:39:25.320
like the actual thing that gets called when you call read here inside of async-redext is this read type.

01:39:26.220 --> 01:39:30.175
The read type just holds a reference to the reader and implements future.

01:39:30.677 --> 01:39:37.410
And what it does is it creates a buffer and then calls pull read and then returns you the stuff that got back.

01:39:37.957 --> 01:39:42.053
So it's just a convenient wrapper so that you don't have to call pull read yourself.

01:39:42.917 --> 01:39:44.270
There's no magic to it really.

01:39:44.977 --> 01:39:50.796
It is just the X methods are just so that you don't have to write a bunch of code to call the low level future methods yourself.

01:39:54.853 --> 01:39:55.957
And similarly for writes.

01:39:57.685 --> 01:40:00.213
The other thing you should be aware of when it comes to I.O.

01:40:01.356 --> 01:40:04.687
is that for a lot of these methods,

01:40:05.509 --> 01:40:08.117
and again we can look at,

01:40:08.117 --> 01:40:09.521
we can just look at async read I suppose,

01:40:09.561 --> 01:40:12.500
you see it takes a mutable reference to self.

01:40:13.005 --> 01:40:14.703
This is the same thing as in the standard library.

01:40:14.865 --> 01:40:16.713
If you try to read from a TCP stream,

01:40:16.995 --> 01:40:19.380
you need to have a mutable reference to that TCP stream.

01:40:20.424 --> 01:40:22.670
And what we often see,

01:40:22.871 --> 01:40:23.452
unfortunately,

01:40:23.593 --> 01:40:26.220
is that people have a TCP stream or something,

01:40:26.460 --> 01:40:28.389
and it's in some larger struct somewhere,

01:40:28.871 --> 01:40:31.844
and you have two different futures that both need to access the struct,

01:40:32.124 --> 01:40:34.813
and so you end up doing an ARC mutex

01:40:35.354 --> 01:40:36.036
TCP stream,

01:40:36.598 --> 01:40:41.260
so that these two different futures can both access this underlying IOR resource.

01:40:42.765 --> 01:40:43.467
This works,

01:40:44.672 --> 01:40:46.980
but it is very often not what you want.

01:40:47.502 --> 01:40:48.143
In general,

01:40:48.284 --> 01:40:52.274
if you find yourself putting an IO resource behind a mutex,

01:40:53.137 --> 01:40:54.620
you can probably do better.

01:40:54.841 --> 01:41:01.000
Like you're probably leaving performance on the table because now you're forcing these threads to interlock on the mutex,

01:41:01.581 --> 01:41:07.600
to sort of interleave their execution on the mutex with the other work that they might do.

01:41:08.162 --> 01:41:08.805
In reality,

01:41:08.905 --> 01:41:11.336
this is a really good fit for things like the actor pattern.

01:41:11.497 --> 01:41:17.880
So the idea here is that instead of storing that TCP stream inside of this deeply nested struct with a mutex,

01:41:18.361 --> 01:41:22.837
you actually spawn a separate top-level task that owns the TCP stream.

01:41:22.897 --> 01:41:23.956
It doesn't need a mutex at all.

01:41:25.117 --> 01:41:26.121
And it has,

01:41:26.161 --> 01:41:26.422
let's say,

01:41:26.442 --> 01:41:35.216
a channel that people can send things for it to write into or send messages for it to then read out stuff from that TCP stream.

01:41:35.652 --> 01:41:42.581
The idea being that you have one task that owns the TCP stream and can access it without going through a mutex without the overhead that that entails,

01:41:43.063 --> 01:41:45.093
and then do the work over it and then choose to either,

01:41:45.334 --> 01:41:45.595
you know,

01:41:45.655 --> 01:41:50.368
fan in requests that need to be written or fan out things that have been read.

01:41:52.118 --> 01:41:52.880
So very,

01:41:52.960 --> 01:41:56.730
very rarely do you actually want a mutex TCP stream,

01:41:56.830 --> 01:41:58.926
just so that that's something you're aware of.

01:42:02.670 --> 01:42:02.850
Okay,

01:42:02.850 --> 01:42:03.674
I'm going to pause there.

01:42:03.775 --> 01:42:09.201
The next thing I'll talk about is the connection between async read and async write and sync and stream.

01:42:10.535 --> 01:42:12.583
But let's take questions here before we continue.

01:42:17.081 --> 01:42:17.201
Yeah,

01:42:17.321 --> 01:42:20.533
edge triggered versus level triggered is the framing I was thinking of.

01:42:26.870 --> 01:42:27.773
Don't drop a child,

01:42:27.814 --> 01:42:27.934
bro.

01:42:28.763 --> 01:42:29.133
That's true.

01:42:40.255 --> 01:42:40.381
Um...

01:42:42.659 --> 01:42:46.014
Are there any examples of such actors that own TCP connections or something like that?

01:42:46.155 --> 01:42:47.494
Curious about some implementation details.

01:42:49.076 --> 01:42:52.312
So it's actually a pretty straightforward pattern,

01:42:52.674 --> 01:42:52.815
right?

01:42:52.855 --> 01:42:57.581
So the idea here is that you just

01:43:00.345 --> 01:43:02.127
TXRX is

01:43:03.970 --> 01:43:05.332
Tokyo Sync

01:43:05.692 --> 01:43:07.174
MPSC channel.

01:43:09.715 --> 01:43:25.949
uh eight why not um and you tokyo spawn and i guess here i can do a tcp is tokyo net tcp uh tcp stream connect i don't know 127

01:43:26.450 --> 01:43:26.870
001

01:43:32.452 --> 01:43:45.332
on whatever port 8080 await unwrap and then what I can do here is async move and in here

01:43:46.453 --> 01:43:52.678
I do while let some bytes is rx dot next dot await

01:43:55.690 --> 01:43:59.159
TCP dot write all bytes,

01:44:00.141 --> 01:44:00.643
dot await,

01:44:01.705 --> 01:44:02.186
dot unwrap.

01:44:02.489 --> 01:44:02.695
Again,

01:44:02.695 --> 01:44:03.006
I'm not.

01:44:03.528 --> 01:44:05.306
I'm just sort of demonstrating the pattern here.

01:44:05.927 --> 01:44:07.651
And now what I can do is here,

01:44:07.731 --> 01:44:07.972
you know,

01:44:07.972 --> 01:44:08.873
I can send,

01:44:09.435 --> 01:44:09.775
I don't know,

01:44:10.236 --> 01:44:14.986
a vec of I want to write these bytes.

01:44:16.090 --> 01:44:17.053
But I could also

01:44:19.963 --> 01:44:20.966
Tokyo spawn.

01:44:25.330 --> 01:44:31.206
Async move loop.

01:44:36.281 --> 01:44:36.682
this,

01:44:37.523 --> 01:44:43.955
I could have multiple tasks now that are each individually sending bytes for this thing to write.

01:44:44.771 --> 01:44:47.160
If I didn't have this dedicated actor,

01:44:47.281 --> 01:44:49.187
like this thing that owns the I-O resource,

01:44:49.628 --> 01:44:53.567
I would have to take the TCP stream and stick it behind a mutex and an arc,

01:44:53.949 --> 01:44:56.227
and then have each of these have clones of the arc,

01:44:56.529 --> 01:44:58.538
and then they would each take the mutex,

01:44:59.282 --> 01:45:00.226
sort of alternating,

01:45:00.287 --> 01:45:00.447
right,

01:45:01.293 --> 01:45:02.427
in order to write out the bytes.

01:45:02.930 --> 01:45:04.027
There are trade-offs involved here.

01:45:04.127 --> 01:45:06.047
This is not always a better strategy.

01:45:06.829 --> 01:45:07.553
This does mean,

01:45:07.614 --> 01:45:08.177
for example,

01:45:08.237 --> 01:45:12.047
that you need to allocate a vector for every sequence of bytes you want to write out.

01:45:12.809 --> 01:45:13.411
Or similarly,

01:45:13.712 --> 01:45:14.635
if this was inverted,

01:45:14.755 --> 01:45:18.987
so this would read from the TCP stream and then send it out on a channel,

01:45:19.628 --> 01:45:24.407
we would have to allocate a vector for every read we did in order to be able to give away ownership.

01:45:25.889 --> 01:45:31.627
The advantage is that now these don't have to wait for the I-O to complete in order to continue.

01:45:32.509 --> 01:45:33.090
And also,

01:45:33.512 --> 01:45:38.147
they don't need to have a mutex around the I-O resource that they both need to sort of compete on,

01:45:38.228 --> 01:45:38.854
contend on,

01:45:38.895 --> 01:45:40.087
and reduce the performance of.

01:45:44.536 --> 01:45:44.737
Yeah,

01:45:44.897 --> 01:45:48.454
you can still have back pressure if you want to make sure you don't just spam this,

01:45:48.474 --> 01:45:48.678
right?

01:45:49.351 --> 01:45:49.736
You await this.

01:45:51.211 --> 01:45:54.262
And then you can also adjust how much concurrency you allow here with this.

01:46:03.942 --> 01:46:04.082
Ah,

01:46:04.102 --> 01:46:05.865
and if you want responses,

01:46:06.146 --> 01:46:06.807
then the thing,

01:46:07.327 --> 01:46:09.170
this is a pretty common trick as well.

01:46:10.051 --> 01:46:10.982
You do this.

01:46:23.262 --> 01:46:28.287
Send and here

01:46:28.768 --> 01:46:29.028
I do

01:46:33.754 --> 01:46:36.997
Tokyo Sync one shot channel.

01:46:38.879 --> 01:46:45.698
And the thing I send is a one shot sender and the bytes.

01:46:50.991 --> 01:46:54.021
And so this here will be the number of bytes written.

01:46:57.833 --> 01:47:02.767
So that is the way that you ensure that you make sure that the response is also sent to the one who sent it.

01:47:03.710 --> 01:47:06.679
As you introduce a one-shot channel with every interaction.

01:47:19.178 --> 01:47:19.419
Oh yeah,

01:47:19.459 --> 01:47:20.904
ring buffers are nice for this too,

01:47:20.985 --> 01:47:23.705
but they're a little different than what you would use in this case.

01:47:24.111 --> 01:47:25.361
But I do like ring buffers as well.

01:47:26.751 --> 01:47:27.937
And if you haven't looked at ThingBuff,

01:47:28.078 --> 01:47:29.284
which is a really cool crate,

01:47:29.284 --> 01:47:29.806
go look at it.

01:47:31.594 --> 01:47:31.775
Okay,

01:47:32.036 --> 01:47:35.670
so last thing I want to talk about when it comes to IO resources then is the connection,

01:47:36.011 --> 01:47:36.794
or lack thereof,

01:47:36.935 --> 01:47:38.642
between async read and async write,

01:47:38.963 --> 01:47:40.669
and the sync and stream traits.

01:47:41.231 --> 01:47:41.359
So...

01:47:43.120 --> 01:47:50.215
AsyncRead and AsyncWrite are about individual sequences of bytes that you want to write into or read out of a resource.

01:47:50.918 --> 01:47:51.821
Sync and Stream,

01:47:51.901 --> 01:47:52.644
on the other hand,

01:47:53.266 --> 01:47:54.851
Stream being the more well-known of them,

01:47:55.312 --> 01:47:56.235
are traits specifically for

01:47:57.891 --> 01:47:59.375
units coming out of a stream.

01:47:59.455 --> 01:48:00.277
Think iterator.

01:48:00.558 --> 01:48:03.445
Like each iterator yields you a thing,

01:48:03.465 --> 01:48:05.831
a single thing every time you call next.

01:48:06.914 --> 01:48:07.777
Think of something like,

01:48:08.238 --> 01:48:08.419
again,

01:48:08.439 --> 01:48:12.210
an iterator or a channel where every time you do receive,

01:48:12.230 --> 01:48:13.774
you get a new thing out.

01:48:14.856 --> 01:48:15.538
Whereas again,

01:48:16.079 --> 01:48:16.801
async read,

01:48:17.102 --> 01:48:23.361
you read and you read a bunch of bytes of varying size into a buffer.

01:48:23.762 --> 01:48:25.447
So it's a different kind of interface.

01:48:26.124 --> 01:48:28.231
The bytes do not dictate framing,

01:48:28.311 --> 01:48:30.699
they just say here's a bunch of bytes that I wrote for you.

01:48:31.259 --> 01:48:32.163
And sync is the inverse,

01:48:32.183 --> 01:48:34.051
sync is more like async write,

01:48:34.352 --> 01:48:37.766
except that where async write takes a bunch of bytes and tries to write them into a socket,

01:48:38.188 --> 01:48:41.441
sync takes a single element and tries to put it somewhere.

01:48:41.761 --> 01:48:42.664
Think something like,

01:48:43.226 --> 01:48:47.899
the most close analogy here is something like a channel sender,

01:48:48.222 --> 01:48:50.059
where you can send in one thing at a time.

01:48:51.276 --> 01:48:57.970
Stream and sync are in that way the asynchronous versions of iterator and channel send.

01:48:59.393 --> 01:49:01.601
Sync is not very widely used these days,

01:49:01.762 --> 01:49:03.267
it sort of fell out of favor,

01:49:03.850 --> 01:49:05.660
but stream is still pretty common.

01:49:06.725 --> 01:49:09.312
If you have something that implements async read or async write,

01:49:09.633 --> 01:49:12.861
and you need something that implements sync and stream,

01:49:13.604 --> 01:49:16.081
what you really need to provide is some way to do framing.

01:49:16.562 --> 01:49:17.325
How do you say,

01:49:17.646 --> 01:49:17.887
you know,

01:49:18.791 --> 01:49:21.241
this string of bytes is now one element?

01:49:21.762 --> 01:49:22.589
It's one type,

01:49:23.294 --> 01:49:24.241
one value.

01:49:25.604 --> 01:49:26.349
And similarly,

01:49:27.054 --> 01:49:28.081
I have a bunch of bytes.

01:49:28.262 --> 01:49:31.274
At what point do I turn them into a single value,

01:49:31.274 --> 01:49:33.141
a single element for the purposes of a sync?

01:49:33.899 --> 01:49:37.322
And this is essentially what a codec is.

01:49:37.722 --> 01:49:39.524
This is what framing means.

01:49:39.884 --> 01:49:52.957
It is the conversion between elements or values that are independent to streams of bytes that hopefully match that framing so that you can turn them back into their individual elements.

01:49:54.210 --> 01:49:56.015
There are some tools in Tokyo util,

01:49:56.116 --> 01:50:01.854
like specifically there's a sub module called codec that helps you write adapters between these two traits,

01:50:02.336 --> 01:50:04.644
but just keep in mind that they are separate.

01:50:05.125 --> 01:50:07.364
And this is also not something that's in Tokyo itself.

01:50:07.485 --> 01:50:12.936
And part of the reason for that is because the stream trait and the sync trait are also examples of things that

01:50:13.614 --> 01:50:17.029
We're not quite sure we've arrived at the right abstraction here.

01:50:17.129 --> 01:50:19.789
We're not sure that we know the right definition of these traits.

01:50:20.270 --> 01:50:23.229
And this is why they're not in the standard library.

01:50:23.429 --> 01:50:26.869
There's been a proposal to get stream into the standard library for a while,

01:50:27.291 --> 01:50:30.326
but at least as of the time of this taping,

01:50:30.748 --> 01:50:31.069
I guess,

01:50:32.277 --> 01:50:33.509
stream is not in the standard library,

01:50:33.629 --> 01:50:36.029
and sync I don't think is even being considered at the moment.

01:50:38.583 --> 01:50:40.345
There is a crate called

01:50:43.948 --> 01:50:52.057
TokyoStream, which provides you with the stream trait by re-exporting it from futures core,

01:50:53.178 --> 01:50:55.901
and then implements a bunch of convenience methods around stream.

01:50:56.483 --> 01:51:00.077
But you'll notice that none of the Tokyo types implement stream,

01:51:00.177 --> 01:51:01.161
even the ones you would expect.

01:51:01.503 --> 01:51:04.074
Like an MPSC channel receiver,

01:51:04.094 --> 01:51:04.597
for example,

01:51:04.657 --> 01:51:05.681
will not implement stream.

01:51:06.106 --> 01:51:07.239
And that is because Tokyo...

01:51:07.585 --> 01:51:11.997
...does not want to take a public dependency on this future's core trait,

01:51:12.639 --> 01:51:13.381
or crate rather,

01:51:13.862 --> 01:51:16.781
because if it ever moves into the standard library with a different definition,

01:51:17.262 --> 01:51:20.033
Tokyo would have to do a breaking change to align...

01:51:21.100 --> 01:51:21.301
Sorry,

01:51:22.026 --> 01:51:23.517
with that change in the stream trade.

01:51:23.957 --> 01:51:32.617
And so this is why all of Tokyo's implementations of stream live in the separate crate called Tokyo stream so that it can be upgraded separately from Tokyo.

01:51:33.059 --> 01:51:35.237
And so that if stream does move into the standard library,

01:51:36.382 --> 01:51:39.066
the Tokyo team could cut a new major release just of this crate,

01:51:39.066 --> 01:51:40.157
but not of all of Tokyo,

01:51:40.558 --> 01:51:50.677
which would be pretty sort of disturbing to the whole ecosystem and just update this one re-export and then all the other types would stay the same.

01:51:51.949 --> 01:52:00.776
What you'll notice about Tokyo Stream is that it has these wrappers that are essentially types that you take a type you got out of Tokyo,

01:52:01.257 --> 01:52:03.765
you stick it into one of these types,

01:52:04.025 --> 01:52:05.094
and now it implements Stream.

01:52:06.505 --> 01:52:10.083
So this is the way that you bridge between Tokyo types and Stream.

01:52:10.585 --> 01:52:16.584
There is not an equivalent for Sync because people seem to generally have agreed that Sync is probably not that great of an idea.

01:52:17.903 --> 01:52:19.307
And you'll see the same if you use that

01:52:19.708 --> 01:52:24.663
Tokyo Yuto codec in order to adapt between async-read and async-write and stream and sync,

01:52:25.044 --> 01:52:31.871
that it also operates with stream from the futures core crate and sync from the futures sync crate.

01:52:33.357 --> 01:52:33.840
So it too,

01:52:34.221 --> 01:52:36.270
if there was a standard library implementation of stream,

01:52:37.215 --> 01:52:39.563
would start using the standard library version of stream instead.

01:52:45.793 --> 01:52:46.034
Okay.

01:52:46.797 --> 01:52:50.149
I think that's all I wanted to talk about when it comes to IO resources.

01:52:50.249 --> 01:52:51.631
Let's pause there for questions.

01:53:05.609 --> 01:53:07.659
Sync and stream are often used for web sockets.

01:53:07.680 --> 01:53:07.840
Yeah,

01:53:07.840 --> 01:53:09.026
I've seen it being used for...

01:53:11.326 --> 01:53:13.116
events or streams as well.

01:53:13.437 --> 01:53:14.547
So Tokyo Stream certainly,

01:53:15.717 --> 01:53:17.455
the stream trait is pretty useful.

01:53:17.738 --> 01:53:20.411
And that's also why I think it will end up in the standard library.

01:53:20.757 --> 01:53:23.375
The question is just what should its exact type signature be?

01:53:23.798 --> 01:53:24.992
And that's still under some debate.

01:53:35.482 --> 01:53:37.133
Any hints to why sync is a bad idea?

01:53:38.639 --> 01:53:42.493
I think the observation is that it's not clear that it's valuable to have a trait here.

01:53:44.589 --> 01:53:44.912
Like...

01:53:45.940 --> 01:53:46.622
It's rare,

01:53:46.723 --> 01:53:47.064
I think,

01:53:47.365 --> 01:53:50.215
the observation is that you actually want to be generic over sync.

01:53:50.676 --> 01:53:53.307
I think you quite often want to be generic over stream,

01:53:53.428 --> 01:53:55.275
either in arguments or in return values.

01:53:55.736 --> 01:53:59.055
But being generic over sync is just kind of a little weird.

01:53:59.978 --> 01:54:01.632
And I don't think we've come across very...

01:54:03.341 --> 01:54:06.055
common needs for that to be the case.

01:54:06.596 --> 01:54:11.455
And if you don't have particularly salient concrete needs,

01:54:11.797 --> 01:54:13.835
it's hard to make sure that the interface is the right one.

01:54:14.278 --> 01:54:17.275
So this is not to say that sync shouldn't be standardized.

01:54:17.535 --> 01:54:22.432
It's just we don't have enough evidence for what it should look like to be comfortable stabilizing it.

01:54:26.597 --> 01:54:30.174
Tokyo streams are the same as std async iterators,

01:54:30.294 --> 01:54:30.495
right?

01:54:32.072 --> 01:54:32.353
I mean,

01:54:32.794 --> 01:54:38.006
you can think of the stream trait as the asynchronous version of iterators,

01:54:38.067 --> 01:54:38.407
if you will.

01:54:38.527 --> 01:54:38.648
Yeah,

01:54:38.989 --> 01:54:44.885
there's actually a really good blog post by Boats that talks about,

01:54:45.026 --> 01:54:45.547
where is it?

01:54:46.512 --> 01:54:49.456
The registers of Rust that I thought was really cool,

01:54:50.317 --> 01:55:02.411
where they talk about sort of what is the mapping between different concepts in the async world versus the non-async world versus the iteration world versus the fallibility world.

01:55:03.135 --> 01:55:03.838
And like,

01:55:04.180 --> 01:55:05.909
how does iterator map to stream,

01:55:06.009 --> 01:55:06.511
for example?

01:55:07.972 --> 01:55:12.624
And they also have a follow-up thing on,

01:55:12.825 --> 01:55:15.291
is it patterns and abstractions where they talk about stream?

01:55:18.203 --> 01:55:18.364
No,

01:55:18.546 --> 01:55:19.211
it's a later one.

01:55:19.272 --> 01:55:20.544
I think it's the pull next one.

01:55:21.351 --> 01:55:21.733
In general,

01:55:22.315 --> 01:55:24.404
all of these things on asynchrony,

01:55:24.625 --> 01:55:27.163
I recommend reading if you really want to dig further into this.

01:55:27.951 --> 01:55:28.874
Just without dot boats.

01:55:39.459 --> 01:55:42.466
I'm specifically talking about the experimental std async iter.

01:55:45.412 --> 01:55:46.269
Async iterator.

01:55:47.711 --> 01:55:47.852
Yeah,

01:55:47.912 --> 01:55:52.447
so async iterator is the thing that stream is going to become.

01:55:52.949 --> 01:55:57.224
I don't know whether they've even landed on the name that it really should be async iterator as opposed to stream.

01:55:57.488 --> 01:55:58.924
There's still some debate about that.

01:55:59.207 --> 01:56:01.720
It could be that it ends up stabilizing under the name async iterator,

01:56:02.002 --> 01:56:04.302
but this is the same thing as stream.

01:56:04.747 --> 01:56:06.927
Just trying to figure out what it should look like when stabilized.

01:56:12.352 --> 01:56:12.573
Okay,

01:56:13.557 --> 01:56:15.465
so now we've talked about resources.

01:56:16.067 --> 01:56:17.360
Let's then move on to utilities.

01:56:18.067 --> 01:56:20.399
We've started talking a little bit about this when talking about

01:56:20.760 --> 01:56:21.685
Tokyo Util Codec,

01:56:21.705 --> 01:56:22.187
for example,

01:56:22.267 --> 01:56:22.931
and Tokyo Stream,

01:56:23.333 --> 01:56:26.851
but there are a couple of things inside of Tokyo itself that you should be aware of.

01:56:29.307 --> 01:56:29.852
In particular,

01:56:29.892 --> 01:56:31.363
let's start with the sync module.

01:56:31.907 --> 01:56:38.293
So the sync module provides synchronization primitives that you can use for having different futures,

01:56:39.259 --> 01:56:39.944
different tasks,

01:56:39.944 --> 01:56:40.427
but also just

01:56:40.712 --> 01:56:41.796
specifically futures,

01:56:42.620 --> 01:56:43.443
interact with each other,

01:56:43.523 --> 01:56:44.507
coordinate with each other.

01:56:44.968 --> 01:56:47.727
There are a bunch of different patterns you can use here.

01:56:47.787 --> 01:56:51.847
I'm not going to try to talk about all of the ways in which futures can cooperate.

01:56:52.648 --> 01:56:55.967
The docs here do a decent job of talking about the different ones,

01:56:56.309 --> 01:56:59.887
but I do want to highlight some of the ones that are easy to miss.

01:57:01.752 --> 01:57:02.495
The most basic one,

01:57:02.495 --> 01:57:02.877
of course,

01:57:02.997 --> 01:57:04.102
is the MPSC channel,

01:57:04.122 --> 01:57:05.929
the Multi-Producer Single Consumer Channel.

01:57:06.251 --> 01:57:10.047
This maps directly to what you have in the standard library with std sync mpsc.

01:57:11.949 --> 01:57:12.330
That one,

01:57:12.872 --> 01:57:14.418
I'm not even going to spend a lot of time on.

01:57:14.679 --> 01:57:15.281
It just works.

01:57:15.381 --> 01:57:15.743
It's great.

01:57:16.706 --> 01:57:21.227
There are variations outside of Tokyo that are sometimes faster or work better for particular use cases.

01:57:21.328 --> 01:57:21.530
Again,

01:57:21.852 --> 01:57:23.747
ThingBuff is a thing worth looking at here.

01:57:25.240 --> 01:57:26.203
But ignoring MPSC,

01:57:26.804 --> 01:57:30.354
there are a bunch of other ways in which you can coordinate between futures.

01:57:30.875 --> 01:57:31.417
And usually,

01:57:31.999 --> 01:57:33.343
if you can use one of them,

01:57:34.005 --> 01:57:36.733
chances are it will work better for you than MPSC.

01:57:37.495 --> 01:57:38.769
Think of MPSC as sort of a hammer,

01:57:39.112 --> 01:57:39.314
right?

01:57:39.456 --> 01:57:40.965
Like a lot of things will look like nails,

01:57:40.965 --> 01:57:42.173
you can solve a lot of things with them.

01:57:42.595 --> 01:57:45.350
But often there are more specialized tools that will perform better,

01:57:45.430 --> 01:57:47.369
have better APIs when you can use them.

01:57:48.492 --> 01:57:50.120
The first of these is the one-shot channel.

01:57:50.160 --> 01:57:51.426
I showed you one use of it already.

01:57:51.788 --> 01:57:56.446
So a one-shot channel is a channel that you can only send on once.

01:57:57.029 --> 01:57:57.937
And when you receive,

01:57:57.957 --> 01:57:59.046
you only receive once.

01:57:59.428 --> 01:58:01.800
That means it does not implement the equivalent of stream,

01:58:02.121 --> 01:58:03.247
it just implements future.

01:58:03.588 --> 01:58:06.020
So when you have a one-shot receiver,

01:58:06.482 --> 01:58:07.527
all you can do is await it.

01:58:07.628 --> 01:58:10.687
There's no next because it will only ever yield once.

01:58:12.048 --> 01:58:16.367
And one of the things that is particularly worthwhile to know about the one-shot channel

01:58:17.316 --> 01:58:18.298
over here I'll show you,

01:58:19.682 --> 01:58:22.871
is so there's a receiver and a sender.

01:58:25.953 --> 01:58:28.743
And receiver has a blocking receive.

01:58:29.164 --> 01:58:30.770
So when you have a one-shot receiver,

01:58:30.870 --> 01:58:32.596
you can call blocking receive.

01:58:33.077 --> 01:58:37.531
And so this is one way to bridge between asynchronous and synchronous context.

01:58:38.321 --> 01:58:39.682
And the same thing is true for sender.

01:58:40.063 --> 01:58:41.024
So if you look at sender,

01:58:41.524 --> 01:58:44.547
the send method is not async on one shot.

01:58:45.048 --> 01:58:46.550
It is a synchronous method.

01:58:46.970 --> 01:58:47.571
And so again,

01:58:47.651 --> 01:58:52.456
this is a way to communicate from the synchronous world to the asynchronous world,

01:58:52.896 --> 01:58:55.759
or from the asynchronous world to the synchronous world.

01:58:57.305 --> 01:59:06.155
And this is a particularly useful thing once you do things like spin up a blocking thread somewhere to do some computation and you either want to send it some stuff to do,

01:59:06.696 --> 01:59:07.757
like not regularly,

01:59:07.757 --> 01:59:09.439
you just want to send it one packet of work,

01:59:09.859 --> 01:59:10.620
or crucially,

01:59:10.921 --> 01:59:11.441
you want it to,

01:59:11.601 --> 01:59:12.362
after it finishes,

01:59:12.442 --> 01:59:13.303
send some stuff back.

01:59:14.186 --> 01:59:14.789
If you can,

01:59:14.849 --> 01:59:16.599
you can just use the join handle for this.

01:59:17.060 --> 01:59:17.543
So remember,

01:59:17.604 --> 01:59:18.329
spawn blocking,

01:59:18.349 --> 01:59:18.772
for example,

01:59:18.812 --> 01:59:19.839
returns you a join handle.

01:59:20.199 --> 01:59:25.139
You can then wait in order to get the result of the closure executing in.

01:59:25.861 --> 01:59:28.039
But if you want more fine-tuned control over it,

01:59:28.301 --> 01:59:29.808
you could use a one-shot sender instead,

01:59:29.848 --> 01:59:32.259
which you can use from a blocking context.

01:59:35.911 --> 01:59:36.032
So,

01:59:36.232 --> 01:59:36.874
so one shot,

01:59:37.216 --> 01:59:38.319
very useful tool for,

01:59:38.440 --> 01:59:39.042
for bridging,

01:59:39.423 --> 01:59:42.067
also very useful tool for anything that sort of acknowledgement.

01:59:42.248 --> 01:59:45.538
So you very frequently see something like an MPSC,

01:59:46.160 --> 01:59:46.300
uh,

01:59:46.842 --> 01:59:56.383
that where the thing you send is both some operation and the sender of a one shot for you to send the result of that operation when it's completed.

01:59:56.867 --> 01:59:59.987
This ends up fitting really well into the actor model of the world.

02:00:03.190 --> 02:00:05.939
The next thing in sync that I want to talk about is,

02:00:06.159 --> 02:00:07.906
and I think these are roughly listed in order,

02:00:08.772 --> 02:00:09.597
skipping up MPSC.

02:00:10.523 --> 02:00:11.498
So there's a broadcast channel.

02:00:11.883 --> 02:00:13.027
The broadcast channel is just,

02:00:13.449 --> 02:00:18.405
you produce a value and you know that when you produce that value,

02:00:19.629 --> 02:00:25.677
there's going to be a bunch of copies of the receiver and every consumer receives every value.

02:00:26.694 --> 02:00:26.815
So,

02:00:26.855 --> 02:00:30.925
this is not like a single producer multiple consumer queue,

02:00:30.985 --> 02:00:34.766
where you send in and whoever reads it first has it.

02:00:35.251 --> 02:00:40.748
It is the thing that ensures that everyone sees every broadcast of a value.

02:00:41.951 --> 02:00:42.859
Not very widely used,

02:00:43.000 --> 02:00:43.827
but useful to know about.

02:00:44.411 --> 02:00:46.950
But the really cool one is watch.

02:00:47.994 --> 02:00:48.114
So,

02:00:48.275 --> 02:00:51.262
watch is kind of like a broadcast channel,

02:00:51.863 --> 02:00:56.189
except that it doesn't keep every value you send.

02:00:56.331 --> 02:00:56.533
Instead,

02:00:56.613 --> 02:00:59.187
it only keeps the most recent value.

02:00:59.851 --> 02:01:03.544
And the reason this is cool is because imagine that you have a bunch of receivers,

02:01:04.006 --> 02:01:07.127
but they're not necessarily always checking on the value.

02:01:07.247 --> 02:01:09.640
Like they're not regularly receiving from the channel,

02:01:09.921 --> 02:01:11.385
but every now and again they are.

02:01:12.549 --> 02:01:18.527
What watch allows you to do is not build up like an infinite queue because you had some slow readers.

02:01:18.928 --> 02:01:19.570
And instead,

02:01:19.952 --> 02:01:20.795
when you send,

02:01:20.895 --> 02:01:21.759
you don't really send,

02:01:21.759 --> 02:01:24.027
you just update the broadcast value.

02:01:24.409 --> 02:01:27.987
You update the value that readers will see when they read.

02:01:28.715 --> 02:01:29.899
And then on the reader side,

02:01:30.180 --> 02:01:33.831
you can basically subscribe to changes to the latest value.

02:01:34.931 --> 02:01:36.596
And so if you come back,

02:01:36.696 --> 02:01:36.937
you know,

02:01:37.297 --> 02:01:39.403
way later and it's changed 20 times,

02:01:39.663 --> 02:01:42.811
you only get woken up once and told about the new value.

02:01:43.513 --> 02:01:47.171
This can be extremely useful for communicating things like config changes.

02:01:48.817 --> 02:01:50.961
The fact that something has changed,

02:01:50.961 --> 02:01:52.544
so now go look somewhere else,

02:01:53.145 --> 02:01:58.855
it's a really useful mechanism where the individual notifications are not important.

02:01:59.902 --> 02:02:01.895
What is important is just the latest state.

02:02:02.875 --> 02:02:03.457
So it allows you to,

02:02:03.697 --> 02:02:11.855
you can think of it as sort of as batching updates and amortizing that cost of doing a bunch of receives in a row.

02:02:15.888 --> 02:02:17.452
And then the last one,

02:02:17.692 --> 02:02:18.956
no actually I'll talk about two more,

02:02:19.276 --> 02:02:22.163
because I do want to talk about Semaphore.

02:02:23.150 --> 02:02:25.263
But the next one I want to talk about is Notify.

02:02:26.104 --> 02:02:26.224
So

02:02:26.806 --> 02:02:34.103
Notify is sort of the second to lowest level primitive that you have in Sync.

02:02:34.744 --> 02:02:37.283
Notify is just a type.

02:02:37.871 --> 02:02:38.392
that you,

02:02:39.255 --> 02:02:40.198
there's an example here,

02:02:41.080 --> 02:02:42.204
you create a notify,

02:02:42.304 --> 02:02:43.487
you put it in an arc or something,

02:02:44.148 --> 02:02:47.700
and it's sort of like the condition variable,

02:02:48.061 --> 02:02:48.503
if you will,

02:02:48.864 --> 02:02:49.907
from the synchronous world,

02:02:50.209 --> 02:02:51.777
except not associated with the mutex.

02:02:51.777 --> 02:02:53.607
It's not associated with the value at all.

02:02:54.808 --> 02:02:58.399
You can call.notified and you get a future back that you can await.

02:02:59.021 --> 02:03:01.287
And you continue executing,

02:03:01.388 --> 02:03:05.106
like this await resolves when someone calls notify1.

02:03:06.439 --> 02:03:07.355
That's all it takes.

02:03:07.959 --> 02:03:10.051
So this is a way to just tell someone else,

02:03:10.091 --> 02:03:10.252
hey,

02:03:10.353 --> 02:03:10.715
wake up.

02:03:11.519 --> 02:03:17.037
This can be a really useful or simple way to implement wakers in your own resources.

02:03:17.719 --> 02:03:22.118
Rather than figure out how to do poll calls and distributing this waker and stuff,

02:03:22.359 --> 02:03:24.655
you can often get away with just using a notify.

02:03:25.299 --> 02:03:26.705
And so in your resource,

02:03:26.725 --> 02:03:30.656
what you actually do is you just construct a notify and you do.

02:03:31.669 --> 02:03:39.061
give a clone of the notify await to something or stick it in a queue somewhere that is going to call notify one when there's more work to do.

02:03:39.765 --> 02:03:41.503
And then in the resource,

02:03:41.803 --> 02:03:43.203
wherever you are in your asynchronous function,

02:03:43.323 --> 02:03:44.943
you then just call notify.await.

02:03:45.627 --> 02:03:46.073
And that way,

02:03:46.134 --> 02:03:53.223
the only thing that you need to be concerned about is making sure you call notify one from somewhere and you don't ever need to touch the sort of low level pull interface.

02:03:53.867 --> 02:03:55.343
So that's where notify can be really useful.

02:03:55.583 --> 02:03:56.663
It's useful in other places too,

02:03:56.784 --> 02:03:58.943
but that's the main place I've found it to be useful.

02:04:04.211 --> 02:04:04.451
Okay,

02:04:05.473 --> 02:04:06.395
before I go to Semaphores,

02:04:06.435 --> 02:04:07.657
let's do questions there.

02:04:11.383 --> 02:04:16.133
Does it make sense to use Broadcast for a WebSocket server where the different clients are stored in memory?

02:04:17.143 --> 02:04:20.258
So the main problem with Broadcast is...

02:04:20.944 --> 02:04:22.168
the slow readers problem,

02:04:22.609 --> 02:04:22.830
right?

02:04:22.870 --> 02:04:28.369
So if you have a bunch of WebSocket connections that are all listening on the broadcast channel,

02:04:28.831 --> 02:04:32.245
then imagine what happens if you have a particularly slow client,

02:04:32.245 --> 02:04:33.229
like someone's connected over like

02:04:33.671 --> 02:04:36.281
2G network to your server over WebSocket.

02:04:36.582 --> 02:04:38.912
So your writes out of that channel are really slow.

02:04:39.354 --> 02:04:42.789
That means you're draining things out of the broadcast queue very slowly,

02:04:43.170 --> 02:04:46.323
which means that those can't be dropped because you haven't read them yet,

02:04:46.585 --> 02:04:48.496
which means the broadcast queue just keeps increasing.

02:04:49.059 --> 02:04:49.803
You can set up...

02:04:51.641 --> 02:05:01.035
like a bound or a behavior on broadcast for what should happen if you try to send and the sort of broadcast buffer is full,

02:05:01.396 --> 02:05:04.695
you can choose for it to drop like the latest thing or just refuse to send.

02:05:06.058 --> 02:05:07.853
But ultimately you have a problem there,

02:05:07.954 --> 02:05:08.115
right?

02:05:08.156 --> 02:05:13.095
Which is your application is either going to have to drop things that go out in that web socket,

02:05:13.495 --> 02:05:14.455
that slow web socket,

02:05:14.679 --> 02:05:15.875
or it's gonna have to buffer them forever.

02:05:16.275 --> 02:05:20.015
And that's an application design question that you just have to figure out what the right behavior is.

02:05:20.796 --> 02:05:24.848
The broadcast implementation allows you to choose whatever behavior you want,

02:05:25.088 --> 02:05:26.051
but you do have to choose.

02:05:32.813 --> 02:05:33.034
Oh yeah,

02:05:33.094 --> 02:05:35.682
notify can also be really useful for canceling,

02:05:35.723 --> 02:05:38.311
although I'll talk about a potentially better way to do that later.

02:05:40.133 --> 02:05:42.088
Where imagine that you have a sort of...

02:05:44.962 --> 02:05:45.224
Actually,

02:05:45.264 --> 02:05:45.384
no,

02:05:45.525 --> 02:05:49.231
I don't want to recommend notify for canceling because I want to recommend a different thing for canceling.

02:05:49.575 --> 02:05:49.937
But yes,

02:05:49.977 --> 02:05:51.443
you can use notify for canceling.

02:05:54.355 --> 02:05:58.253
So notify could be used to bridge or wrap sync resources into an async world.

02:05:58.795 --> 02:05:59.468
That's also true,

02:05:59.570 --> 02:05:59.754
right?

02:05:59.855 --> 02:06:02.146
So if you look at the method signatures for notify,

02:06:02.507 --> 02:06:03.070
you'll see that...

02:06:04.375 --> 02:06:07.233
So notified returns the notified and this is a future.

02:06:07.615 --> 02:06:10.992
So this thing is not that useful in...

02:06:12.809 --> 02:06:15.703
The thing you get back from Notified is just implements future.

02:06:15.804 --> 02:06:19.523
So this one is not in and of itself useful in a synchronous world.

02:06:20.003 --> 02:06:22.043
But notify1 is synchronous.

02:06:22.584 --> 02:06:23.728
So you can use

02:06:24.350 --> 02:06:28.483
Notified to have an asynchronous wrapper for a synchronous resource.

02:06:28.803 --> 02:06:31.013
So something synchronous is going to call notify1,

02:06:31.656 --> 02:06:34.103
which it can because notify1 is not an async function.

02:06:35.148 --> 02:06:37.103
And your future is just going to await this Notified.

02:06:43.126 --> 02:06:43.427
All right,

02:06:43.608 --> 02:06:47.363
so the last thing I want to talk about in Tokyo Sync is semaphore.

02:06:48.206 --> 02:06:50.123
Usually you shouldn't need to reach for semaphore.

02:06:50.544 --> 02:06:52.614
Semaphore is a very low-level primitive,

02:06:52.916 --> 02:06:54.423
but it is useful to know what it does.

02:06:55.243 --> 02:06:57.843
Semaphore is a way to have a number.

02:07:00.287 --> 02:07:01.583
Think of it as a ticketing system.

02:07:02.164 --> 02:07:08.363
So you set some maximum number of tickets that are allowed to be active at any point in time.

02:07:09.469 --> 02:07:10.052
And initially,

02:07:10.554 --> 02:07:12.343
let's say there are four tickets.

02:07:13.415 --> 02:07:18.491
A semaphore of size 4 means that someone can take a ticket

02:07:19.412 --> 02:07:20.417
someone else can take a ticket,

02:07:20.799 --> 02:07:21.744
someone else can take a ticket,

02:07:21.985 --> 02:07:22.889
someone else can take a ticket,

02:07:23.271 --> 02:07:25.119
and then the next thing,

02:07:25.179 --> 02:07:25.842
the next task,

02:07:25.862 --> 02:07:30.779
the next future that tries to take a ticket is going to return pending.

02:07:31.200 --> 02:07:39.876
It will not get to proceed until someone who got a ticket drops that ticket and at that point sort of returns it rather to the pool,

02:07:40.298 --> 02:07:41.364
then someone else can come in.

02:07:41.605 --> 02:07:48.425
So it is a way to guarantee that there are at most n things where n is configurable active at one point in time.

02:07:49.650 --> 02:07:52.222
There are a bunch of places where this kind of thing goes up.

02:07:52.643 --> 02:07:53.126
For example,

02:07:53.388 --> 02:07:56.103
a mutex is a single-permit semaphore.

02:07:58.578 --> 02:07:59.866
That is in fact how it's implemented,

02:08:00.390 --> 02:08:00.571
right?

02:08:00.671 --> 02:08:01.922
It is a single permit semaphore.

02:08:03.031 --> 02:08:03.715
There are other semaphores,

02:08:03.736 --> 02:08:04.299
like for example,

02:08:04.420 --> 02:08:13.084
let's say you don't want there to be more than so and so many concurrent requests or so and so many concurrent connections you're handling in your web server.

02:08:13.711 --> 02:08:16.446
You could have a semaphore that is the number of connections you allow,

02:08:16.808 --> 02:08:18.558
and every time you're about to accept a connection,

02:08:18.859 --> 02:08:20.729
you first check whether you can grab a semaphore.

02:08:21.111 --> 02:08:21.674
And if you can't,

02:08:21.775 --> 02:08:26.037
then you just do not accept any more connections until someone gives the ticket back,

02:08:26.118 --> 02:08:27.531
meaning some other connection has been dropped.

02:08:28.035 --> 02:08:32.470
Or if you don't allow more than N concurrent requests on a single connection,

02:08:32.851 --> 02:08:40.473
you have a semaphore with that limit and before you read a new request from the client over that connection,

02:08:40.533 --> 02:08:45.748
you try to grab a ticket from the semaphore and only if you get a ticket do you allow it to send another request.

02:08:46.072 --> 02:08:48.310
Otherwise it has to wait for one of its pending requests to finish.

02:08:49.667 --> 02:08:51.854
So this is a really useful low-level primitive,

02:08:52.055 --> 02:08:54.743
and you'll find that it's actually used by a bunch of high-level primitives.

02:08:54.903 --> 02:08:56.203
So mutex being an example.

02:08:56.624 --> 02:09:00.410
Another example of a place where it's used is in the...

02:09:02.501 --> 02:09:06.250
concurrent request filter in tower,

02:09:06.751 --> 02:09:08.876
I believe also uses Semaphore because it can,

02:09:09.297 --> 02:09:09.477
right?

02:09:09.898 --> 02:09:13.009
This is the kind of pattern that Semaphore enables you to do,

02:09:13.330 --> 02:09:15.096
but its interface is very low level.

02:09:15.498 --> 02:09:16.221
So you'll see here,

02:09:17.306 --> 02:09:17.929
when you create it,

02:09:17.909 --> 02:09:19.155
you say how many permits there are,

02:09:19.135 --> 02:09:19.999
how many tickets there are.

02:09:20.680 --> 02:09:21.864
You can add permits if you want.

02:09:23.108 --> 02:09:24.893
There's an asyncfn acquire,

02:09:25.234 --> 02:09:28.045
which you try to take a ticket and you see whether you get it or not.

02:09:28.145 --> 02:09:28.809
It's async,

02:09:29.030 --> 02:09:31.457
so you can await it and you'll be notified when you can.

02:09:32.570 --> 02:09:33.191
And similarly,

02:09:33.712 --> 02:09:34.533
you can also,

02:09:35.955 --> 02:09:37.057
so with the Semaphore permit,

02:09:37.077 --> 02:09:41.845
you get back the,

02:09:43.047 --> 02:09:43.567
where's my...

02:09:49.797 --> 02:09:49.938
Yeah,

02:09:50.240 --> 02:09:52.275
so if no remaining permits are available,

02:09:52.495 --> 02:09:55.075
acquire waits for an outstanding permit to be dropped.

02:09:55.435 --> 02:09:56.914
So the type that you get back,

02:09:58.142 --> 02:09:59.175
why is the text so long?

02:09:59.860 --> 02:10:05.095
The type that you get back from acquire the semaphore permit here holds that ticket until it gets dropped.

02:10:05.378 --> 02:10:05.995
When it gets dropped,

02:10:06.315 --> 02:10:11.715
the ticket sort of gets returned to the pool and then you allow someone who's waiting on acquire to resume.

02:10:12.839 --> 02:10:15.510
And this is also how you get something like a read or writer lock,

02:10:15.834 --> 02:10:15.955
right?

02:10:15.995 --> 02:10:19.555
So a read or writer lock is actually one that has N permit.

02:10:20.664 --> 02:10:25.919
and taking out the read side of the lock just takes one semaphore.

02:10:26.661 --> 02:10:27.706
And if you are a writer,

02:10:27.947 --> 02:10:30.619
you have to try to acquire all of the semaphores at once.

02:10:30.819 --> 02:10:33.579
That is how you know that you have exclusive access.

02:10:36.662 --> 02:10:36.884
So yeah,

02:10:37.085 --> 02:10:37.469
semaphore,

02:10:37.852 --> 02:10:38.719
useful thing to know about.

02:10:41.886 --> 02:10:47.239
Not a thing that you should generally need to use very often,

02:10:47.381 --> 02:10:48.919
but it is useful to know that it exists.

02:11:04.041 --> 02:11:04.241
Okay,

02:11:05.503 --> 02:11:07.566
moving on from Tokyo Sync.

02:11:11.711 --> 02:11:14.143
The next thing we have is Joinset.

02:11:15.951 --> 02:11:16.870
So Joinset...

02:11:16.972 --> 02:11:17.259
So Joinset...

02:11:18.707 --> 02:11:23.363
is a collection of tasks that are running at the Tokyo runtime.

02:11:24.224 --> 02:11:26.863
And the idea here is that let's say you...

02:11:31.848 --> 02:11:32.816
What's a good example of this?

02:11:33.280 --> 02:11:34.259
Let's say you're writing a web crawler.

02:11:34.561 --> 02:11:39.037
So you have a bunch of URLs that you want to crawl from this website.

02:11:39.579 --> 02:11:43.776
And so you really want to have those crawlers run kind of in parallel.

02:11:44.539 --> 02:11:46.112
And so you want to spawn each one.

02:11:47.139 --> 02:11:53.143
But after you've initiated all of these tasks that are all going to be downloading a different URL,

02:11:53.747 --> 02:11:55.642
you want to wait for all of them to finish.

02:11:56.334 --> 02:11:58.527
But how do you know when they've all finished?

02:11:58.928 --> 02:11:59.069
Well,

02:11:59.069 --> 02:12:00.053
you could have a vector,

02:12:00.435 --> 02:12:01.660
and then like every spawn,

02:12:01.680 --> 02:12:03.267
you stick the join handle into the vector,

02:12:03.829 --> 02:12:05.216
and then after you've spawned all of them,

02:12:05.277 --> 02:12:07.147
you loop over the vector and you wait each one.

02:12:08.369 --> 02:12:09.113
That does work,

02:12:09.173 --> 02:12:10.781
but it's not really what you want to do.

02:12:11.263 --> 02:12:12.498
You can instead use a join set.

02:12:12.923 --> 02:12:15.232
So the idea of a join set is you construct one,

02:12:16.176 --> 02:12:21.536
and then you call spawn and you pass it a future that it will then call Tokyo spawn on,

02:12:21.937 --> 02:12:25.456
and it will take the returning join handle and sort of stick it inside itself,

02:12:25.597 --> 02:12:26.603
inside of the join set.

02:12:27.275 --> 02:12:27.596
And then,

02:12:27.716 --> 02:12:28.238
crucially,

02:12:29.140 --> 02:12:32.951
joinset has a joinNext method that is asynchronous.

02:12:33.191 --> 02:12:38.831
You can call it on the loop in order to get the output results of each spawn future as they resolved.

02:12:39.252 --> 02:12:40.078
And importantly,

02:12:40.561 --> 02:12:42.291
this happens in any order.

02:12:43.031 --> 02:12:43.152
So,

02:12:43.433 --> 02:12:45.942
imagine again that you have this setup where you have these,

02:12:46.544 --> 02:12:48.382
let's say you're crawling 10,000 URLs.

02:12:48.707 --> 02:12:52.424
You would end up with a vector that's 10,000 join handles long.

02:12:53.167 --> 02:12:54.555
If you then write your for loop,

02:12:55.037 --> 02:12:58.816
what will actually happen is you wait for the first URL that you spawned to finish,

02:12:59.117 --> 02:13:01.167
then you went for the second URL you spawned to finish,

02:13:01.247 --> 02:13:01.632
then the third,

02:13:01.632 --> 02:13:02.137
then the fourth,

02:13:02.177 --> 02:13:02.299
etc.

02:13:03.107 --> 02:13:06.340
But it could be that URL number 18 finished way before

02:13:06.681 --> 02:13:07.344
URL number one.

02:13:08.430 --> 02:13:08.557
And

02:13:08.991 --> 02:13:09.953
With this vector approach,

02:13:10.174 --> 02:13:11.016
you wouldn't know that,

02:13:11.016 --> 02:13:13.141
you wouldn't get to print anything until the first one is finished,

02:13:13.381 --> 02:13:15.406
even if that might be the slowest one to crawl,

02:13:15.446 --> 02:13:17.089
it's like some giant website or something.

02:13:18.690 --> 02:13:19.452
With join set,

02:13:19.752 --> 02:13:20.814
when you call join next,

02:13:20.834 --> 02:13:21.836
what that means is,

02:13:22.377 --> 02:13:28.989
give me the output of the futures that I have spawned in whatever order they become available in.

02:13:29.770 --> 02:13:33.480
So this can be a super useful way to keep track of large numbers of futures,

02:13:34.021 --> 02:13:37.029
and then make sure that you wait for them or collect the results after the fact.

02:13:39.607 --> 02:13:40.611
That is all it really does,

02:13:41.736 --> 02:13:43.201
and it's useful to know about.

02:13:44.964 --> 02:13:48.337
Do notice though that it specifically is for spawning.

02:13:49.159 --> 02:13:52.237
So this will use Tokyo spawn behind the scenes.

02:13:52.317 --> 02:13:53.897
It will run them as parallel tasks.

02:13:54.339 --> 02:13:57.517
It is not for sort of local concurrency.

02:13:57.638 --> 02:14:00.777
So what I mean by that is it's not for if you have a,

02:14:01.139 --> 02:14:04.217
you already have a top level task and you don't want to spawn them.

02:14:04.297 --> 02:14:07.657
You just want to run them concurrently inside of the current task.

02:14:08.057 --> 02:14:09.777
Then a join set does not let you do that.

02:14:15.536 --> 02:14:15.918
Unless

02:14:16.340 --> 02:14:18.649
I have missed something.

02:14:18.969 --> 02:14:19.107
No.

02:14:23.955 --> 02:14:24.660
For that,

02:14:24.841 --> 02:14:25.869
I don't know.

02:14:26.932 --> 02:14:29.709
I don't think Tokyo has an equivalent to this.

02:14:31.276 --> 02:14:33.989
Let me see just in case they've added it and I'm lying.

02:14:39.937 --> 02:14:40.060
No,

02:14:40.121 --> 02:14:40.509
it does not.

02:14:40.889 --> 02:14:41.023
So.

02:14:42.738 --> 02:14:46.373
I'm not actually going to recommend that you use this because it has a bunch of problems.

02:14:49.707 --> 02:14:56.085
But there is this type called futures unordered that does not spawn and instead just locally looks at them in the current task

02:14:57.407 --> 02:14:59.438
So this is a thing you can use instead,

02:14:59.498 --> 02:15:00.965
but it does have a bunch of problems

02:15:01.387 --> 02:15:12.185
I'm expecting the one day Tokyo will sort of get its own version of this that isn't broken quite a severe way but actually getting this version right like the version that doesn't spawn right is

02:15:12.766 --> 02:15:19.105
Quite complicated and if you look at the the github issues for this type you'll see that there are a bunch of discussions about

02:15:20.099 --> 02:15:21.309
How should this actually work?

02:15:21.671 --> 02:15:22.034
And in fact,

02:15:22.759 --> 02:15:24.349
that's not what I meant to do at all.

02:15:25.353 --> 02:15:26.708
Let me fix that real quick.

02:15:29.561 --> 02:15:29.728
Aha.

02:15:32.923 --> 02:15:34.667
If we look at without boats again,

02:15:35.910 --> 02:15:36.592
you'll see here,

02:15:37.193 --> 02:15:38.877
futures are ordered in the order of futures.

02:15:39.699 --> 02:15:42.977
That talks about this exact type and why it's actually pretty complicated to get right.

02:15:43.599 --> 02:15:45.917
So I'd recommend you read that if you really want to dig into it.

02:15:46.379 --> 02:15:49.437
But know the join set is very often the thing that you want,

02:15:49.919 --> 02:15:55.757
specifically because usually you do want to spawn these so that they can execute in parallel and not just concurrently.

02:15:56.299 --> 02:15:57.677
What I mean by in parallel is that

02:15:58.118 --> 02:16:01.853
the different tasks that you spawn get to work on different worker threads at the same time.

02:16:02.236 --> 02:16:03.504
Whereas if you don't spawn them,

02:16:03.565 --> 02:16:04.833
if you just sort of join them,

02:16:05.134 --> 02:16:08.613
then they're only executing on a single worker thread at a time.

02:16:13.895 --> 02:16:14.076
Okay,

02:16:14.177 --> 02:16:17.393
questions on join set before I move on?

02:16:29.145 --> 02:16:29.305
Yeah,

02:16:29.366 --> 02:16:31.753
so there's also here in,

02:16:32.114 --> 02:16:33.578
in fact,

02:16:33.598 --> 02:16:34.621
I'll show it in task.

02:16:35.944 --> 02:16:37.389
You'll see that under task,

02:16:37.690 --> 02:16:40.701
there is my line.

02:16:41.414 --> 02:16:41.821
I am lying.

02:16:43.841 --> 02:16:44.724
In the root of Tokyo,

02:16:45.105 --> 02:16:47.613
there's a macro called join and there's a macro called try join.

02:16:48.614 --> 02:16:49.116
And these,

02:16:49.577 --> 02:16:55.053
you actually give a list of futures and it will wait for all of them to resolve.

02:16:55.955 --> 02:16:59.593
And then it will give you back a tuple of the results in the same order you pass them in.

02:16:59.814 --> 02:17:03.550
So this is a way for you to run multiple futures concurrently,

02:17:03.610 --> 02:17:04.313
but not in parallel.

02:17:04.655 --> 02:17:08.013
So within the context of a single task without using any Tokyo spawn.

02:17:09.677 --> 02:17:14.711
But the downside of using join here is that it requires that you have a static number.

02:17:15.633 --> 02:17:20.109
You know at compile time how many different futures you're joining from,

02:17:21.052 --> 02:17:23.202
but they are allowed to have different return values,

02:17:23.222 --> 02:17:24.207
different output values.

02:17:25.613 --> 02:17:26.435
Try join is the same,

02:17:26.576 --> 02:17:28.299
just they're allowed to be fallible.

02:17:39.276 --> 02:17:40.320
If you don't spawn them,

02:17:40.400 --> 02:17:42.226
doesn't Tokyo still work still if needed?

02:17:42.466 --> 02:17:42.587
No.

02:17:43.169 --> 02:17:44.633
So if you use join here,

02:17:45.856 --> 02:17:46.920
or futures unordered,

02:17:47.582 --> 02:17:49.128
that means you're not spawning them.

02:17:49.609 --> 02:17:50.753
If you're not spawning them,

02:17:51.074 --> 02:17:54.951
that means they're just nested futures inside of whatever future you're currently in.

02:17:55.192 --> 02:17:56.236
So they're nested futures,

02:17:56.256 --> 02:17:57.762
they're not top level tasks.

02:17:58.204 --> 02:18:01.295
And because Tokyo only gets to schedule top level tasks,

02:18:01.697 --> 02:18:05.068
it cannot work steal one of these sort of embedded futures down here.

02:18:05.630 --> 02:18:08.193
And so if you use join or futures unordered without spawning,

02:18:08.732 --> 02:18:11.920
Those futures will execute concurrently within this task,

02:18:12.342 --> 02:18:14.066
but they will not get to execute in parallel,

02:18:14.066 --> 02:18:15.449
they will not get to be work stolen.

02:18:21.948 --> 02:18:26.513
Does spawning a Tokyo task allocate a new stack like go or beam instead of using memory as needed?

02:18:27.901 --> 02:18:28.161
Yes,

02:18:28.181 --> 02:18:31.711
you can think of that as roughly right.

02:18:34.197 --> 02:18:36.086
Rust futures are kind of stackless,

02:18:36.146 --> 02:18:38.497
like they don't truly have a stack.

02:18:38.677 --> 02:18:40.027
They're more like state machines.

02:18:41.397 --> 02:18:43.184
But when you spawn a task,

02:18:43.244 --> 02:18:47.975
it does get its own heap allocation for the task and for the state machine.

02:18:53.757 --> 02:19:01.222
What's a good way to pause all tasks on join all temporarily until something is done for it to be resumed?

02:19:01.889 --> 02:19:04.029
You'd want to use join plus select.

02:19:04.069 --> 02:19:05.324
I'll talk about select in a moment.

02:19:09.837 --> 02:19:10.018
Okay,

02:19:11.964 --> 02:19:14.232
moving on to Select,

02:19:14.272 --> 02:19:14.653
in fact.

02:19:15.153 --> 02:19:15.455
All right,

02:19:15.515 --> 02:19:22.673
so Select is one of the coolest features of Async and also the easiest one to burn yourself on.

02:19:24.134 --> 02:19:26.460
The idea behind

02:19:28.365 --> 02:19:31.553
Select is that you have a bunch of different features.

02:19:32.599 --> 02:19:35.973
and you want to wait for one of them to complete.

02:19:36.675 --> 02:19:38.673
This could be sort of the first one to complete.

02:19:38.994 --> 02:19:42.273
Another name for select that you might think about in your head is race.

02:19:42.874 --> 02:19:45.413
So the idea is that you have multiple futures and they're racing,

02:19:45.613 --> 02:19:47.433
and you just want whichever one finished first,

02:19:47.674 --> 02:19:49.593
you want to do something when that one finishes,

02:19:49.895 --> 02:19:51.033
and then forget about the other ones.

02:19:52.115 --> 02:20:00.653
Common examples of these are things like wait for a TCP packet or the user to press control C.

02:20:01.926 --> 02:20:07.365
Or wait for an input on this TCP channel or on standard in.

02:20:08.206 --> 02:20:18.485
Or wait for a new message on this channel or for this write to complete.

02:20:20.586 --> 02:20:20.927
Or,

02:20:21.348 --> 02:20:21.589
you know,

02:20:21.769 --> 02:20:28.445
wait for input on this channel or for this notify to complete that tells me that I should shut down early.

02:20:29.826 --> 02:20:31.505
Select embodies all of these.

02:20:32.377 --> 02:20:33.420
When you write a select,

02:20:33.761 --> 02:20:37.573
the idea is that you write a bunch of arms inside of the select.

02:20:38.495 --> 02:20:40.873
I wish they had an actual example here.

02:20:41.056 --> 02:20:41.223
Ah,

02:20:41.223 --> 02:20:41.453
they do.

02:20:42.275 --> 02:20:43.301
So when you write a select,

02:20:43.603 --> 02:20:45.533
you write a bunch of arms for the select.

02:20:46.194 --> 02:20:49.753
Each arm has something that needs to be a future.

02:20:50.035 --> 02:20:50.577
So in this case,

02:20:50.638 --> 02:20:53.853
doStuffAsync is some method that runs a future.

02:20:54.273 --> 02:20:57.713
And moreAsyncWork is also a function that produces a future.

02:20:59.203 --> 02:20:59.364
And...

02:21:00.718 --> 02:21:02.142
When you use select in this way,

02:21:02.584 --> 02:21:05.833
what's going to happen under the hood is you construct each of those features.

02:21:06.013 --> 02:21:07.043
They're embedded features,

02:21:07.043 --> 02:21:08.233
so they're not top-level tasks.

02:21:08.733 --> 02:21:09.460
Embedded features,

02:21:09.702 --> 02:21:10.933
they get to run concurrently.

02:21:11.734 --> 02:21:13.722
And whichever one finishes first,

02:21:14.083 --> 02:21:16.753
we're going to execute the block under that one.

02:21:17.516 --> 02:21:19.513
And then we're going to drop all the other ones.

02:21:19.915 --> 02:21:20.478
All the other ones,

02:21:20.478 --> 02:21:22.026
we're just going to drop them,

02:21:22.448 --> 02:21:23.513
not do anything more with them.

02:21:24.228 --> 02:21:25.812
So let's say this one finishes first,

02:21:26.113 --> 02:21:27.376
then we're going to go into this arm,

02:21:27.396 --> 02:21:28.519
we're going to execute this code,

02:21:28.719 --> 02:21:31.225
and then we're going to continue from after the select.

02:21:32.786 --> 02:21:33.427
So for example,

02:21:33.767 --> 02:21:38.194
here you can see we are selecting over two different streams,

02:21:38.775 --> 02:21:40.517
and if you go into this one,

02:21:40.597 --> 02:21:43.802
then the V will be the V we bound back from this next call,

02:21:44.122 --> 02:21:45.344
and you get to access that in there,

02:21:45.624 --> 02:21:46.345
and similarly here.

02:21:49.205 --> 02:21:52.416
And you can do the same over things like a sleep,

02:21:52.637 --> 02:21:52.777
right?

02:21:52.837 --> 02:21:54.777
So this is one way to implement a timeout,

02:21:55.220 --> 02:21:57.477
is that you call stream.next in a select,

02:21:57.838 --> 02:22:02.596
and the other arm is you're waiting on some sleep future,

02:22:02.957 --> 02:22:03.097
right?

02:22:03.218 --> 02:22:05.330
And so if the sleep finishes first,

02:22:05.411 --> 02:22:06.497
then you go into this arm,

02:22:07.139 --> 02:22:09.232
and if the stream.next finishes first,

02:22:09.232 --> 02:22:09.977
you go into this arm.

02:22:10.582 --> 02:22:12.457
And so what that will be is a timeout.

02:22:15.537 --> 02:22:15.658
So,

02:22:16.100 --> 02:22:17.886
select is useful for all sorts of things,

02:22:17.987 --> 02:22:25.520
anything where you want to wait for multiple different kinds of things and do different kinds of things in return or in response to them finishing.

02:22:27.093 --> 02:22:30.248
Before I talk about the complications around select and about cancellation,

02:22:30.670 --> 02:22:32.551
does the basic premise of select make sense?

02:22:50.398 --> 02:22:53.504
Large select blocks are a pain because the LSP basically doesn't work inside them.

02:22:54.265 --> 02:22:57.521
One of the pains of select is that it's a giant macro.

02:22:58.485 --> 02:22:59.091
And that means that...

02:23:00.877 --> 02:23:01.058
Like,

02:23:01.178 --> 02:23:04.489
IDE integration often doesn't understand the syntax because it's,

02:23:05.031 --> 02:23:05.974
as far as it can see,

02:23:05.974 --> 02:23:08.672
it's just arbitrary macro input code.

02:23:08.973 --> 02:23:10.287
So it doesn't actually know what it turns into.

02:23:10.853 --> 02:23:13.366
So large select macros tend to be pretty annoying.

02:23:14.733 --> 02:23:20.736
Usually you'll want to keep the select pretty slim and then move the actual logic into separate functions.

02:23:32.858 --> 02:23:35.565
Why is there no await on the async functions inside of the select?

02:23:35.745 --> 02:23:37.285
How does Rust run them without the await?

02:23:37.766 --> 02:23:38.470
So the answer to that,

02:23:39.496 --> 02:23:41.085
why is there not a.await here?

02:23:41.827 --> 02:23:43.175
And the answer to that is because

02:23:43.899 --> 02:23:48.465
Tokyo's select macro expects that everything that's passed here is a future.

02:23:48.985 --> 02:23:54.085
And so the expanded version of the macro will have a.await in there.

02:23:54.868 --> 02:23:56.458
But you don't write the await yourself.

02:23:56.961 --> 02:23:59.835
And the reason for that is because if you wrote the await yourself,

02:24:00.297 --> 02:24:03.378
you could in theory pass in something that wasn't a future.

02:24:03.801 --> 02:24:05.194
And then all of this would get really weird.

02:24:05.941 --> 02:24:09.621
The slightly more complicated answer is that it doesn't actually call.08 for you.

02:24:09.803 --> 02:24:10.779
It doesn't add a.08.

02:24:11.002 --> 02:24:15.217
It has to deal with the underlying pull calls for various reasons.

02:24:16.461 --> 02:24:20.980
But the net way to think about it is the things you passed in must be futures.

02:24:21.341 --> 02:24:21.572
Therefore,

02:24:21.572 --> 02:24:21.761
you

02:24:22.022 --> 02:24:23.910
Because Tokyo knows they must be futures,

02:24:24.151 --> 02:24:25.537
you don't have to write the.08 yourself.

02:24:28.387 --> 02:24:31.359
What's the behavior of SELECT when multiple futures are ready with the result?

02:24:32.123 --> 02:24:32.324
Yeah,

02:24:32.646 --> 02:24:33.613
so this can happen.

02:24:36.265 --> 02:24:41.340
Usually this happens because multiple of the futures were actually ready before the SELECT even started.

02:24:42.102 --> 02:24:44.069
But it could also be that during the execution,

02:24:44.390 --> 02:24:47.139
multiple of them happened to technically be ready,

02:24:47.922 --> 02:24:50.512
but because this is all single-threaded,

02:24:50.552 --> 02:24:51.797
like there's no actual parallelism,

02:24:51.797 --> 02:24:52.580
it's just concurrency,

02:24:53.123 --> 02:24:53.283
what

02:24:53.786 --> 02:24:56.540
SELECT is really doing is it's calling pull.

02:24:57.007 --> 02:24:59.017
on all of the futures over and over.

02:25:00.465 --> 02:25:01.449
It's not actually that dumb,

02:25:01.449 --> 02:25:03.741
it has optimization so it doesn't do it unnecessarily,

02:25:04.062 --> 02:25:04.967
but you can think of it as,

02:25:05.369 --> 02:25:06.836
it calls poll on the first future.

02:25:07.379 --> 02:25:08.243
If that's not ready,

02:25:08.284 --> 02:25:09.570
it calls poll on the second future.

02:25:09.610 --> 02:25:10.253
If that's not ready,

02:25:10.274 --> 02:25:11.520
it calls poll on the third future.

02:25:11.861 --> 02:25:12.806
If the third future is ready,

02:25:13.108 --> 02:25:15.098
then it goes into that arm,

02:25:15.198 --> 02:25:15.861
executes that code,

02:25:16.243 --> 02:25:17.671
and then exits from the select.

02:25:18.032 --> 02:25:18.495
Otherwise,

02:25:18.495 --> 02:25:19.741
it goes to check whether the fourth,

02:25:20.384 --> 02:25:21.650
polling the fourth future is ready,

02:25:21.971 --> 02:25:22.112
etc.

02:25:23.324 --> 02:25:24.792
And then if it gets to the bottom,

02:25:24.792 --> 02:25:25.937
it goes back to the first one again.

02:25:26.238 --> 02:25:28.607
That's sort of how you can think of the implementation of select,

02:25:28.648 --> 02:25:31.017
even though in reality it is smarter than that.

02:25:32.240 --> 02:25:33.330
But in terms of fairness,

02:25:33.391 --> 02:25:34.097
it's a good question.

02:25:34.277 --> 02:25:34.560
Like,

02:25:34.621 --> 02:25:36.517
what if multiple futures are in fact ready?

02:25:36.658 --> 02:25:37.677
Which one does it choose?

02:25:38.178 --> 02:25:39.365
And the answer to that is,

02:25:39.405 --> 02:25:39.969
you'll see here,

02:25:40.291 --> 02:25:41.437
there's a section on fairness.

02:25:41.980 --> 02:25:42.803
And by default,

02:25:42.883 --> 02:25:46.257
select randomly chooses which branch to execute first.

02:25:46.659 --> 02:25:49.617
So you get a random branch that is ready.

02:25:51.341 --> 02:25:52.786
So that if you call select in a root,

02:25:52.806 --> 02:25:53.388
for example,

02:25:53.569 --> 02:25:56.097
you don't always end up with the first branch being the one that's taken.

02:25:57.300 --> 02:25:59.057
There are ways to override this.

02:25:59.138 --> 02:26:02.348
Like you can make a branch be biased to say,

02:26:02.850 --> 02:26:05.277
always choose this arm if it's ready.

02:26:05.698 --> 02:26:06.222
Otherwise,

02:26:06.262 --> 02:26:08.037
just do fair among the remaining ones.

02:26:08.517 --> 02:26:09.625
But this is like...

02:26:11.033 --> 02:26:12.797
There are some subtleties involved here,

02:26:12.797 --> 02:26:17.269
and if you actually care about exactly which arm gets executed when multiple are ready,

02:26:17.550 --> 02:26:18.695
you should read this paragraph,

02:26:19.156 --> 02:26:21.003
or this sort of little section,

02:26:21.465 --> 02:26:22.649
to figure out what's right for you.

02:26:27.496 --> 02:26:29.549
Is Tokyo Select any different from Future Select?

02:26:31.015 --> 02:26:33.263
I don't remember the exact details of Future Select.

02:26:33.303 --> 02:26:34.969
I think they're fairly similar,

02:26:36.193 --> 02:26:38.681
but there are a couple of ways in which they're different,

02:26:38.742 --> 02:26:39.685
such as I think

02:26:40.026 --> 02:26:41.551
Future Select requires a weight,

02:26:41.591 --> 02:26:41.952
whereas the

02:26:43.015 --> 02:26:43.957
Tokyo one does not.

02:26:45.902 --> 02:26:47.547
But they're mostly similar.

02:26:47.767 --> 02:26:49.232
You can think of them as mostly similar.

02:26:58.614 --> 02:27:01.064
Bias can only be added once to the top of the macro,

02:27:01.205 --> 02:27:02.289
not per arm.

02:27:03.298 --> 02:27:03.419
Ah,

02:27:03.500 --> 02:27:03.743
sorry,

02:27:03.803 --> 02:27:04.066
yes.

02:27:04.429 --> 02:27:05.053
Biased is,

02:27:06.178 --> 02:27:08.228
prefer them in the order they're listed.

02:27:08.691 --> 02:27:10.339
So you set it once for the whole select,

02:27:10.359 --> 02:27:12.429
you don't get to choose which arms are biased.

02:27:12.611 --> 02:27:13.177
Totally right.

02:27:15.298 --> 02:27:15.500
Okay.

02:27:16.913 --> 02:27:19.148
So that's the reasons why select is nice.

02:27:19.872 --> 02:27:22.047
Then we get to the reason why select is complicated.

02:27:22.429 --> 02:27:24.382
And that has to do with something called cancellation safety.

02:27:26.597 --> 02:27:26.738
So,

02:27:28.471 --> 02:27:30.682
Let's imagine that we have the following.

02:27:36.572 --> 02:27:37.497
Let's do a loop.

02:27:37.758 --> 02:27:39.848
We have a select.

02:27:43.889 --> 02:27:46.904
And inside of the select we have one arm that is

02:28:04.363 --> 02:28:05.693
Read a certain value.

02:28:07.487 --> 02:28:07.893
Does something.

02:28:08.735 --> 02:28:10.340
We have another that is

02:28:12.166 --> 02:28:14.253
Tokyo time sleep.

02:28:39.283 --> 02:28:39.483
Okay,

02:28:40.004 --> 02:28:41.065
so let's say I have this.

02:28:43.948 --> 02:28:44.876
Let's assume that

02:28:45.280 --> 02:28:45.401
I...

02:28:46.435 --> 02:28:47.027
Yeah, that's fine.

02:28:49.918 --> 02:28:50.787
I'll just write this.

02:28:50.907 --> 02:28:54.147
So we have read a certijsonvalue,

02:28:55.975 --> 02:28:56.317
fn,

02:28:56.981 --> 02:28:57.947
and it returns a...

02:29:00.729 --> 02:29:03.907
Everyone knows that a certijsonvalue is actually just a string.

02:29:05.375 --> 02:29:06.107
And this is a to-do.

02:29:08.105 --> 02:29:08.285
Okay,

02:29:08.607 --> 02:29:11.038
so let's say that we have this use of the select macro in a loop.

02:29:11.419 --> 02:29:12.202
The idea here,

02:29:12.322 --> 02:29:13.746
the intent of the loop,

02:29:14.107 --> 02:29:14.328
right,

02:29:14.448 --> 02:29:14.829
is that

02:29:15.752 --> 02:29:19.464
I want to be reading stuff into a certi.json value,

02:29:19.946 --> 02:29:22.155
but every second I want to write zzz.

02:29:23.200 --> 02:29:27.662
I just want to do that and then I want to keep going around until I get a certi.json value out,

02:29:27.863 --> 02:29:31.139
and it's only when I actually get the value out that I'm ready to print something.

02:29:33.354 --> 02:29:33.675
In fact,

02:29:34.176 --> 02:29:37.606
let's make this a little bit more interesting and make it be a...

02:29:41.088 --> 02:29:41.209
No,

02:29:41.450 --> 02:29:42.595
string is fine.

02:29:44.363 --> 02:29:45.631
So now the question becomes,

02:29:46.295 --> 02:29:47.301
what goes in here?

02:29:47.663 --> 02:29:50.758
Let me write something that's not cancellation safe to show you what can go wrong.

02:29:51.783 --> 02:29:58.073
I have a buff here that is 1024,

02:29:58.073 --> 02:29:59.375
and I do something like,

02:30:01.077 --> 02:30:03.000
let's say I have a TCP here.

02:30:07.170 --> 02:30:07.451
Yeah.

02:30:10.370 --> 02:30:18.500
TCP stream connect await unwrap.

02:30:25.287 --> 02:30:30.680
So here this takes a new TCP stream.

02:30:33.747 --> 02:30:37.006
And down here I do tcp.read.

02:30:37.912 --> 02:30:38.773
mute buff,

02:30:39.154 --> 02:30:39.274
oh,

02:30:39.274 --> 02:30:39.554
wait.

02:30:44.298 --> 02:30:44.598
unwrap.

02:30:46.200 --> 02:30:51.704
And then what I actually want to do here is loop.

02:30:51.784 --> 02:30:59.631
Actually,

02:30:59.991 --> 02:31:02.971
let me just do s is string near

02:31:05.973 --> 02:31:20.890
like this and then I do s dot push stir or push buff n and then if s

02:31:20.930 --> 02:31:26.499
dot len is greater than 100 then I return s

02:31:30.545 --> 02:31:34.871
0 u h and bring me a Tokyo TCP stream

02:31:36.290 --> 02:31:39.387
And bring me read async redext.

02:31:41.448 --> 02:31:44.907
And that's fine.

02:31:47.178 --> 02:31:48.967
We'll just assert that this is UTF-8.

02:31:49.369 --> 02:31:49.686
Why not?

02:31:56.954 --> 02:31:57.347
All right.

02:31:57.728 --> 02:32:00.487
So now I've written a readAssertedJsonValue that just returns a string.

02:32:02.051 --> 02:32:03.987
I guess assertedJsonValue here is a lie.

02:32:04.348 --> 02:32:05.307
This is really readAstring.

02:32:06.374 --> 02:32:08.520
Read a string of 100 charis.

02:32:10.204 --> 02:32:11.127
That's really what I've written,

02:32:11.407 --> 02:32:12.891
so let's name it like that.

02:32:15.071 --> 02:32:16.114
So this all looks fine,

02:32:16.636 --> 02:32:16.816
right?

02:32:17.840 --> 02:32:18.522
Sort of naively,

02:32:18.662 --> 02:32:18.883
right?

02:32:19.204 --> 02:32:21.371
This asynchronous function creates a string,

02:32:21.912 --> 02:32:22.554
it has a buffer,

02:32:22.855 --> 02:32:23.938
it reads into the buffer,

02:32:24.400 --> 02:32:27.047
it keeps pushing onto the string,

02:32:27.509 --> 02:32:29.775
I don't actually need the n here,

02:32:29.876 --> 02:32:29.996
no,

02:32:30.016 --> 02:32:30.798
I do need the n here.

02:32:32.022 --> 02:32:34.650
It keeps reading bytes out of the TCP stream,

02:32:35.414 --> 02:32:36.357
parsing them as a string,

02:32:36.438 --> 02:32:38.205
pushing them onto the string it's accumulating,

02:32:38.466 --> 02:32:40.515
and once the string is greater than 100 characters,

02:32:40.776 --> 02:32:41.459
then it returns us.

02:32:42.062 --> 02:32:42.785
Looks great,

02:32:43.247 --> 02:32:43.387
right?

02:32:44.683 --> 02:32:49.543
The problem here is what happens if this connection is slow.

02:32:51.167 --> 02:32:52.753
So imagine that we go through this loop,

02:32:53.134 --> 02:32:54.499
so we enter the loop first,

02:32:54.720 --> 02:32:55.563
we go into the select,

02:32:55.985 --> 02:32:58.134
and then the select tries to execute this function,

02:32:58.796 --> 02:32:59.680
this function runs,

02:32:59.880 --> 02:33:00.643
it allocates a buffer,

02:33:01.083 --> 02:33:02.207
it does a tcp read,

02:33:02.990 --> 02:33:04.013
and let's say it gets,

02:33:04.013 --> 02:33:05.017
I don't know,

02:33:05.378 --> 02:33:06.461
it gets 10 bytes,

02:33:06.562 --> 02:33:07.103
10 characters.

02:33:07.764 --> 02:33:08.789
So it takes 10 characters,

02:33:08.869 --> 02:33:10.275
it pushes it onto the string,

02:33:11.158 --> 02:33:12.423
the length is not greater than 100,

02:33:12.563 --> 02:33:13.367
so it doesn't return,

02:33:13.508 --> 02:33:14.030
it loops,

02:33:14.311 --> 02:33:15.035
it goes back here,

02:33:15.336 --> 02:33:16.963
and now it tries to do a tcp read again,

02:33:17.325 --> 02:33:18.090
and remembering now,

02:33:18.452 --> 02:33:20.143
this now has 10 characters in it.

02:33:20.651 --> 02:33:20.872
right?

02:33:21.293 --> 02:33:24.725
But this await realizes there's no more data to read at the moment.

02:33:24.765 --> 02:33:25.587
So it goes to sleep,

02:33:25.647 --> 02:33:26.169
it yields.

02:33:26.832 --> 02:33:27.012
Okay.

02:33:27.032 --> 02:33:29.722
So that means that we end up back here up at the select,

02:33:30.023 --> 02:33:31.729
the select tried to execute this,

02:33:31.810 --> 02:33:33.035
but this future isn't ready yet.

02:33:33.276 --> 02:33:35.585
So it then goes to await the next future.

02:33:36.087 --> 02:33:36.267
Okay.

02:33:36.548 --> 02:33:37.311
So that's a sleep.

02:33:37.672 --> 02:33:37.873
Great.

02:33:38.194 --> 02:33:40.280
So it now tries to await the sleep.

02:33:40.802 --> 02:33:42.467
So now we have two futures that are,

02:33:42.908 --> 02:33:43.210
and you know,

02:33:43.190 --> 02:33:43.571
it hasn't,

02:33:43.612 --> 02:33:44.677
a second hasn't passed yet.

02:33:44.898 --> 02:33:46.144
So now it's two futures.

02:33:46.505 --> 02:33:48.067
Both of those futures are not runnable.

02:33:49.088 --> 02:33:52.483
And so now the select kind of just waits for one of them to become runnable.

02:33:53.350 --> 02:33:53.697
So far,

02:33:53.717 --> 02:33:54.023
so good.

02:33:54.931 --> 02:33:56.423
Now let's imagine that...

02:33:59.452 --> 02:34:00.515
one second passes.

02:34:00.876 --> 02:34:02.501
So this future now becomes runnable,

02:34:02.661 --> 02:34:06.292
like the IO event queue or like the thing that drives timers rather,

02:34:07.456 --> 02:34:09.682
now has a full second expired.

02:34:09.783 --> 02:34:13.514
It realizes that this particular sleep future should now be awoken.

02:34:13.534 --> 02:34:16.883
It calls wake on the waker for this future.

02:34:17.305 --> 02:34:20.575
That moves that future from non-runnable to runnable.

02:34:20.877 --> 02:34:22.201
The select picks up on that.

02:34:22.583 --> 02:34:23.907
And so it goes around again.

02:34:24.721 --> 02:34:26.509
It might even try to pull this future again,

02:34:26.529 --> 02:34:28.175
but it still says I don't have any more bytes.

02:34:28.860 --> 02:34:29.795
So it goes to this one.

02:34:30.098 --> 02:34:31.115
This one now resolves.

02:34:31.296 --> 02:34:32.735
So we enter this block.

02:34:34.078 --> 02:34:35.128
Now that we've entered this block,

02:34:35.148 --> 02:34:35.915
we do this print.

02:34:36.278 --> 02:34:37.655
And then we finish the select.

02:34:38.099 --> 02:34:39.751
And when we finish the select,

02:34:39.811 --> 02:34:40.395
what happens?

02:34:41.117 --> 02:34:44.235
All the other futures that didn't finish get dropped.

02:34:44.677 --> 02:34:47.195
That means that this future gets dropped.

02:34:48.610 --> 02:34:55.147
And then we go back around the loop and then we do it again and we construct a new future for this and a new future for that.

02:34:55.829 --> 02:34:59.187
The problem is these 10 characters that we've already read.

02:35:00.790 --> 02:35:04.187
Because they were in this future the first time around the loop.

02:35:05.148 --> 02:35:11.119
And then when we dropped this future at the point of finishing this block,

02:35:11.540 --> 02:35:15.427
then those 10 characters are dropped because they were contained within the future.

02:35:16.747 --> 02:35:18.253
And so once that happened,

02:35:19.056 --> 02:35:20.400
then we drop those characters,

02:35:20.420 --> 02:35:21.283
they're gone forever.

02:35:23.125 --> 02:35:24.610
So when we go back around the loop,

02:35:25.252 --> 02:35:28.403
and then we create a new instance of this future,

02:35:29.065 --> 02:35:31.273
that means we call this function afresh.

02:35:31.675 --> 02:35:33.883
It starts a new string with no characters in it,

02:35:34.064 --> 02:35:35.270
and then it starts reading into this.

02:35:35.812 --> 02:35:36.636
So we've lost,

02:35:36.697 --> 02:35:38.043
we've dropped on the floor,

02:35:38.363 --> 02:35:39.883
10 characters that we're never getting back.

02:35:41.932 --> 02:35:42.835
And so we might actually,

02:35:42.855 --> 02:35:43.979
if this connection is slow enough,

02:35:44.160 --> 02:35:46.107
we might never get into this branch,

02:35:46.389 --> 02:35:48.039
because we keep reading a couple of characters,

02:35:48.220 --> 02:35:49.507
but then we keep hitting the timeout,

02:35:49.808 --> 02:35:52.260
which then causes us to exit the select,

02:35:52.341 --> 02:35:53.667
which causes us to drop the future,

02:35:54.047 --> 02:35:55.920
which causes us to drop all the characters we read,

02:35:56.161 --> 02:35:57.107
and then we loop back around.

02:35:58.636 --> 02:36:02.531
This is an example of the problem of cancellation.

02:36:02.932 --> 02:36:07.241
The problem of cancellation when you're using selects is that you have a future that got canceled,

02:36:07.241 --> 02:36:07.922
it got aborted,

02:36:07.922 --> 02:36:08.744
it got dropped,

02:36:09.144 --> 02:36:12.691
and it had some state that was actually important that went away.

02:36:13.132 --> 02:36:16.251
These 10 bytes are just as if they were never read.

02:36:17.271 --> 02:36:20.382
And this can lead you to really problematic situations like,

02:36:21.144 --> 02:36:23.554
imagine that this was not reading just a string of characters,

02:36:23.675 --> 02:36:25.604
it was actually reading a JSON object.

02:36:26.307 --> 02:36:28.564
Maybe you now dropped the opening curly bracket.

02:36:29.107 --> 02:36:31.275
And so now as you keep going around,

02:36:31.556 --> 02:36:36.314
you actually never end up with a valid JSON object because you never got the opening bracket,

02:36:36.415 --> 02:36:37.479
or rather you got it,

02:36:37.459 --> 02:36:38.283
but then you dropped it.

02:36:39.190 --> 02:36:45.185
This leads to enormous problems down the line where you just silently drop state of futures.

02:36:46.107 --> 02:36:49.761
And this is the really big thing to be aware of whenever you use selects,

02:36:50.363 --> 02:36:54.318
is that either your futures need to be what's known as cancellation safe,

02:36:54.659 --> 02:36:58.006
meaning that they can be resumed without having lost any state.

02:36:58.879 --> 02:36:59.160
Or,

02:37:00.103 --> 02:37:02.350
you need to write your select so that it doesn't matter,

02:37:02.431 --> 02:37:06.072
like these futures are never attempted to be reused.

02:37:06.415 --> 02:37:08.571
But cancellation safety is usually the thing that you want.

02:37:09.115 --> 02:37:10.787
There are two ways to achieve cancellation safety.

02:37:11.875 --> 02:37:15.104
The first of them is that you'll see on a bunch of

02:37:15.486 --> 02:37:16.308
Tokyo types,

02:37:16.448 --> 02:37:18.775
like if you look at

02:37:19.317 --> 02:37:20.120
MPSC receiver,

02:37:20.140 --> 02:37:20.742
for instance,

02:37:21.344 --> 02:37:24.414
you'll see that the receive method says under cancel safety,

02:37:24.735 --> 02:37:26.053
this method is cancel save.

02:37:26.956 --> 02:37:31.032
If receive is used as an event in Tokyo's select statement and some other branch completes first,

02:37:31.153 --> 02:37:34.028
it is guaranteed that no messages were received on this channel.

02:37:34.731 --> 02:37:39.610
The implication being that there are no messages that might be received and then get lost forever,

02:37:40.031 --> 02:37:42.723
as a result of that future of receive being dropped.

02:37:43.867 --> 02:37:48.483
So receive for an MPC channel is safe to use in this kind of context.

02:37:49.024 --> 02:37:51.923
This asynchronous future is not cancellation safe.

02:37:52.324 --> 02:37:54.974
If you drop its future and then try to resume,

02:37:55.255 --> 02:37:56.660
you will have lost state,

02:37:56.841 --> 02:37:57.820
or you may have lost state.

02:37:58.103 --> 02:37:58.284
You know,

02:37:58.888 --> 02:38:00.036
if it never did any read,

02:38:00.036 --> 02:38:01.063
of course you haven't lost anything.

02:38:02.806 --> 02:38:02.927
So,

02:38:03.829 --> 02:38:04.371
in general,

02:38:04.531 --> 02:38:10.097
you want to read through anything that you use in a select and make sure that they're all cancellation safe.

02:38:10.623 --> 02:38:17.745
And the way to make something cancellation safe if it isn't is to construct the future outside of the loop,

02:38:21.251 --> 02:38:21.792
like this,

02:38:23.855 --> 02:38:25.418
and then in the select,

02:38:26.520 --> 02:38:29.321
use a mutable reference to the future instead.

02:38:30.216 --> 02:38:35.915
Because that way you're never dropping the future when you get to the select because the future was never owned here in the first place.

02:38:36.656 --> 02:38:37.159
And so that way,

02:38:37.179 --> 02:38:37.944
when you go around,

02:38:37.964 --> 02:38:39.895
you're actually resuming the same future.

02:38:41.039 --> 02:38:42.995
This doesn't quite work because of pinning.

02:38:43.777 --> 02:38:45.466
So the actual way that you need to do this,

02:38:45.486 --> 02:38:47.155
and I think there's an example of this down here.

02:38:47.715 --> 02:38:47.836
Oh,

02:38:47.836 --> 02:38:47.958
yeah,

02:38:47.978 --> 02:38:49.735
these are the things that are cancellation safe.

02:38:50.097 --> 02:38:51.395
These are not cancellation safe.

02:38:51.455 --> 02:38:52.175
You need to be careful.

02:38:54.537 --> 02:38:58.335
But there's an example here of how you can avoid this problem.

02:38:59.247 --> 02:38:59.814
Uh.

02:39:01.415 --> 02:39:05.291
where you pin it outside of the loop,

02:39:05.653 --> 02:39:07.211
and then you take a mutable reference.

02:39:07.612 --> 02:39:09.326
This pinning is kind of annoying,

02:39:09.770 --> 02:39:09.931
right?

02:39:10.453 --> 02:39:10.776
You just,

02:39:11.058 --> 02:39:12.510
but it won't compile without it.

02:39:13.113 --> 02:39:14.450
So at least there's that.

02:39:15.684 --> 02:39:15.809
Pin.

02:39:18.173 --> 02:39:22.491
And I think actually we can use std future pin here.

02:39:24.674 --> 02:39:26.271
std task pin.

02:39:27.793 --> 02:39:29.571
std pin pin.

02:39:29.980 --> 02:39:30.185
Okay,

02:39:30.226 --> 02:39:30.411
great.

02:39:31.087 --> 02:39:32.473
Std pin pin.

02:39:35.103 --> 02:39:37.002
And then you can pass a mutable reference to it here instead.

02:39:37.324 --> 02:39:39.941
But you do need to pin it in order to use this trick.

02:39:40.343 --> 02:39:40.865
But once you do,

02:39:41.448 --> 02:39:46.717
then now you don't have to worry about the cancellation safety because you're not ever canceling that future.

02:39:47.483 --> 02:39:49.030
So this is what we mean by cancellation safety.

02:39:51.903 --> 02:39:52.848
I have more to say on this,

02:39:52.868 --> 02:39:54.859
but I'll pause here for questions first.

02:40:09.097 --> 02:40:11.042
It's just only because selected is in a loop.

02:40:14.188 --> 02:40:15.511
If select is not in a loop,

02:40:15.571 --> 02:40:23.107
this tends to not really be a problem because it usually means that you don't care about the other features being dropped.

02:40:23.887 --> 02:40:29.827
Because they were constructed in here and you're never really resuming them because you're not running that line of code again.

02:40:30.367 --> 02:40:33.507
So it only really tends to come up as a problem in a loop.

02:40:34.708 --> 02:40:40.264
You could probably write some code where this problem arises even though you're not using a loop,

02:40:40.304 --> 02:40:41.307
but that is much less common.

02:40:49.290 --> 02:40:50.635
What does pinning do under the hood?

02:40:50.755 --> 02:40:52.032
Does it change the type of fut?

02:40:52.375 --> 02:40:52.496
Yeah,

02:40:52.556 --> 02:41:00.284
so the future type here actually becomes a pin mutable reference to the future that comes in here.

02:41:01.015 --> 02:41:04.933
So it turns this into it's no longer just this future.

02:41:05.295 --> 02:41:05.997
It is actually a pin,

02:41:06.498 --> 02:41:08.785
a pinned mutable reference to that future.

02:41:11.880 --> 02:41:17.204
Does this mean that ideally we need to make sure that all the processes in the HTTP handler is cancel safe?

02:41:18.416 --> 02:41:20.611
I'm not sure what you mean by HTTP handler.

02:41:21.315 --> 02:41:26.326
This only applies to things that are awaited on in a select,

02:41:27.308 --> 02:41:28.651
in the arms,

02:41:28.972 --> 02:41:31.024
the arm definitions of the selects.

02:41:32.497 --> 02:41:32.678
Yeah,

02:41:32.718 --> 02:41:34.704
pain was a good Freudian slip here,

02:41:34.704 --> 02:41:36.670
I agree.

02:41:39.647 --> 02:41:39.767
Yeah,

02:41:39.807 --> 02:41:41.192
so the behavior is different now,

02:41:42.255 --> 02:41:45.445
which is totally correctly pointed out here that here,

02:41:45.987 --> 02:41:47.875
we will now only ever read one of these,

02:41:47.935 --> 02:41:49.561
but that's kind of what we intended,

02:41:49.621 --> 02:41:49.782
right?

02:41:50.063 --> 02:41:51.118
Because we had a break here.

02:41:51.443 --> 02:41:53.808
So we intended for the loop not to continue anyway,

02:41:54.068 --> 02:41:55.050
the moment this resolves.

02:42:02.143 --> 02:42:03.814
Select is more like a future than a loop,

02:42:03.875 --> 02:42:04.116
right?

02:42:05.123 --> 02:42:06.719
So select is.

02:42:08.611 --> 02:42:12.325
A future that internally loops over all of its arms?

02:42:12.867 --> 02:42:14.139
So kind of both?

02:42:14.967 --> 02:42:17.504
You should think of select as being a future.

02:42:18.007 --> 02:42:18.509
It isn't,

02:42:19.132 --> 02:42:20.840
but that is sort of what it is.

02:42:22.327 --> 02:42:24.475
It is also internally kind of like a loop.

02:42:27.807 --> 02:42:30.722
In this scenario the future is never cancelled and is just ignored.

02:42:32.053 --> 02:42:32.645
Um...

02:42:34.313 --> 02:42:34.454
Well,

02:42:34.794 --> 02:42:35.896
in the pin case,

02:42:36.177 --> 02:42:37.379
the future is never cancelled.

02:42:37.720 --> 02:42:38.802
In the old case,

02:42:40.967 --> 02:42:45.159
when we say cancellation safety and when we say a future is cancelled,

02:42:45.500 --> 02:42:49.014
what we mean is that it is dropped before it got to finish.

02:42:49.777 --> 02:42:50.580
So it got cancelled,

02:42:50.580 --> 02:42:51.343
it got aborted,

02:42:51.684 --> 02:42:51.905
right?

02:42:51.985 --> 02:42:53.070
It started doing work,

02:42:53.471 --> 02:42:54.737
it accumulated some state,

02:42:54.979 --> 02:42:57.149
and then we dropped it rather than letting it complete.

02:42:57.230 --> 02:42:57.778
In other words,

02:42:57.778 --> 02:42:58.371
it was cancelled.

02:42:59.949 --> 02:43:01.412
So in this case we did cancel it.

02:43:02.433 --> 02:43:10.107
In the pin case it does not get cancelled because dropping it here does not mean that it doesn't get to do any more work the next time around the loop.

02:43:22.692 --> 02:43:23.797
If we pin the future,

02:43:23.917 --> 02:43:24.640
once it resolves,

02:43:24.700 --> 02:43:26.447
won't that make it a one-shot future?

02:43:26.847 --> 02:43:27.527
I'm not sure I understand.

02:43:28.250 --> 02:43:30.327
So one-shots are different from this.

02:43:30.829 --> 02:43:35.907
One-shot is a mechanism for having two different futures communicate with each other,

02:43:36.228 --> 02:43:38.007
so that one can send a value to the other.

02:43:39.769 --> 02:43:43.227
It has nothing to do with us future-only resolving ones.

02:43:43.628 --> 02:43:45.367
All futures only ever resolve ones.

02:43:52.324 --> 02:43:55.319
This versus calling timeout on Feud in a loop.

02:43:56.243 --> 02:43:56.779
Not sure I follow.

02:43:57.920 --> 02:44:01.799
Could we have made the future cancellation safe by passing in the string that we write to?

02:44:02.300 --> 02:44:02.441
Yeah,

02:44:02.441 --> 02:44:04.639
so that is another way that you could solve this problem.

02:44:04.699 --> 02:44:07.591
So instead of pinning here,

02:44:08.856 --> 02:44:09.579
you could do this.

02:44:20.451 --> 02:44:24.447
And then do mute S.

02:44:25.834 --> 02:44:26.727
And then have this like.

02:44:27.618 --> 02:44:29.462
I guess not return,

02:44:29.682 --> 02:44:31.567
and instead it'll print s here.

02:44:32.228 --> 02:44:33.812
This will take an s,

02:44:33.892 --> 02:44:36.739
which is a mutable reference to a string.

02:44:37.661 --> 02:44:39.967
This no longer gives s here,

02:44:41.089 --> 02:44:41.450
like so.

02:44:42.031 --> 02:44:42.152
Yeah,

02:44:42.212 --> 02:44:46.062
so this is an example of something that would also make it be cancellation safe,

02:44:47.826 --> 02:44:52.915
but that assumes that that's only true if read is cancellation safe.

02:44:54.098 --> 02:44:56.223
And we can check whether read is cancellation safe,

02:44:56.223 --> 02:44:57.085
so if we go to read,

02:44:57.967 --> 02:45:00.232
async read x,

02:45:00.512 --> 02:45:02.714
cancellation safety.

02:45:02.856 --> 02:45:03.774
This method is cancel safe.

02:45:03.835 --> 02:45:06.593
If you use it as an event in Tokyo select and some other branch completes first,

02:45:06.613 --> 02:45:08.371
then it's guaranteed that no data was read.

02:45:08.735 --> 02:45:12.890
So only because of this clause is this safe.

02:45:14.375 --> 02:45:15.283
But given that clause,

02:45:15.626 --> 02:45:16.575
this is cancellation safe.

02:45:17.354 --> 02:45:25.571
And usually I tend to tell people always document the cancellation safety of anything that you call from a select.

02:45:31.552 --> 02:45:31.672
If

02:45:32.013 --> 02:45:34.820
I have some work after the loop that does not depend on the foot,

02:45:36.184 --> 02:45:38.991
we need to manually drop it to avoid unnecessary background processes.

02:45:40.313 --> 02:45:40.474
Okay,

02:45:40.494 --> 02:45:44.471
so this is in the pin case.

02:45:45.571 --> 02:45:46.775
So if we have this,

02:45:47.337 --> 02:45:48.080
then yes,

02:45:48.260 --> 02:45:48.963
down here,

02:45:49.063 --> 02:45:50.247
you might want to drop Vue.

02:45:52.009 --> 02:45:53.836
But it doesn't actually matter because remember,

02:45:54.278 --> 02:45:56.887
this is not an actively running thing.

02:45:57.408 --> 02:45:59.907
This is just the state of the future.

02:46:01.030 --> 02:46:02.987
And so you're not really wasting system resources.

02:46:03.067 --> 02:46:04.807
You're wasting a little bit of stack memory.

02:46:05.509 --> 02:46:08.907
You're not really like wasting compute resources because this future,

02:46:09.269 --> 02:46:11.761
if it's not being awaited or run in a select,

02:46:11.902 --> 02:46:12.947
it doesn't do anything.

02:46:13.308 --> 02:46:14.367
So you're not wasting compute.

02:46:19.729 --> 02:46:24.199
Is whatever Tokyo Sync MPSC uses for cancellation safety the same or related to this mute technique?

02:46:24.707 --> 02:46:24.852
No.

02:46:25.179 --> 02:46:32.679
So the way that you can implement cancellation safety internally in some kind of resource is just by having it do atomic things.

02:46:32.920 --> 02:46:34.849
I don't necessarily mean CPU atomics,

02:46:35.211 --> 02:46:36.879
although that can be the way to do it.

02:46:37.319 --> 02:46:37.658
So that...

02:46:38.777 --> 02:46:48.415
You basically don't have any await points between when you consume a value or like consume a resource like reading bytes from a file socket and when you return them.

02:46:49.016 --> 02:46:51.306
So you know that if you consume the resource,

02:46:51.667 --> 02:46:53.575
then you definitely also returned it.

02:46:53.937 --> 02:46:55.695
That is the way that you guarantee cancellation safety.

02:46:56.176 --> 02:47:03.132
If you consume some resources like you read some bytes off of the wire and then you have some await in there before you return that value,

02:47:03.332 --> 02:47:04.555
then you're not cancellation safe.

02:47:05.752 --> 02:47:07.098
Because you could be dropped.

02:47:07.560 --> 02:47:09.247
At any await point you could be dropped.

02:47:17.223 --> 02:47:19.663
It's funny how cancellation on safe code is still safe rust.

02:47:19.963 --> 02:47:21.900
So safe rust is a very particular meaning,

02:47:22.182 --> 02:47:22.303
right?

02:47:22.443 --> 02:47:27.723
Safe rust means that it cannot have memory on safety.

02:47:28.384 --> 02:47:32.363
Things like one type being treated as another or have undefined behavior.

02:47:33.387 --> 02:47:34.843
There's no undefined behavior here.

02:47:35.064 --> 02:47:36.196
You just dropped a bunch of data,

02:47:36.742 --> 02:47:36.863
right?

02:47:36.923 --> 02:47:38.252
So it's wrong,

02:47:38.615 --> 02:47:39.803
but it's not memory on safety.

02:47:40.187 --> 02:47:41.783
And that's what we mean by safe and rust.

02:47:43.121 --> 02:47:46.635
So this is more of a definitional question of what does safe mean.

02:47:47.736 --> 02:47:49.764
And when we say that something is unsafe,

02:47:50.205 --> 02:47:52.855
do we mean the formal sense of rust on safety?

02:47:53.135 --> 02:47:54.903
Or do we mean unsafe as in general,

02:47:54.944 --> 02:47:57.515
like this could lead to buggy behavior?

02:47:57.876 --> 02:47:59.435
And those are two different meanings of the word.

02:48:06.230 --> 02:48:08.423
What I mean by one shot is that it can't be reused in the select.

02:48:08.523 --> 02:48:11.703
This is only useful in the case where you only want to use this kind of future once.

02:48:15.526 --> 02:48:15.668
Well,

02:48:15.708 --> 02:48:16.540
so sort of,

02:48:16.601 --> 02:48:16.743
right?

02:48:16.803 --> 02:48:18.068
So you could here,

02:48:18.932 --> 02:48:20.438
if you end up in this branch,

02:48:20.579 --> 02:48:21.563
you could then say...

02:48:23.655 --> 02:48:25.491
You could reassign to Futir.

02:48:25.591 --> 02:48:27.410
You couldn't actually do it this way because of the pin.

02:48:27.831 --> 02:48:31.151
But you could imagine that you reconstruct the future in here.

02:48:31.991 --> 02:48:32.254
In fact,

02:48:32.275 --> 02:48:33.044
I think you would use...

02:48:33.692 --> 02:48:33.938
Is it...

02:48:35.402 --> 02:48:36.151
Dot replace?

02:48:37.153 --> 02:48:38.929
I can never quite remember what...

02:48:42.158 --> 02:48:42.844
Pin...

02:48:43.591 --> 02:48:43.873
Set.

02:48:46.931 --> 02:48:47.061
Set.

02:48:49.941 --> 02:48:51.747
So you could do this in order to...

02:48:53.993 --> 02:48:54.995
Once you've read a thing,

02:48:55.275 --> 02:48:56.998
if you actually want to keep looping around,

02:48:57.259 --> 02:48:57.599
then yeah,

02:48:57.619 --> 02:48:59.142
you would replace it with a new future,

02:48:59.803 --> 02:49:04.991
but inside of the pin so that it itself remains cancellation safe.

02:49:12.251 --> 02:49:14.840
So if you want something to happen in one select arm on interval,

02:49:14.900 --> 02:49:16.898
then also the interval should be defined outside the loop,

02:49:16.959 --> 02:49:17.141
right?

02:49:17.384 --> 02:49:17.547
Yes,

02:49:17.547 --> 02:49:18.439
so that's also true.

02:49:18.743 --> 02:49:21.620
So this thing will not happen every second.

02:49:22.223 --> 02:49:25.741
It will happen a second after the start of every select.

02:49:26.243 --> 02:49:28.417
So if you actually wanted something to happen on an interval,

02:49:28.759 --> 02:49:28.900
well,

02:49:28.900 --> 02:49:30.177
you would probably use the interval.

02:49:30.463 --> 02:49:31.157
So Tokyo has a...

02:49:31.586 --> 02:49:31.872
I'm sorry.

02:49:33.702 --> 02:49:35.511
inside of the time module.

02:49:37.235 --> 02:49:40.031
I haven't really talked about time because it's fairly straightforward.

02:49:40.453 --> 02:49:45.151
The only thing to know about here is that there's a minimum limit on how long intervals can be in Tokyo.

02:49:45.552 --> 02:49:46.431
Like it doesn't really support,

02:49:46.531 --> 02:49:47.591
I think intervals shorter than...

02:49:49.400 --> 02:49:50.611
100 milliseconds or something.

02:49:51.993 --> 02:49:54.871
But you can have an interval that you can construct.

02:49:55.731 --> 02:50:00.591
And then what you would call inside of here is.tick on that interval.

02:50:00.691 --> 02:50:03.711
But you would construct the interval outside the loop precisely for this reason.

02:50:04.051 --> 02:50:04.433
And in fact,

02:50:04.433 --> 02:50:05.097
if you look at tick,

02:50:05.399 --> 02:50:06.042
cancel safety,

02:50:06.384 --> 02:50:07.691
this method is cancellation saved.

02:50:08.332 --> 02:50:09.450
So make sure to always check that.

02:50:17.350 --> 02:50:22.047
I wonder if a different select API could exist that makes it less likely to make a mistake here.

02:50:22.047 --> 02:50:23.294
You are not the first person to wonder that,

02:50:23.535 --> 02:50:25.223
and we haven't really come up with one yet.

02:50:25.947 --> 02:50:26.891
If you have a good idea,

02:50:27.012 --> 02:50:27.715
then absolutely,

02:50:27.795 --> 02:50:31.599
but it's actually surprisingly hard to figure out what should happen here.

02:50:32.187 --> 02:50:33.152
One of the questions is,

02:50:33.654 --> 02:50:36.266
should futures be cancelled on drop?

02:50:36.607 --> 02:50:39.046
What should the drop behavior be for a future?

02:50:39.227 --> 02:50:39.990
Currently it means cancel,

02:50:39.990 --> 02:50:42.461
but it's not clear whether that should be the case.

02:50:43.807 --> 02:50:46.527
This also ties into the question of asynchronous drop.

02:50:46.895 --> 02:50:47.477
So currently,

02:50:48.179 --> 02:50:50.507
if you have a future and it implements drop,

02:50:50.708 --> 02:50:53.525
then your implementation of drop is not async.

02:50:54.271 --> 02:50:55.686
Drop is a synchronous method.

02:50:56.231 --> 02:50:58.723
That means you can't do asynchronous things in your drop,

02:50:59.125 --> 02:51:02.162
but trying to fix that is all sorts of complicated for other reasons.

02:51:04.032 --> 02:51:05.257
So this one's tricky.

02:51:11.446 --> 02:51:11.907
All right,

02:51:12.528 --> 02:51:17.038
so that is cancellation safety,

02:51:17.118 --> 02:51:19.403
which mostly comes up in the context of select.

