02:52:35.533 --> 02:52:36.580
But under sync,

02:52:36.620 --> 02:52:38.290
I think there's some interesting stuff.

02:52:40.513 --> 02:52:42.211
I'll talk about cancellation token in a second.

02:52:44.156 --> 02:52:44.970
Delay queues.

02:52:45.031 --> 02:52:45.599
Basically,

02:52:46.065 --> 02:52:46.653
things that are...

02:52:50.184 --> 02:52:54.935
bigger and also a little bit more unstable constructions on top of the Tokyo primitives.

02:52:55.236 --> 02:52:56.681
I mean,

02:52:56.701 --> 02:52:59.651
Tokyo primitives are usually sort of lower level things,

02:52:59.711 --> 02:53:00.895
building blocks that you can use,

02:53:01.135 --> 02:53:04.595
whereas Tokyo Utils tries to provide higher level abstractions on top of that.

02:53:09.177 --> 02:53:12.715
But there are a couple of things that I want to call out from here.

02:53:15.738 --> 02:53:17.407
And they're both unknown.

02:53:17.447 --> 02:53:18.912
One is under task and the other is under.

02:53:23.327 --> 02:53:24.032
Where is the other one?

02:53:25.967 --> 02:53:27.301
Where is task tracker?

02:53:29.678 --> 02:53:29.799
Ha,

02:53:29.919 --> 02:53:30.523
it's even deeper.

02:53:31.554 --> 02:53:31.718
Okay.

02:53:32.187 --> 02:53:34.359
So the first one of these is cancellation token.

02:53:35.987 --> 02:53:41.462
Cancellation token is unrelated to cancellation in terms of select.

02:53:42.790 --> 02:53:47.560
What cancellation token is for is specifically imagine you have this like giant system,

02:53:47.560 --> 02:53:49.042
you have a bunch of Tokyo spawns,

02:53:49.062 --> 02:53:51.467
like you have a bunch of different background tasks running.

02:53:52.030 --> 02:53:52.775
And at some point,

02:53:52.855 --> 02:53:54.687
like the user presses control C.

02:53:56.019 --> 02:53:58.251
and you want to have graceful shutdown.

02:53:58.371 --> 02:54:00.371
You want your entire program to like,

02:54:00.431 --> 02:54:04.931
you want all of those different tasks that you have to start exiting.

02:54:06.514 --> 02:54:08.171
One of the ways you could do this is you could,

02:54:08.251 --> 02:54:11.451
as we talked about on the runtime call shutdown.

02:54:12.196 --> 02:54:12.971
And when you do that,

02:54:13.614 --> 02:54:16.047
the next time every task yields,

02:54:16.268 --> 02:54:16.911
it gets dropped.

02:54:16.991 --> 02:54:18.551
And then eventually all the tasks are dropped.

02:54:18.753 --> 02:54:21.311
And so eventually your shutdown

02:54:22.387 --> 02:54:25.959
returns because all the tasks are gone and now you can shut down.

02:54:26.260 --> 02:54:26.902
But in reality,

02:54:26.922 --> 02:54:29.773
you didn't really let those futures finish up their work.

02:54:30.054 --> 02:54:33.328
You just kind of dropped them when they were in some kind of pending state.

02:54:34.012 --> 02:54:36.803
One way that you can improve on this situation is to use a cancellation token.

02:54:37.863 --> 02:54:39.809
What this type does is that you can,

02:54:40.912 --> 02:54:45.067
it's kind of like a notify and in fact I think it's implemented using notify internally,

02:54:45.630 --> 02:54:46.614
but you construct one,

02:54:47.036 --> 02:54:50.694
you can clone them and give them out to all of your different tasks that you spawn.

02:54:51.659 --> 02:55:04.659
And the idea with it is every cancellation token has a cancelled method that is an asynchronous function that will only return the moment someone calls cancel on the cancellation token.

02:55:05.288 --> 02:55:08.943
But all of the clones of a cancellation token are connected.

02:55:09.424 --> 02:55:12.630
So if you call cancel on any clone of the cancellation token,

02:55:13.151 --> 02:55:19.143
then the canceled future on all the cancellation tokens will suddenly yield.

02:55:19.743 --> 02:55:24.152
So the idea here is that for all of the tasks that you spawn in various places,

02:55:24.492 --> 02:55:30.083
you have them do a select over the main work that they do and canceled.

02:55:31.155 --> 02:55:31.978
And so that way,

02:55:32.299 --> 02:55:34.446
whenever they get this cancelled signal,

02:55:34.767 --> 02:55:37.864
then they can choose what to do in order to clean up and then they can choose to exit.

02:55:38.931 --> 02:55:43.147
So this is a way for you to have one place in your program where you say,

02:55:43.248 --> 02:55:43.489
okay,

02:55:43.930 --> 02:55:44.887
time to shut down.

02:55:45.709 --> 02:55:46.652
And then at that point,

02:55:47.715 --> 02:55:50.665
all of the threads start hitting this clause of their select.

02:55:51.208 --> 02:55:51.673
At that point,

02:55:51.673 --> 02:55:52.705
they can choose what to do.

02:55:52.846 --> 02:55:53.925
Maybe they exit their loop.

02:55:54.205 --> 02:55:55.221
Maybe they do some cleanup,

02:55:55.262 --> 02:55:55.485
whatever.

02:55:55.807 --> 02:55:56.510
But eventually,

02:55:56.832 --> 02:55:57.716
when they get that signal,

02:55:57.757 --> 02:55:59.365
they should know that it's time to wrap up,

02:55:59.765 --> 02:56:01.292
stop reading from channels,

02:56:02.336 --> 02:56:03.802
stop reading from TCP sockets,

02:56:03.822 --> 02:56:04.485
whatever it might be,

02:56:04.806 --> 02:56:08.045
and just sort of finish up and then eventually return.

02:56:08.632 --> 02:56:09.383
And...

02:56:09.657 --> 02:56:10.099
Hopefully,

02:56:10.621 --> 02:56:11.585
at some point after that,

02:56:11.746 --> 02:56:13.152
your runtime should become idle.

02:56:13.493 --> 02:56:22.232
There should no longer be any runnable tasks because they should all have sort of reacted to either this cancellation signal or cascading signals from that.

02:56:22.935 --> 02:56:32.371
Like they were reading from a channel and the sender end of the channel they were reading from has now been closed because that thing saw the cancellation signal.

02:56:32.813 --> 02:56:36.869
So eventually it should propagate all the way down until all of your tasks have gracefully exited.

02:56:37.515 --> 02:56:47.993
And the cancellation token is just a handy means to have the trigger to start a shutdown and the means in which to react to that shutdown signal.

02:56:49.322 --> 02:56:52.605
There is also a stream cancel.

02:56:53.166 --> 02:57:01.553
There's an equivalent type specifically for streams that has a sort of this tripwire thing where you have,

02:57:01.773 --> 02:57:05.977
you can take a stream and you can wrap it with a thing that will close the stream,

02:57:06.037 --> 02:57:10.141
like have the stream start to yield none the moment someone calls cancel on this trigger.

02:57:10.683 --> 02:57:12.247
And so it's the same kind of construction.

02:57:12.568 --> 02:57:17.401
It just forcibly makes a stream start returning none with the same ultimate purpose.

02:57:21.895 --> 02:57:28.728
So this can be a really nice way to give your application the ability to do graceful shutdown,

02:57:29.089 --> 02:57:37.244
but it does require that you thread this tripwire or this cancellation token all the way through your program so that every task has a way to know that,

02:57:37.345 --> 02:57:37.546
okay,

02:57:37.586 --> 02:57:40.719
it's time to shut down now.

02:57:46.104 --> 02:57:46.687
Okay.

02:57:55.109 --> 02:58:09.615
let's see can you keep reading from a channel after the center has been dropped so it depends um if you look at

02:58:11.346 --> 02:58:11.467
the

02:58:12.170 --> 02:58:14.843
Tokyo MPSC channel,

02:58:14.863 --> 02:58:14.984
right?

02:58:15.366 --> 02:58:17.565
It is a multi-producer single consumer.

02:58:18.286 --> 02:58:21.645
And so the rule is that when all the sender handles have been dropped,

02:58:21.986 --> 02:58:24.285
then it's no longer possible to send values into the channel.

02:58:24.647 --> 02:58:26.324
This is considered the termination of the stream.

02:58:26.566 --> 02:58:28.420
And so then poll will start to return none.

02:58:29.306 --> 02:58:31.516
But if one sender is dropped,

02:58:31.797 --> 02:58:37.105
then that doesn't mean that the channel is closed and you will still block waiting for more values.

02:58:38.587 --> 02:58:40.324
There is a way to specifically say

02:58:42.541 --> 02:58:42.966
Or is it...

02:58:49.277 --> 02:58:49.400
No,

02:58:49.441 --> 02:58:49.769
there's not.

02:58:49.949 --> 02:58:50.335
I'm like...

02:58:52.290 --> 02:58:52.613
But yeah,

02:58:52.774 --> 02:58:54.349
so the answer to this is like,

02:58:54.890 --> 02:58:55.433
a channel,

02:58:56.440 --> 02:58:57.849
if all the senders have been dropped,

02:58:58.230 --> 02:59:01.409
then the receiver will still receive whatever's maybe in the channel,

02:59:01.771 --> 02:59:02.862
but after there is no more,

02:59:02.942 --> 02:59:03.589
it'll get a none,

02:59:03.789 --> 02:59:04.639
and then at that point,

02:59:04.700 --> 02:59:05.489
no to stop reading.

02:59:06.031 --> 02:59:06.883
Similar to an iterator,

02:59:07.086 --> 02:59:07.249
really.

02:59:13.298 --> 02:59:14.343
What if you're writing a library,

02:59:14.444 --> 02:59:15.228
like an actor library,

02:59:15.288 --> 02:59:18.865
then it's hard to share the cancellation tokens as the user might create their own one.

02:59:19.408 --> 02:59:19.850
It's true.

02:59:20.191 --> 02:59:32.169
And this is one of the ways in which it would actually be handy if cancellation tokens was in the standard library so that everyone could agree on how to signal it's time to finish now.

02:59:33.292 --> 02:59:34.335
Until that happens,

02:59:34.335 --> 02:59:35.378
and I don't know whether it will,

02:59:35.459 --> 02:59:37.365
it would probably go inside the context maybe,

02:59:38.991 --> 02:59:40.797
until we get something like that,

02:59:41.245 --> 02:59:42.510
If you're a library author,

02:59:43.353 --> 02:59:45.640
you could have sort of two APIs,

02:59:45.701 --> 02:59:45.841
right?

02:59:45.982 --> 02:59:48.621
One that takes a cancellation token and one that does not.

02:59:48.981 --> 02:59:49.786
And if you don't get one,

02:59:50.047 --> 02:59:51.434
you just do whatever you normally do,

02:59:51.535 --> 02:59:56.601
which is you block forever or your awaits might take forever during shutdown.

02:59:56.761 --> 02:59:57.561
You might just get dropped.

02:59:57.881 --> 03:00:00.134
But if the user provides you with a cancellation token,

03:00:00.154 --> 03:00:01.261
then you're willing to respect it.

03:00:02.363 --> 03:00:02.483
That,

03:00:02.483 --> 03:00:02.785
of course,

03:00:02.805 --> 03:00:06.405
would mean that you would take a public dependency on the Tokyo util crate,

03:00:06.668 --> 03:00:07.799
which you might not be willing to do.

03:00:09.444 --> 03:00:11.397
But you're sort of caught between a rock and a hard place here.

03:00:11.798 --> 03:00:18.116
There's no great solution for having libraries that support being gracefully shut down,

03:00:18.256 --> 03:00:18.497
sadly.

03:00:19.638 --> 03:00:23.577
Unless you just write your own type that wraps this that you tell people to write in,

03:00:23.878 --> 03:00:26.437
and then they need to figure out how to bridge between them.

03:00:27.304 --> 03:00:27.837
It's unfortunate.

03:00:33.773 --> 03:00:35.198
Because token is not mutable,

03:00:35.298 --> 03:00:40.589
can I use it as a static to avoid needing to pass it to every function that's going to depend on it?

03:00:44.442 --> 03:00:44.843
You know,

03:00:45.024 --> 03:00:47.153
that is an interesting question.

03:00:55.076 --> 03:00:56.360
I think you can,

03:00:56.580 --> 03:00:57.022
actually,

03:00:57.182 --> 03:00:58.887
because I think it is,

03:00:58.968 --> 03:00:59.108
yeah,

03:00:59.108 --> 03:01:00.613
it's both send and sync.

03:01:04.011 --> 03:01:04.333
So yeah,

03:01:04.373 --> 03:01:04.655
I mean,

03:01:04.876 --> 03:01:06.365
I think in principle you could.

03:01:06.365 --> 03:01:06.827
You could have a,

03:01:07.169 --> 03:01:07.289
you,

03:01:07.792 --> 03:01:09.881
it couldn't actually be a normal static because the,

03:01:09.921 --> 03:01:11.905
unless the constructor is const.

03:01:12.549 --> 03:01:12.670
Yeah,

03:01:12.670 --> 03:01:14.019
the constructor is not const.

03:01:14.885 --> 03:01:16.651
And so you would need to use something like a,

03:01:17.474 --> 03:01:19.341
a once lock in a static.

03:01:20.465 --> 03:01:21.309
But if you did,

03:01:21.430 --> 03:01:22.455
then yeah,

03:01:22.515 --> 03:01:23.641
you could use a static for this.

03:01:24.545 --> 03:01:26.720
It might get really annoying for things like tests,

03:01:27.143 --> 03:01:27.324
right?

03:01:27.525 --> 03:01:29.540
Because all of your tests will use the same static.

03:01:29.926 --> 03:01:31.916
So if you go cancel in any test,

03:01:32.077 --> 03:01:32.941
all of the tests will exit.

03:01:33.203 --> 03:01:36.200
And this is the perpetual problem with statics,

03:01:36.260 --> 03:01:36.401
right?

03:01:36.441 --> 03:01:37.601
Is that they truly are global.

03:01:38.543 --> 03:01:39.590
But if you don't have tests,

03:01:39.952 --> 03:01:41.381
then you could probably do this.

03:01:41.682 --> 03:01:42.980
I don't know that I would recommend it.

03:01:49.596 --> 03:01:51.769
Will async drop replace cancellation tokens?

03:01:52.472 --> 03:01:52.593
No,

03:01:52.856 --> 03:01:54.349
even if we had async drop,

03:01:54.975 --> 03:01:55.709
that would be convenient,

03:01:55.869 --> 03:02:02.549
but it wouldn't replace cancellation tokens because async drop is just to allow you to do asynchronous operations when you are dropped.

03:02:03.069 --> 03:02:08.809
But cancellation tokens are the way that you learn that you should exit and should start to drop yourself.

03:02:13.952 --> 03:02:14.517
Yeah,

03:02:14.699 --> 03:02:16.703
often the way you would do is you would do a

03:02:17.817 --> 03:02:19.001
cancellation in libraries,

03:02:19.001 --> 03:02:19.804
you would have like,

03:02:20.386 --> 03:02:22.533
give me something that implements future,

03:02:22.994 --> 03:02:25.123
and I will treat that as my cancellation.

03:02:25.445 --> 03:02:28.418
So you just take anything that implements future with the output type as unit,

03:02:28.779 --> 03:02:32.615
and someone could pass in a cancellation token or whatever their own means are.

03:02:33.378 --> 03:02:34.301
It doesn't really matter,

03:02:34.662 --> 03:02:34.843
right?

03:02:35.124 --> 03:02:38.758
So they could just take call canceled and just pass this type in,

03:02:39.120 --> 03:02:41.051
because as long as you're generic over what you take,

03:02:41.091 --> 03:02:41.393
you're okay.

03:02:44.057 --> 03:02:45.062
If you pants to cancel token,

03:02:45.103 --> 03:02:47.153
every function does not behave just like go context.

03:02:47.494 --> 03:02:47.616
Yeah,

03:02:47.616 --> 03:02:48.352
in some ways it does.

03:02:52.554 --> 03:02:52.916
Um,

03:02:54.304 --> 03:02:55.653
all right.

03:02:57.516 --> 03:02:58.018
Uh,

03:02:58.098 --> 03:03:01.792
there's also the type called task tracker that can be useful to know about in Tokyo util.

03:03:02.374 --> 03:03:02.535
Um,

03:03:02.696 --> 03:03:05.793
it's sort of a combination with cancellation token.

03:03:06.497 --> 03:03:06.618
Uh,

03:03:06.598 --> 03:03:08.113
you can use it to get graceful shutdown.

03:03:08.594 --> 03:03:10.502
I'm not actually going to talk about this in detail,

03:03:10.542 --> 03:03:11.928
but there's a decent,

03:03:12.290 --> 03:03:12.672
uh,

03:03:13.637 --> 03:03:17.851
blog post on this on the Tokyo blog on Graceful Shutdown that I recommend you read.

03:03:17.851 --> 03:03:25.440
It talks a lot about exactly this and how to wire it all together correctly and how you can use Task Tracker to make your life a little bit simpler.

03:03:29.232 --> 03:03:29.533
All right.

03:03:31.496 --> 03:03:32.369
We're on the home stretch.

03:03:33.070 --> 03:03:35.069
I think those are all the utilities I wanted to talk about.

03:03:36.310 --> 03:03:36.631
Now,

03:03:37.172 --> 03:03:45.069
the only thing that remains is a couple of like foot guns that are particularly common that people run into all the time.

03:03:46.032 --> 03:03:48.789
And I'll go through these pretty rapidly because they're not huge topics.

03:03:48.889 --> 03:03:54.087
They're just things that you just need to be aware of so that you don't shoot yourself in the foot with them.

03:03:59.326 --> 03:03:59.446
Um,

03:03:59.446 --> 03:03:59.627
okay,

03:03:59.627 --> 03:04:00.249
so number one.

03:04:02.723 --> 03:04:03.284
Tokyo spawn.

03:04:04.987 --> 03:04:06.489
When you spawn something,

03:04:12.258 --> 03:04:14.061
and I think I mentioned this earlier briefly,

03:04:14.141 --> 03:04:15.225
but I want to reiterate it.

03:04:15.546 --> 03:04:17.612
The join handle that you get back,

03:04:19.097 --> 03:04:20.221
when you drop it,

03:04:20.802 --> 03:04:22.689
you're not waiting for that task.

03:04:23.292 --> 03:04:25.601
That task continues to run in the background.

03:04:27.390 --> 03:04:29.521
And there are two implications of this.

03:04:29.862 --> 03:04:33.531
The first one is when you drop the join handle,

03:04:33.932 --> 03:04:37.341
you're not guaranteed that that task is finished doing the work.

03:04:38.002 --> 03:04:38.404
But also,

03:04:38.725 --> 03:04:40.111
it continues to run.

03:04:40.512 --> 03:04:42.601
It continues to use resources.

03:04:43.301 --> 03:04:44.925
And so because it spawned,

03:04:44.965 --> 03:04:46.168
because it's running in the background,

03:04:46.509 --> 03:04:51.421
just dropping it is not sufficient if you want your system to not be wasting resources over time.

03:04:51.945 --> 03:04:54.161
So if you truly want it to stop.

03:04:54.488 --> 03:05:00.385
then you need to do something like call abort so that Tokyo knows that the next time that future yields,

03:05:00.726 --> 03:05:01.793
it shouldn't resume it,

03:05:01.773 --> 03:05:03.565
it should drop it and it should cancel it instead.

03:05:04.608 --> 03:05:06.705
So that's the first aspect of this that's important.

03:05:07.086 --> 03:05:12.585
The second aspect of this is when you return from an asynchronous function that happened to run Tokyo spawn,

03:05:13.166 --> 03:05:16.505
you now have this thing that's running in the background that might be doing something important.

03:05:17.284 --> 03:05:18.969
But from the outside,

03:05:18.969 --> 03:05:20.412
from the caller's perspective,

03:05:20.693 --> 03:05:24.143
of the function that internally did a Tokyo spawn,

03:05:24.826 --> 03:05:27.679
the caller doesn't know that there's now this background thing.

03:05:28.261 --> 03:05:28.866
Which means crucially,

03:05:28.866 --> 03:05:30.561
it doesn't know that it might have to wait for it.

03:05:31.504 --> 03:05:33.509
So imagine that you have a background thread that's like,

03:05:33.650 --> 03:05:33.990
I don't know,

03:05:34.011 --> 03:05:35.775
you Tokyo spawned doing a,

03:05:36.076 --> 03:05:36.216
uh...

03:05:37.428 --> 03:05:38.591
a file copy.

03:05:39.333 --> 03:05:39.513
Well,

03:05:39.974 --> 03:05:47.078
if your asynchronous main function calls a thing that calls a thing that calls a thing that ultimately spawns this thing that copies the files,

03:05:47.520 --> 03:05:49.388
but nothing awaits the join handle,

03:05:49.991 --> 03:05:53.125
then what's going to happen is the thing that spawned the file copy returns,

03:05:53.527 --> 03:05:54.129
and then we return,

03:05:54.189 --> 03:05:54.450
return,

03:05:54.511 --> 03:05:54.772
return,

03:05:54.832 --> 03:05:56.057
return all the way back to main.

03:05:56.518 --> 03:05:59.851
Main also doesn't know about this background spawn that's going on,

03:06:00.193 --> 03:06:01.638
so main finishes.

03:06:02.120 --> 03:06:02.742
And at that point,

03:06:02.943 --> 03:06:06.225
all outstanding tasks are dropped because main exited.

03:06:06.559 --> 03:06:07.223
And at that point,

03:06:07.464 --> 03:06:09.013
your file copy stops in the middle.

03:06:09.913 --> 03:06:11.868
And so it's really important to remember...

03:06:12.815 --> 03:06:15.629
whether you want to do something whenever you do a spawn.

03:06:16.210 --> 03:06:17.275
Think about the fact,

03:06:18.038 --> 03:06:20.369
or consider every time you do a spawn,

03:06:20.789 --> 03:06:23.869
assign it to a variable and decide what to do with that variable.

03:06:24.410 --> 03:06:26.179
If you truly want it to be dropped,

03:06:26.541 --> 03:06:27.546
then you can drop it,

03:06:27.546 --> 03:06:28.069
that's fine,

03:06:28.431 --> 03:06:32.089
but you should make a conscious decision about whether dropping is the correct choice,

03:06:32.489 --> 03:06:34.049
or whether it should actually be awaited,

03:06:34.349 --> 03:06:36.769
or whether it should actually be communicated further up,

03:06:36.990 --> 03:06:38.489
or whether it should actually be aborted.

03:06:38.917 --> 03:06:44.233
But make a conscious decision rather than just letting the default behavior come back to bite you later.

03:06:52.643 --> 03:06:52.824
Yeah,

03:06:53.086 --> 03:06:55.620
it's not as though a background task is necessarily useless,

03:06:55.700 --> 03:06:55.821
right?

03:06:55.841 --> 03:06:57.521
It could be you actually wanted to run in the background.

03:06:57.641 --> 03:06:58.741
You don't want it to be aborted.

03:06:59.025 --> 03:07:00.101
You don't want it to be awaited.

03:07:00.241 --> 03:07:00.562
Like it's a,

03:07:00.542 --> 03:07:01.485
I don't know,

03:07:01.526 --> 03:07:07.321
it's your logger or it's forwarding something from a channel or reading something from a channel.

03:07:07.662 --> 03:07:11.798
So it could be the correct decision is to sort of forget the handle,

03:07:11.798 --> 03:07:14.021
like drop the handle and just let the background task running.

03:07:14.382 --> 03:07:17.521
It's more that it should be a conscious choice what you want to happen.

03:07:18.463 --> 03:07:21.021
I think the default behavior is actually reasonable as a default.

03:07:21.429 --> 03:07:21.980
It's more that.

03:07:22.368 --> 03:07:24.521
You should really think about whether that default applies to you.

03:07:27.203 --> 03:07:27.424
Okay,

03:07:28.348 --> 03:07:31.721
second thing to be aware of is that tasks are single-threaded.

03:07:32.382 --> 03:07:39.740
So when you do a Tokyo spawn or whatever you do in your asyncfn main is a single task,

03:07:40.241 --> 03:07:40.381
right?

03:07:40.624 --> 03:07:41.881
We've talked about what tasks are.

03:07:42.121 --> 03:07:43.025
It's a single task,

03:07:43.346 --> 03:07:47.441
which means that it's being executed by a single worker pool thread.

03:07:49.013 --> 03:07:52.242
If you do a bunch of work in different futures,

03:07:52.362 --> 03:07:54.649
but they're all in a single top-level task,

03:07:55.011 --> 03:07:59.029
that means all of that work is only being executed by a single thread.

03:07:59.911 --> 03:08:03.362
If you want work to be spread across multiple threads,

03:08:03.683 --> 03:08:10.229
then you need to spawn those futures so they become top-level tasks so that they can be executed in parallel.

03:08:11.129 --> 03:08:20.385
If you just use something like select or join or well not a join set because it spawns for you for exactly this reason but if you use a join or a select

03:08:21.552 --> 03:08:23.338
or a futures unordered for that matter,

03:08:24.302 --> 03:08:28.759
what you end up with is a bunch of futures that are executing concurrently but not in parallel.

03:08:29.180 --> 03:08:31.229
So they're all being executed by this one thread,

03:08:31.690 --> 03:08:35.804
but only one of the futures are being run at any given point in time.

03:08:36.265 --> 03:08:37.891
That may or may not be what you want.

03:08:37.972 --> 03:08:40.165
Sometimes you do actually want to multiplex them on one thread,

03:08:40.447 --> 03:08:45.426
but you should be aware of the fact that futures embedded in futures are always single-threaded.

03:08:45.847 --> 03:08:48.769
You need to spawn them and turn them into tasks in order to get parallelism.

03:08:53.280 --> 03:09:01.188
And then the final thing I want to talk about is a foot gun that I see pretty often in an over-reliance on MPSC channels.

03:09:01.973 --> 03:09:04.646
So we see this in particular with the actor model actually,

03:09:04.746 --> 03:09:06.977
where you spin up something that's an actor,

03:09:07.299 --> 03:09:07.902
it owns,

03:09:07.922 --> 03:09:08.224
let's say,

03:09:08.224 --> 03:09:09.269
a TCP connection.

03:09:09.973 --> 03:09:13.632
And what you do is you keep sending messages to the actor for things like,

03:09:13.652 --> 03:09:14.294
write these bytes,

03:09:14.314 --> 03:09:15.015
write these bytes,

03:09:15.035 --> 03:09:15.717
write these bytes,

03:09:15.777 --> 03:09:17.019
or handle this request,

03:09:17.079 --> 03:09:17.881
handle this request.

03:09:18.565 --> 03:09:22.338
The actor is again a single top-level task.

03:09:23.161 --> 03:09:23.705
As a result,

03:09:23.846 --> 03:09:25.015
it only has a single thread.

03:09:25.781 --> 03:09:26.403
And as a result,

03:09:27.005 --> 03:09:31.438
that single thread has to handle all of those requests one at a time.

03:09:32.481 --> 03:09:34.179
Now that's not inherently a problem,

03:09:34.219 --> 03:09:34.361
right?

03:09:34.421 --> 03:09:38.639
It might be that one at a time is the fastest you can write out on this TCP stream anyway.

03:09:39.081 --> 03:09:43.420
And if you had multiple tasks all trying to write out to the same TCP stream,

03:09:43.420 --> 03:09:44.601
they would need a mutex or something.

03:09:44.823 --> 03:09:46.072
So that's not inherently bad.

03:09:46.819 --> 03:09:53.809
The problem you run into is that when you have a sort of fan-in pattern into a single actor,

03:09:53.849 --> 03:09:56.252
a single task that needs to do something about them,

03:09:56.773 --> 03:09:59.917
it needs to pay a cost for every channel received.

03:10:01.178 --> 03:10:01.600
And again,

03:10:01.660 --> 03:10:03.529
if you think of these receives as being like,

03:10:03.529 --> 03:10:05.215
write these bytes or handle these requests,

03:10:05.576 --> 03:10:06.720
sometimes that's reasonable,

03:10:07.081 --> 03:10:12.276
but very often the loop on the actor is probably going to look something like,

03:10:12.396 --> 03:10:12.657
you know,

03:10:12.777 --> 03:10:13.780
while,

03:10:13.880 --> 03:10:14.081
uh,

03:10:14.662 --> 03:10:18.052
while let sum equals channel dot receive,

03:10:18.593 --> 03:10:18.815
and then,

03:10:18.836 --> 03:10:19.078
you know,

03:10:19.179 --> 03:10:20.573
do a bunch of work with that message.

03:10:21.715 --> 03:10:24.264
That means that by the time it comes around,

03:10:24.706 --> 03:10:26.171
depending on how much work there's in the loop,

03:10:26.472 --> 03:10:28.923
by the time it comes back around to read from the channel again,

03:10:29.225 --> 03:10:31.193
there might be five new things in that channel.

03:10:31.955 --> 03:10:34.303
But it needs to read them one at a time,

03:10:34.604 --> 03:10:39.942
even though there might be more efficient ways to handle those incoming requests in batch.

03:10:40.805 --> 03:10:42.531
How you choose to do that batching

03:10:43.369 --> 03:10:45.279
There are a bunch of different ways to do so.

03:10:46.083 --> 03:10:47.258
You could use things like a...

03:10:47.864 --> 03:10:48.005
Well,

03:10:48.065 --> 03:10:49.391
watch is not really appropriate here,

03:10:49.652 --> 03:10:50.556
but you could imagine,

03:10:50.577 --> 03:10:51.159
for example,

03:10:51.380 --> 03:10:54.329
that instead of having a channel to this actor,

03:10:54.690 --> 03:10:59.551
the input to this actor is actually a mutex over a vec rate.

03:11:00.159 --> 03:11:01.886
And so if you want to send something to the actor,

03:11:01.926 --> 03:11:03.834
what you do is you take the mutex,

03:11:04.195 --> 03:11:06.926
you extend the vector with the bytes you want it to write,

03:11:07.107 --> 03:11:08.192
and then you drop the mutex.

03:11:09.015 --> 03:11:12.287
And then the loop on the actor's side no longer looks like,

03:11:12.688 --> 03:11:12.869
get,

03:11:13.290 --> 03:11:13.531
you know,

03:11:13.812 --> 03:11:17.453
one small set of bytes and then go again and get a small set of bytes.

03:11:17.695 --> 03:11:19.060
Instead it takes the mutex,

03:11:19.341 --> 03:11:22.574
it takes the entire vector out and leaves an empty vector behind,

03:11:22.895 --> 03:11:25.051
and then it writes all of those bytes out at once.

03:11:25.635 --> 03:11:27.433
That might be way more efficient.

03:11:28.148 --> 03:11:37.939
and allow it to get to much higher bandwidth because it allows it to batch the cost across multiple calls into the actor.

03:11:39.176 --> 03:11:40.281
This pattern doesn't always work,

03:11:40.441 --> 03:11:41.967
it doesn't always fit what the actor needs to do,

03:11:42.509 --> 03:11:48.265
but in general there's a tendency I see to over-rely on MPSC channels,

03:11:48.325 --> 03:11:49.688
especially for actors,

03:11:50.169 --> 03:11:54.065
where it's often the right call for the simplicity of actors,

03:11:54.125 --> 03:11:55.511
especially at lower throughput,

03:11:55.772 --> 03:11:59.884
but when you get to systems that strain the resources more,

03:12:01.309 --> 03:12:07.783
you might want to start to think about these kinds of optimizations to amortize the cost of communication and synchronization here.

03:12:10.151 --> 03:12:10.653
I think,

03:12:10.914 --> 03:12:14.447
I think those are all the things I want to say about Tokyo.

03:12:15.449 --> 03:12:18.507
But I'll spend some time in chat and see if there are more things.

03:12:18.627 --> 03:12:18.788
Again,

03:12:19.331 --> 03:12:22.507
doesn't have to be about the sort of foot guns I just talked about,

03:12:22.607 --> 03:12:23.675
but across the whole stream,

03:12:23.696 --> 03:12:25.147
let's do a sort of quick,

03:12:25.307 --> 03:12:26.239
I don't want to say Q&amp;A,

03:12:26.401 --> 03:12:26.807
but a quick,

03:12:27.429 --> 03:12:28.727
everything I talked about at Tokyo,

03:12:28.887 --> 03:12:31.127
are there things that you still get confused by?

03:12:32.169 --> 03:12:38.307
You want more detail on things that have bit you in the past to sort of round off the stream here.

03:12:43.625 --> 03:12:44.771
It sounds a bit like a ring buffer.

03:12:44.872 --> 03:12:45.015
Yeah,

03:12:45.015 --> 03:12:46.071
it is kind of like a ring buffer.

03:12:46.332 --> 03:12:46.573
In fact,

03:12:46.593 --> 03:12:52.956
you can use a ring buffer for this if you're willing to copy out of it rather than steal.

03:13:01.021 --> 03:13:02.971
What things in Tokyo are actually parallel,

03:13:03.051 --> 03:13:03.815
not just concurrent?

03:13:04.395 --> 03:13:05.880
It's only Tokyo spawn,

03:13:08.048 --> 03:13:09.553
and of course runtime spawn,

03:13:09.593 --> 03:13:10.195
which is the same.

03:13:10.835 --> 03:13:12.226
Spawn blocking is parallel,

03:13:12.448 --> 03:13:13.415
because it runs on a different thread.

03:13:14.335 --> 03:13:15.900
Join set is parallel,

03:13:15.980 --> 03:13:20.373
because when you give a future to a join set,

03:13:20.433 --> 03:13:20.995
it spawns them.

03:13:21.538 --> 03:13:24.735
So basically the answer is only things that are spawned are parallel.

03:13:29.745 --> 03:13:32.239
And the IO event loop is parallel.

03:13:41.606 --> 03:13:42.348
When doing batching,

03:13:42.448 --> 03:13:46.077
usually you want to parameterize it with two inputs,

03:13:46.077 --> 03:13:48.523
the max batch size and the max wait time for a batch to fill.

03:13:49.785 --> 03:13:52.283
Is there something in the Tokyo ecosystem that implements such a pattern?

03:13:54.086 --> 03:13:55.362
Not that I know of.

03:13:55.984 --> 03:13:57.943
But we're talking like five lines of code.

03:13:58.243 --> 03:14:01.843
So I don't think so.

03:14:02.246 --> 03:14:02.563
But maybe.

03:14:09.896 --> 03:14:11.201
Request says it wants a Tokyo

03:14:11.763 --> 03:14:13.751
1.x runtime when running with another runtime.

03:14:13.831 --> 03:14:15.847
Is Tokyo doing something special that request needs?

03:14:16.596 --> 03:14:16.841
Well,

03:14:16.943 --> 03:14:17.780
so… Well,

03:14:17.780 --> 03:14:17.902
so…

03:14:22.354 --> 03:14:31.146
This gets at the fact that in order for Tokyo to know when futures need to move from the non-runnable queue to the runnable queue,

03:14:31.707 --> 03:14:35.031
it needs to know which things those futures are waiting for.

03:14:36.072 --> 03:14:38.920
Which means that when those futures use,

03:14:39.120 --> 03:14:39.541
for example,

03:14:39.541 --> 03:14:41.025
a Tokyo TCP stream,

03:14:42.188 --> 03:14:43.291
that's how Tokyo knows.

03:14:43.371 --> 03:14:45.343
It's because Tokyo implemented the TCP stream,

03:14:45.544 --> 03:14:46.631
so it knows what to wait for.

03:14:46.751 --> 03:14:49.771
So it knows when to move them and basically how to implement wake.

03:14:51.233 --> 03:14:54.161
If you try to use a non-Tokyo runtime,

03:14:54.502 --> 03:14:56.247
but you're trying to use the Tokyo resources,

03:14:56.868 --> 03:14:59.236
you run into a problem because the Tokyo resources,

03:14:59.899 --> 03:15:00.882
like a TCP stream,

03:15:01.765 --> 03:15:03.632
when you call poll on it and it realizes,

03:15:03.852 --> 03:15:04.013
like,

03:15:04.073 --> 03:15:06.361
let's say you call poll read on a TCP stream,

03:15:07.043 --> 03:15:08.067
it knows that,

03:15:08.208 --> 03:15:08.328
oh,

03:15:08.469 --> 03:15:09.533
I didn't have any bytes to read.

03:15:09.814 --> 03:15:13.427
I need to register myself somewhere so that the runtime...

03:15:14.684 --> 03:15:16.951
So that I can notify the runtime when I need to resume,

03:15:17.734 --> 03:15:20.511
basically I need to register myself with the I-O event loop.

03:15:21.399 --> 03:15:23.066
So it looks for an I-O event loop,

03:15:23.488 --> 03:15:25.215
specifically the Tokyo I-O event loop,

03:15:25.436 --> 03:15:27.075
and it doesn't find one.

03:15:27.279 --> 03:15:32.346
Then it doesn't know where to put its waker and its file descriptor for something to be picked up later.

03:15:33.619 --> 03:15:36.713
And so that's why when you use the Tokyo I-O resources,

03:15:37.014 --> 03:15:41.499
you need to also use the Tokyo runtime because the I-O resources are tied to the I-O event loop.

03:15:42.728 --> 03:15:43.250
If you use,

03:15:43.290 --> 03:15:43.631
let's say,

03:15:44.012 --> 03:15:45.677
the async stood runtime or something,

03:15:45.878 --> 03:15:47.583
but you're trying to use a Tokyo resource,

03:15:47.984 --> 03:15:50.129
then when a pull read happens,

03:15:50.349 --> 03:15:57.003
it doesn't have anywhere to put its state that it can rely on will call wake later.

03:15:59.090 --> 03:16:01.337
And so request,

03:16:01.377 --> 03:16:01.899
I believe,

03:16:01.999 --> 03:16:04.707
uses Tokyo resources all the way down.

03:16:04.787 --> 03:16:06.222
Like it uses Tokyo TCP streams,

03:16:06.222 --> 03:16:06.667
for example.

03:16:06.988 --> 03:16:13.487
And you can't run that in a non-Tokyo runtime because that connection with the IO event loop would be lost.

03:16:18.812 --> 03:16:20.347
Does Tokyo not do MPMC?

03:16:21.028 --> 03:16:21.149
No,

03:16:21.310 --> 03:16:23.042
Tokyo does not have a multi-producer,

03:16:23.082 --> 03:16:23.867
multi-consumer channel.

03:16:27.083 --> 03:16:28.145
If this hasn't been asked already,

03:16:28.286 --> 03:16:31.893
why does the async writeExt have implementations for each individual type,

03:16:31.974 --> 03:16:32.655
such as writeU8,

03:16:32.976 --> 03:16:34.599
instead of a generic time parameter?

03:16:35.981 --> 03:16:39.719
I think that one is because it's not clear what it would be generic over.

03:16:40.740 --> 03:16:45.174
Let's say you had a write number,

03:16:45.355 --> 03:16:46.438
and it's generic over t.

03:16:48.021 --> 03:16:49.037
Where t is what?

03:16:50.764 --> 03:16:55.519
What is the bound that allows it to take a number and turn it into a sequence of bytes?

03:16:56.720 --> 03:16:58.177
And it gets complicated,

03:16:58.218 --> 03:16:58.339
right?

03:16:58.479 --> 03:16:59.060
If you get a

03:16:59.742 --> 03:17:04.711
U128, the order in which you write the individual bytes of a

03:17:05.452 --> 03:17:08.938
U128 out to the writer depends on the endianness,

03:17:08.978 --> 03:17:09.459
for example.

03:17:10.639 --> 03:17:14.579
And so there's no generic bound to really express that.

03:17:15.079 --> 03:17:17.419
And so that's why you end up with individual methods.

03:17:25.551 --> 03:17:30.244
Can you talk about broadcast and the overhead that comes with having a bunch of receivers and senders?

03:17:32.299 --> 03:17:37.897
So there shouldn't be that much overhead when using broadcast with multiple receivers.

03:17:38.639 --> 03:17:40.748
I don't think broadcast allows multiple sender.

03:17:43.279 --> 03:17:46.370
Is it sender?

03:17:49.717 --> 03:17:49.958
Oh yeah,

03:17:50.058 --> 03:17:51.441
send takes a reference to self.

03:17:51.742 --> 03:17:51.943
Okay.

03:17:53.546 --> 03:17:54.930
So there's not,

03:17:54.970 --> 03:17:55.271
I think,

03:17:55.271 --> 03:17:57.697
a huge overhead to having multiple.

03:17:57.958 --> 03:18:01.912
The main problem you run into with broadcasts is if you have slow readers,

03:18:02.253 --> 03:18:04.422
they hold up all of the readers,

03:18:04.683 --> 03:18:05.065
or rather,

03:18:05.567 --> 03:18:06.189
it's not quite true.

03:18:06.210 --> 03:18:07.234
They don't hold up the readers,

03:18:07.274 --> 03:18:13.117
but they either hold up the sender or they cause rights to start to get dropped and they start losing messages.

03:18:14.181 --> 03:18:16.750
But that's just sort of an inherent problem here.

03:18:16.790 --> 03:18:18.335
This is the lagging problem that

03:18:27.639 --> 03:18:29.563
Does TokyoSpawn create an OS thread or a green thread?

03:18:29.603 --> 03:18:30.894
It creates a green thread.

03:18:32.063 --> 03:18:33.522
What about keeping a mutex guard between awaits?

03:18:33.603 --> 03:18:34.816
We already talked about that earlier.

03:18:35.463 --> 03:18:37.722
Is there a way to access the blocking thread pool of the runtime?

03:18:37.863 --> 03:18:40.737
Can I get a handle to it and send it somewhere else?

03:18:42.269 --> 03:18:42.677
Sort of.

03:18:42.983 --> 03:18:43.927
So if you look at runtime,

03:18:44.991 --> 03:18:47.400
there is a method called handle that gives you a handle.

03:18:48.123 --> 03:18:49.060
And on a handle,

03:18:49.922 --> 03:18:50.707
which is clone,

03:18:50.988 --> 03:18:52.195
there is a spawn blocking.

03:18:52.795 --> 03:19:01.395
And spawn blocking lets you run something on the pool and get an asynchronous future back.

03:19:02.600 --> 03:19:06.715
So you can pass a handle around and use that to spawn things onto the blocking pool.

03:19:07.639 --> 03:19:09.635
But that is your handle to the blocking pool.

03:19:13.561 --> 03:19:16.874
Can you talk about how you deal with handling what would normally require async drop,

03:19:16.915 --> 03:19:20.570
like losing third party async libraries you would like to clean up on drop,

03:19:20.731 --> 03:19:22.274
but those cleanups would be async?

03:19:23.038 --> 03:19:24.175
There's not a great answer to this.

03:19:24.355 --> 03:19:24.979
Async drop just,

03:19:25.342 --> 03:19:27.435
it sucks that we don't have it and it's really hard to get.

03:19:28.796 --> 03:19:31.282
You will see that for a bunch of types,

03:19:31.502 --> 03:19:32.965
not close is a bad example of this,

03:19:33.066 --> 03:19:38.392
but what is a good example of this?

03:19:46.478 --> 03:19:48.651
I guess actually maybe file.

03:19:57.737 --> 03:19:57.858
No,

03:19:58.140 --> 03:19:59.611
file is also a bad example here.

03:20:03.318 --> 03:20:04.527
I guess TCP stream,

03:20:04.830 --> 03:20:05.031
maybe.

03:20:08.238 --> 03:20:09.631
Or buff stream.

03:20:10.594 --> 03:20:12.571
Maybe buff stream is the one I want to talk about.

03:20:16.754 --> 03:20:18.205
Although maybe that doesn't solve the problem either.

03:20:19.146 --> 03:20:21.085
I guess maybe there is an example of this in Tokyo.

03:20:21.205 --> 03:20:22.284
So what I'm looking for is,

03:20:22.626 --> 03:20:29.084
you'll see a bunch of asynchronous libraries have an asynchronous function called close or something like it.

03:20:30.088 --> 03:20:34.264
And the idea is that if you know that you want to drop this type,

03:20:34.727 --> 03:20:38.765
then you should call this function in order to drop it.

03:20:38.946 --> 03:20:42.124
So close would be an asynchronous function that consumes self.

03:20:42.853 --> 03:20:46.286
And so the idea is that if you have the ability to manually drop it,

03:20:46.286 --> 03:20:47.893
like you know that you're going to drop this thing,

03:20:48.335 --> 03:20:50.124
rather than relying on the drop trait,

03:20:50.164 --> 03:20:51.249
like it just going out of scope,

03:20:51.591 --> 03:20:52.755
call this method instead,

03:20:52.996 --> 03:20:56.229
and then it will actually get to do its asynchronous cleanup.

03:20:57.768 --> 03:21:07.545
You also see this actually in synchronous methods where you might have a close function just because the close thing might error.

03:21:08.087 --> 03:21:10.694
And so if you just let the thing be dropped,

03:21:11.476 --> 03:21:13.944
the error from the result is just silenced,

03:21:13.944 --> 03:21:14.425
it's forgotten.

03:21:15.626 --> 03:21:23.545
So you are encouraged to call the close method if you can in order to recover that error or see that error and not have it just be silenced.

03:21:24.515 --> 03:21:24.836
And you can,

03:21:25.217 --> 03:21:26.723
the same thing applies for async,

03:21:26.723 --> 03:21:28.549
that you can provide an async function close.

03:21:28.951 --> 03:21:30.507
That doesn't perfectly solve the problem,

03:21:30.548 --> 03:21:30.669
right?

03:21:30.769 --> 03:21:36.900
Because there are cases where it's just going to be dropped and you don't really have control over logic that happens on drop,

03:21:36.980 --> 03:21:38.249
except through the drop trade.

03:21:39.270 --> 03:21:40.114
When that happens,

03:21:41.138 --> 03:21:44.049
the best thing that I know of here is

03:21:46.212 --> 03:21:52.469
So there's a handle current or try current that lets you get a handle to the current

03:21:53.138 --> 03:21:53.849
Tokyo runtime.

03:21:55.264 --> 03:21:55.669
And then.

03:21:57.009 --> 03:21:58.232
When you get that handle,

03:21:58.513 --> 03:22:03.445
you can then spawn code that would get to do your cleanup stuff.

03:22:04.329 --> 03:22:05.445
It's not beautiful.

03:22:06.407 --> 03:22:06.870
It means,

03:22:06.890 --> 03:22:07.413
for example,

03:22:07.413 --> 03:22:09.545
that if you get dropped off of the runtime,

03:22:10.207 --> 03:22:13.185
then now you don't get to execute anything to do that cleanup properly.

03:22:14.387 --> 03:22:17.085
But it is sort of a best effort asynchronous cleanup.

03:22:17.946 --> 03:22:18.408
Ultimately,

03:22:18.488 --> 03:22:18.770
though,

03:22:19.111 --> 03:22:22.005
this is a problem and we just don't have a great solution for it.

03:22:25.853 --> 03:22:26.176
Um...

03:22:36.435 --> 03:22:38.798
Tokyo Sync broadcast is not a multi-producer,

03:22:38.838 --> 03:22:39.339
multi-consumer.

03:22:39.459 --> 03:22:39.579
No.

03:22:40.140 --> 03:22:40.841
Broadcast,

03:22:41.222 --> 03:22:46.028
so broadcast is specifically not a multi-producer,

03:22:46.068 --> 03:22:47.911
multi-consumer queue.

03:22:48.291 --> 03:22:49.713
It is a broadcast queue.

03:22:50.134 --> 03:22:51.215
What that means is,

03:22:51.516 --> 03:22:52.658
and the distinction is,

03:22:52.938 --> 03:22:53.058
an

03:22:54.420 --> 03:23:02.473
MPMC channel is any sender can send a thing and one of the consumers will get that thing.

03:23:03.204 --> 03:23:06.414
A broadcast is any sender can send a thing,

03:23:07.176 --> 03:23:08.861
all consumers will get that thing.

03:23:09.428 --> 03:23:10.541
So the semantics are different.

03:23:13.844 --> 03:23:13.964
Uh,

03:23:15.107 --> 03:23:20.961
does the can-do the cancel safe futures or methods internally revert state?

03:23:21.263 --> 03:23:24.141
How do they know when to do that if they can become canceled in the middle?

03:23:24.741 --> 03:23:24.863
Um,

03:23:25.047 --> 03:23:25.881
it depends actually.

03:23:26.261 --> 03:23:30.381
So some of them are just written in such a way that they are cancellation safe.

03:23:30.441 --> 03:23:32.041
So they don't actually have to revert anything.

03:23:32.381 --> 03:23:36.088
They're just written in such a way that there's no a wait point between the-

03:23:37.347 --> 03:23:38.392
the sort of commit point,

03:23:38.433 --> 03:23:41.791
like the point where they change externally visible state and when they return.

03:23:42.093 --> 03:23:44.325
And so therefore they're just naturally cancellation safe.

03:23:44.626 --> 03:23:47.816
And some of them will actually have a sort of drop guard.

03:23:48.096 --> 03:23:54.217
So they'll construct a type internally that they create an instance of before they do some stuff.

03:23:54.559 --> 03:23:56.325
And so if the whole thing gets dropped,

03:23:56.566 --> 03:24:00.782
the drop implementation of that instance will do some revert stuff.

03:24:01.104 --> 03:24:02.615
That is a much more complicated pattern,

03:24:02.635 --> 03:24:03.825
but we do see it sometimes.

03:24:07.766 --> 03:24:10.841
Do you think Tokyo will remain the most common asynchronous runtime in the future?

03:24:13.423 --> 03:24:15.029
At least for the foreseeable future,

03:24:15.089 --> 03:24:22.050
I don't see any particularly relevant general purpose runtimes at least.

03:24:22.170 --> 03:24:26.581
There are runtimes that are better suited for sort of specific domains,

03:24:26.681 --> 03:24:27.082
for example,

03:24:27.102 --> 03:24:27.664
like embedded,

03:24:28.848 --> 03:24:34.941
but I don't know of any that are sort of compelling as a general purpose executor at the moment.

03:24:38.077 --> 03:24:40.526
Does the send method on channels call wake?

03:24:42.503 --> 03:24:42.909
Yes.

03:24:43.491 --> 03:24:49.547
That is exactly the way in which they allow the receiver to realize that,

03:24:49.687 --> 03:24:49.808
oh,

03:24:49.868 --> 03:24:52.289
this future has now moved from non-runnable to runnable.

03:25:08.706 --> 03:25:12.778
Why doesn't Tokyo implement Unix sockets of the type SOCKSECPACKET?

03:25:13.763 --> 03:25:14.335
I don't know.

03:25:14.661 --> 03:25:15.396
I don't know what that-

03:25:16.187 --> 03:25:17.732
variant of Unix sockets are.

03:25:18.174 --> 03:25:26.055
There are a bunch of like utility crates around Tokyo that provide like alternate socket types,

03:25:26.075 --> 03:25:26.616
for example.

03:25:27.458 --> 03:25:29.383
I think also there is,

03:25:30.144 --> 03:25:31.610
so this is a thing called asyncfd,

03:25:32.293 --> 03:25:39.258
which is basically a wrapper type specifically on Linux on anything that has a file descriptor that implements the standard

03:25:40.101 --> 03:25:41.467
Unix sort of read and write interface.

03:25:42.190 --> 03:25:43.617
So you might be able to use that,

03:25:43.757 --> 03:25:43.918
but...

03:25:45.534 --> 03:25:52.231
Tokyo is never going to support like every single possible resource directly in the library.

03:25:52.695 --> 03:25:54.411
That would just not be feasible.

03:25:54.832 --> 03:26:03.791
But the idea is that you should be able to write additional resources as other crates that people can use and they will interoperate nicely through things like the Waker.

03:26:13.235 --> 03:26:19.111
Would changing an asynchronous function that is pubbed from cancellation safe to non-cancellation safe be considered a breaking change for SemVer?

03:26:19.651 --> 03:26:20.871
That's a very good question.

03:26:23.335 --> 03:26:24.691
There's no well-defined answer to this.

03:26:24.892 --> 03:26:26.471
I would claim that the answer is yes.

03:26:26.953 --> 03:26:29.991
Because you have changed the correctness contract of the function.

03:26:31.630 --> 03:26:31.831
Right?

03:26:31.891 --> 03:26:32.071
Like,

03:26:32.432 --> 03:26:34.197
someone has been using your code correctly,

03:26:35.200 --> 03:26:40.176
and now you have made their code incorrect by changing your code,

03:26:40.557 --> 03:26:46.020
and they were relying on something that was at least assuming the cancellation safety was publicly documented before,

03:26:46.322 --> 03:26:47.427
then it would be a breaking change.

03:26:48.008 --> 03:26:50.340
If you never promised anything about cancellation safety,

03:26:50.662 --> 03:26:50.963
then no,

03:26:51.003 --> 03:26:52.169
I don't think it's a breaking change.

03:26:52.430 --> 03:26:54.217
So this becomes a question of documentation,

03:26:54.297 --> 03:26:54.518
really.

03:26:54.940 --> 03:26:57.612
Did you ever promise that it was cancellation safe?

03:26:57.975 --> 03:26:58.539
In general,

03:26:59.022 --> 03:26:59.667
when you call...

03:27:00.380 --> 03:27:01.785
third party libraries for things,

03:27:02.106 --> 03:27:04.275
you should be pessimistic about what they promise you.

03:27:04.496 --> 03:27:05.925
So if they don't guarantee a thing,

03:27:06.247 --> 03:27:07.655
you're not allowed to assume that thing.

03:27:08.095 --> 03:27:08.980
Or if you assume it,

03:27:08.960 --> 03:27:11.655
you should also specifically check it because it's allowed to change.

03:27:21.643 --> 03:27:23.639
Any plans on decrusting the small ecosystem?

03:27:23.719 --> 03:27:23.841
No.

03:27:25.339 --> 03:27:26.626
I don't think it's particularly relevant.

03:27:29.300 --> 03:27:31.256
Toki is not really good for real-time applications.

03:27:31.619 --> 03:27:31.861
I mean,

03:27:32.605 --> 03:27:36.829
that's generally true for anything that doesn't use a real-time operating system.

03:27:38.661 --> 03:27:41.859
But this sort of gets at what I was implying with embedded,

03:27:41.939 --> 03:27:42.061
right,

03:27:42.061 --> 03:27:46.433
is that there are runtimes that are better for specific kinds of use cases.

03:27:47.459 --> 03:27:50.957
So I was more referring to a general-purpose asynchronous runtime.

03:27:55.448 --> 03:27:58.989
Are there any workarounds for synchronous to asynchronous to synchronous to asynchronous call stacks?

03:27:59.315 --> 03:27:59.517
I mean,

03:27:59.517 --> 03:28:00.792
the answer is basically don't do it.

03:28:01.035 --> 03:28:02.349
It will come back to bite you.

03:28:05.442 --> 03:28:09.793
The slightly more helpful answer is channels are usually the way that you do this,

03:28:09.853 --> 03:28:11.528
whether one shot or MPSC.

03:28:12.015 --> 03:28:15.014
They are the best means we have for really bridging that gap.

03:28:16.649 --> 03:28:21.096
Things like block in place are crutches where if you use them a lot,

03:28:21.417 --> 03:28:22.899
or similar like handle current,

03:28:23.099 --> 03:28:23.921
if you use them a lot,

03:28:25.083 --> 03:28:27.847
you're going to run into really sad times as a result.

03:28:28.768 --> 03:28:33.261
Because those nested patterns end up just performing really poorly,

03:28:33.642 --> 03:28:35.587
having really hard to debug runtime failures.

03:28:36.271 --> 03:28:39.207
You don't generally want those sync async sandwiches.

03:28:45.501 --> 03:28:45.742
Okay,

