03:29:24.843 --> 03:29:28.063
What are good strategies for migrating from sync to async?

03:29:28.103 --> 03:29:32.348
I find that trying to write certain modules using a runtime and throwing handles around is difficult.

03:29:34.343 --> 03:29:40.560
There's not a general purpose solution here for rewriting things from sync to async.

03:29:41.623 --> 03:29:46.001
I think I've usually found that you kind of want to go outside in rather than inside out.

03:29:46.463 --> 03:29:47.086
Like trying to write,

03:29:47.447 --> 03:29:52.955
wrap asynchronous things with synchronous things tends to be a bunch of pain because...

03:29:54.595 --> 03:29:59.091
You now end up spawning multiple runtimes in each place where there's an interface.

03:29:59.472 --> 03:30:00.655
If you start from the top,

03:30:00.936 --> 03:30:02.580
you can have one asynchronous runtime,

03:30:02.920 --> 03:30:05.667
and initially you're going to have things that block the runtime,

03:30:05.667 --> 03:30:07.351
and you can use block in place or spawn blocking.

03:30:07.911 --> 03:30:11.423
And so that direction of the port tends to be easier,

03:30:11.764 --> 03:30:13.831
and then you just push async more and more down.

03:30:14.252 --> 03:30:15.671
So that tends to work better.

03:30:21.783 --> 03:30:28.364
The problem with real-time async is I don't think Rust has the right abstraction since real-time requires to some extent detail how to make a CPU...

03:30:31.733 --> 03:30:33.332
How much CPU a process is going to consume.

03:30:33.574 --> 03:30:33.694
Yeah,

03:30:33.694 --> 03:30:38.773
it's unclear whether in real-time operating systems this is the right interface.

03:30:38.893 --> 03:30:39.515
It might be,

03:30:40.697 --> 03:30:41.800
but it's much less clear.

03:30:47.353 --> 03:30:48.345
The domain is without boots.

03:30:51.331 --> 03:30:51.992
Without dot boats.

